const CHAPTER_FULL_TEXT = {
  "1": "Chapter 1: The Power of Thinking on Paper\n\n第⼀章：纸上思考的⼒量 (Zhǐ shàng s kǎo de lìliàng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To change how you see writing and to get you set up with\npowerful tools that will help you all year.\n\n改变你对写作的看法，并为你配备今年将会⽤到的强⼤⼯具。\n\nLesson 1.1: Why We Write\n\n第⼀课：我们为何写作 (Wǒmen wèihé xiězuò)\n\n\fPart 1: Writing as Architecture\n写作即建筑 (Xiězuò jí jiànzhú)\n\nThink about the most amazing building you've ever seen. What makes it amazing? Its design, its strength, its beauty? Now\nimagine how it was built. The architects didn't just start stacking bricks randomly. They started with a plan.\nWriting is exactly the same.\n\nThe best writing isn't just a pile of ideas. It is a strong, well-designed structure built to hold up your ideas and present them\npowerfully to the world.\nYour Goal This Year 今年的⽬标 (J nnián de mùbi o):\nTo become the architect of your ideas. This class will teach you the blueprints.\n\n成为你想法的建筑师。本课程将教你如何绘制蓝图。\n\nPart 2: Your Master Blueprint\n你的核⼼蓝图 (Nǐ de héx n lántú)\n\nEvery architect needs a blueprint. Every writer needs a process. This is yours for the entire course. Follow it whenever you\nfeel lost.\nThe Master Flowchart 核⼼流程图 (Héx n liúchéngtú)(This page features a clean, easy-to-read version of the Master\nFlowchart visual)\nRemember 记住 (Jìzhù): This is your map. You can't get lost if you know where you are on the map.\n这是你的地图。如果你知道在地图上的位置，就不会迷路。\n\n\fPart 3: Activity - Human vs. AI Brainstorming\n\n活动：⼈脑与⼈⼯智能头脑⻛暴 (Rénnǎo yǔ réng ng zhìnéng tóunǎo f ngbào)\n\nAI tools like DeepSeek and Perplexity are like super-powered brainstorming partners. They can help you overcome the fear\nof the blank page. Quilbot will help you craft your writing into beautiful structures. Notion will help you collect and organise\nall the ideas.\n⼈⼯智能⼯具（如DeepSeek和Perplexity）就像超级头脑⻛暴伙伴。它们可以帮助你克服对空⽩⻚的恐惧。\n\nTask - Brainstorm\nEasy Prompt Question\n\nTopic 主题 (Zhǔtí): Should schools have uniforms? 学校应该穿校服吗？\n\nManual Brainstorm ⼈⼯头脑⻛暴 (Réng ng tóunǎo f ngbào): Your teacher will ask for ideas. Watch how the list grows\nslowly.\n\nAI Brainstorm AI头脑⻛暴 (AI tóunǎo f ngbào): Your teacher will ask an AI the same question. Watch how fast the ideas\n\nappear.\n\nIt's not about copying 这不是抄袭 (Zhè bùshì ch oxí). It's about getting raw materials. A sculptor needs clay. A writer\nneeds ideas. AI gives you the clay. You are the sculptor 你是雕塑家 (Nǐ shì di osùji ). Your job is to shape those ideas into\nsomething that is truly yours.\n\nKey Takeaway 关键要点 (Gu njiàn yàodiǎn): AI is a tool for generating possibilities 可能性 (kěnéngxìng), not for finding\nanswers 答案 (dá'àn).\n\nPart 4: Activity - Think-Pair-Share\n\n活动：思考-配对-分享 (S kǎo - pèiduì - f nxiǎng)\n\nIt's okay to be nervous about academic writing. Everyone is at first. Let's get those fears out in the open.\n\n对学术写作感到紧张是可以的。每个⼈⼀开始都这样。让我们把这些恐惧公开出来。\n\n\fPrompt 提⽰ (Tíshì): What is your biggest problem or fear with academic writing?\n你对学术写作最⼤的问题或恐惧是什么？\n\nStep 1 THINK 思考 (S kǎo) 2 min)\nJot down your thoughts in the space below.\n\n在下⾯空⽩处记下你的想法。\n\n[Your Thoughts 你的想法:]\n________________________________________________________________\n________________________________________________________________\n________________________________________________________________\n\nStep 2 PAIR 配对 (Pèiduì) 3 min)\n\nDiscuss your fears with a partner. Do you share any of the same fears?\n与伙伴讨论你的恐惧。你们有相同的恐惧吗？\n[Notes from Discussion 讨论笔记:]\n________________________________________________________________\n________________________________________________________________\n________________________________________________________________\n\nStep 3 SHARE 分享 (F nxiǎng) 10 min)\n\nListen as your teacher writes everyone's fears on the board. You are not alone. This course is designed to solve every\nsingle one of these problems.\n听⽼师把每个⼈的恐惧写在⿊板上。你并不孤单。本课程旨在解决所有这些问题。\n\nHomework\nTask - Set up all your accounts and start to learn 1) Quillbot, 2) Notion 3) Create your school page\nIn NOTION - create a school page.\nAdd a title\nAdd - /database and insert a page for all your subjects\ne.g.\nSubjects\nName\nEnglish\nChemistry\nMaths\nBiology\n\n\fLesson 1.2: Tooling Up & Your Starting Point\n第⼆课：装备⼯具与了解起点 (Zhu ngbèi g ngjù yǔ liǎojiě qǐdiǎn)\n\nPart 1: In-Class Diagnostic Writing\n课堂诊断写作 (Kètáng zhěnduàn xiězuò)\n\nImportant 重要 (Zhòngyào): This is not a test 不是测验 (bùshì cèyàn). This is not for a grade. This is simply to help\nunderstand your starting point so I can be a better teacher for you this year. Please do your best, but do not stress.\n\n这只是为了帮助⽼师了解你的起点，以便今年能更好地教你。请尽⼒⽽为，但不要有压⼒。\n\nTask 任务 (Rènwù):\n\nIn the next 20 minutes, please write a short essay in response to the prompt below.\n\n在接下来的40分钟内，请就下⾯的提⽰写⼀篇短⽂。\n\nPrompt 提⽰ (Tíshì): What is one rule at our school that you would change? Brainstorm ideas, choose one.\nArgue for your position. Give at least one reason to support your argument.\n\n你想改变学校的哪⼀条规则？论证你的⽴场。⾄少给出⼀个理由来⽀持你的论点。\n\nThings to include 尝试包括以下内容 (Chángshì b okuò y xià nèiróng):\nǐ\n\nA clear sentence that states your opinion 陈述你观点的清晰句⼦。\nAt least one reason for your opinion ⾄少⼀个⽀持你观点的理由。\n\nAn example if you can think of one 如果能想到的话，举⼀个例⼦。\nA conclusion that restates your main idea 重述你主要观点的结论。\n\nWrite your essay below 在下⾯写下你的⽂章:\nExample:\n\nFirst rough idea (Spelling and grammar mistakes are ok)\nOne rule I would change is the rule for school uniforms. I thinks that students should be allow to wear there own clothes to\nschool.\nMy main reason is that clothes let us to express ourself. School is a place we are finding out who we are. Uniforms make\neveryone look the same and it feel like we cannot be creative. It supress our identity.\nFor example, a student who is artistic might want to wore a shirt with a interesting design. But with an uniform, this is not\npossible. It is not allowed.\nSo… we should not have uniforms. It would make school a more better place if we can wear what we want and express are\npersonalities.\n\n\fA.I. Idea\n\nOne rule I would change is the rule that we must wear school uniforms. I believe that students should be allowed to wear\ntheir own clothes to school.\nMy main reason is that personal clothing allows students to express their individuality. School is a place where we are\nfinding out who we are, and our fashion choices are a big part of that. When everyone is forced to wear the same uniform, it\nfeels like the school is telling us to all be the same person, and this can suppress our creativity and personal identity.\nFor example, an artistic student might wear a unique hat or a shirt with a cool design to show their creativity. An athletic\nstudent might wear their favourite team's jersey to show their passion. But with a strict uniform, these small but important\nforms of self-expression are not allowed.\nIn conclusion, getting rid of the uniform rule would make the school a more positive place because it would let students\nexpress their unique personalities and feel more comfortable being themselves.\n\nPart 2: Your Digital Toolbelt 你的数字⼯具带 (N de shùzì g ngjù dài)\nǐ\n\nYour task is to get familiar with the tools we'll use all year.\n\n你的任务是熟悉我们全年将使⽤的⼯具。\n\nTask 1:\n\nExplore the Tools 探索⼯具 (Tànsuǒ g ngjù)\nQuillbot:\nFind a sentence you wrote in your diagnostic today.\n找到你今天在诊断写作中写的⼀个句⼦。\n\nPaste it into Quillbot's Grammar Checker 语法检查器 (Yǔfǎ jiǎnchá qì). What does it suggest?\n把它粘贴到Quillbot的语法检查器中。它有什么建议？\n\nNow paste it into the Paraphraser paraphrasing tool 改写⼯具 (Gǎixiě g ngjù). How does it change the sentence?\nDoes it keep the same meaning?\n\n现在把它粘贴到改写⼯具中。它是如何改变句⼦的？它是否保持原意？\n\nRemember 记住 (Jìzhù): The paraphraser is for learning new vocabulary and sentence structures. Never 绝不 (Jué\nbù) copy and paste directly from it into your essay.\n改写⼯具⽤于学习新词汇和句⼦结构。切勿直接复制粘贴到你的⽂章中。\n\nPerplexity/DeepSeek:\n\nThink of a hobby or topic you love (e.g., basketball, K-pop, climate change, video games).\n\n想⼀个你喜欢的爱好或主题（例如：篮球、K-pop、⽓候变化、电⼦游戏）。\n\nType a question about it into the search bar. For example: \"What are the most effective strategies for defending in\nbasketball?\" or \"What is the history of K-pop?\"",
  "10": "Chapter 10: The Analytical Essay\n第⼗章：分析类⽂章 (F nx lèi wénzh ng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond summarising what a text says and learn to\n\nanalyze how it says it and why it matters.\n\n超越总结⽂本说了什么，学习分析它如何说以及为什么重要。\n\nLesson 10.1: Summary vs. Analysis\n第⼀课：总结与分析 (Zǒngjié yǔ f nx )\n\nPart 1: The Fundamental Difference\n\n根本区别 (G nběn q bié)\n\nSummary 总结 (Zǒngjié): Telling what happened. It describes the main points or events. It answers the question: \"What\nis this text about?\"\n讲述发⽣了什么。它描述要点或事件。它回答的问题是：“这篇⽂本是关于什么的？”\n\nAnalysis 分析 (F nx ): Explaining how and why it happened. It interprets the meaning, importance, and effects of those\npoints. It answers the question: \"How does this text work and why does it matter?\"\n\n解释它是如何以及为什么发⽣的。它阐释这些要点的含义、重要性和效果。它回答的问题是：“这篇⽂本是如何起作⽤的，为什么\n它重要？”\n\nExample: A Movie Review 例⼦：⼀篇影评\nSummary: \"In The Matrix, Neo takes a pill, learns he's in a simulation, and joins a rebellion against the machines.\"\n“在《⿊客帝国》中，尼奥吃了⼀颗药丸，得知⾃⼰⾝处⼀个模拟世界，并加⼊了⼀场对抗机器的叛乱。\n”\n\nAnalysis: \"The Wachowskis use the red pill/blue pill choice not just as a plot device, but as a powerful metaphor for the\n\npainful yet liberating process of awakening to harsh truths. The visual contrast of the bleak real world versus the\ncomfortable simulation argues that true freedom requires accepting a difficult reality over a comfortable lie.\"\n\n“沃卓斯基姐妹使⽤红药丸/蓝药丸的选择不仅仅作为⼀个情节设置，⽽是作为⼀个强有⼒的隐喻，象征着觉醒到残酷真理的痛苦\n但解放的过程。 bleak 真实世界与舒适模拟世界的视觉对⽐论证了真正的⾃由需要接受困难的现实，⽽不是舒适的谎⾔。”\n\nPart 2: The Analytical Thesis\n\n\f分析类论⽂陈述 (F nx lèi lùnwén chénshù)\n\nAn analytical thesis makes a claim about the deeper meaning or mechanics of a text.\n\n分析类论⽂陈述对⽂本的更深层含义或机制提出主张。\n\nFormula 公式:\nIn Text , Author uses [literary element/strategy] to suggest [argument about theme/meaning].\n\n在[⽂本]中，[作者]使⽤[⽂学元素/策略]来表明[关于主题/含义的论点]。\n\nExample 例⼦:\n\"In The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald uses the contrasting symbolism of the East Egg and West Egg to critique the\nrigid and ultimately corrupt nature of the American upper class in the 1920s.\"\n\n“在《了不起的盖茨⽐》中，菲茨杰拉德通过东卵和⻄卵的对⽐象征，批判了1920年代美国上流社会僵化且最终腐败的本质。”\n\nLesson 10.2: What to Analyze?\n\n第⼆课：分析什么？(F nx shénme?)\n\nYou cannot analyse everything. You must focus on specific elements the author uses to create meaning.\n你⽆法分析所有东⻄。你必须专注于作者⽤来创造意义的特定元素。\n\nPart 1: The Author's Toolkit\n\n作者的⼯具箱 (Zuòzhě de g ngjù xi ng)\n\nElement 元素 (Yuánsù)\n\nWord Choice Diction) 措辞\nCuòcí)\n\n(\n\nSentence Structure Syntax\n\n句⼦结构 (Jùzi jiégòu)\n\nImagery 意象 (Yìxiàng)\n\nFigurative Language ⽐喻语⾔\nBǐyù yǔyán)\n\n(\n\nTone 语⽓ (Yǔqì)\n\nWhat It Is 是什么\n\nThe specific words an author chooses.\nHow sentences are built (short, long,\nsimple, complex).\nLanguage that appeals to the senses\n(sight, sound, touch, taste, smell).\nSimile, metaphor, personification,\nsymbolism.\nThe author's attitude toward the subject\n(e.g., sarcastic, serious, humorous).\n\nAnalytical Question 分析性问题\nWhy did the author choose this word instead of a synonym?\nWhat tone (angry, sad, joyful) do the words create?\nHow does the sentence structure affect the pace or feeling\nof the text? Does it create urgency, calm, or confusion?\nWhat image does the author create? How does this image\nmake us feel or what does it represent?\nWhat is being compared? What does this comparison help\nus understand? What does a symbol represent?\nWhat words or details reveal the author's tone? How does\nthis tone influence the reader's perception?\n\nPart 2: The Analytical Ladder\n\n分析阶梯 (F nx ji t )\n\nAnalysis is a process of climbing from the concrete to the abstract.\n\n分析是⼀个从具体攀登到抽象的过程。\n\n\fHow to climb the ladder 如何攀登阶梯:\nDescribe What? \"The author uses a metaphor.\"\n描述（什么？）: “作者使⽤了⼀个隐喻。”\n\nAnalyze How? \"She compares life to a 'broken-winged bird that cannot fly.'\"\n\n分析（如何？）: “她将⽣活⽐作⼀只‘折翼⽆法⻜翔的⻦ʼ。”\n\nInterpret So What? \"This metaphor suggests that without dreams, life is crippled, lonely, and loses its purpose and\nability to move forward.\"\n\n阐释（那⼜怎样？）: “这个隐喻表明，没有梦想，⽣活是残缺的、孤独的，并失去了其⽬标和前进的能⼒。”\n\nLesson 10.3: Building an Analytical Paragraph\n\n第三课：构建分析段落 (Gòujiàn f nx duànluò)\n\nPart 1: The PEEL Method, Revisited\n重温PEEL法 (Chóngw n PEEL fǎ)\n\nThe PEEL structure is perfect for analysis. Remember:\nPEEL结构⾮常适合分析。记住：\n\nP Point Your topic sentence that makes a claim about an author's choice.\n你的主题句，对作者的选择提出主张。\n\nE Evidence): A specific quote or example from the text that shows that choice.\n\n来⾃⽂本的具体引⽤或例⼦，显⽰该选择。\n\nE Explanation): Your ANALYSIS. This is where you explain how the evidence proves your point. What does the\nword/image/symbol do? How does it work?\n\n\f你的分析。在这⾥你解释证据如何证明你的观点。这个词/意象/象征有什么作⽤？它是如何起作⽤的？\n\nL Link Connect your analysis back to the essay's main thesis.\n\n将你的分析重新连接到⽂章的主要论⽂陈述上。\n\nPart 2: Practice: Analyse an Image\n\n练习：分析⼀个意象 (Liànxí: F nx y gè yìxiàng)\n\nRead this excerpt from F. Scott Fitzgerald's The Great Gatsby:阅读菲茨杰拉德《了不起的盖茨⽐》中的这段节选：\n\"…I became aware of the old island here that flowered once for Dutch sailors' eyes—a fresh, green breast of the new\nworld.… for a transitory enchanted moment man must have held his breath in the presence of this continent… face to\nface for the last time in history with something commensurate to his capacity for wonder.\"\n\nAnalyse the imagery 分析意象:\nP Point Fitzgerald uses organic, fertile imagery to describe the American continent.\n“菲茨杰拉德使⽤有机的、肥沃的意象来描述美洲⼤陆。”\n\nE Evidence): He calls it a \"fresh, green breast of the new world\" that \"flowered\" for the sailors.\n“他称其为‘新世界清新、绿⾊的胸膛ʼ，为⽔⼿们‘盛开ʼ。”\n\nE Explanation - The Analysis! The words \"fresh,\" \"green,\" \"breast,\" and \"flowered\" create a powerful image of\nnature, life, and nurturing promise. This portrays America not as a built city, but as a pure, natural, and almost motherly\nland of infinite potential and sustenance, which makes its eventual corruption in the modern age (a central theme of the\nbook) seem even more tragic.\n“新鲜”、“绿⾊”、“胸膛”和“盛开”这些词创造了⼀个关于⾃然、⽣命和养育承诺的强⼤意象。这描绘的美国不是⼀个建成的城\n市，⽽是⼀⽚纯净的、⾃然的、⼏乎是⺟亲般的、拥有⽆限潜⼒和 sustenance 的⼟地，这使得它最终在现代的堕落（本书的⼀\n个核⼼主题）显得更加悲剧。\n\nL Link This idealised vision of the past underscores the novel's critique of the corrupted American Dream of the\n1920s.\n“这种对过去的理想化 vision 强调了⼩说对1920年代腐朽的美国梦的批判。”\n\nHomework: The Analyst's Lab\n\n作业：分析师的实验室 (F nx sh de shíyàn shì)\n\nTask 1 Summary vs. Analysis\n\nFind a short article or a key passage from a book. Write a 2-sentence summary of it. Then, write a 2-sentence analysis of\none of the author's choices (e.g., word choice, tone, imagery).\n找⼀篇短⽂或书中的⼀个关键段落。写⼀个两句话的总结。然后，对作者的⼀个选择（例如：措辞、语⽓、意象）写⼀个两句话的分\n析。\n\nSummary 总结: ____________________________________________________\nAnalysis 分析: ____________________________________________________\n\nTask 2 Climb the Ladder\n\nChoose a short poem, a famous speech excerpt, or a song lyric. Complete the analytical ladder for a specific line.\n选择⼀⾸短诗、⼀段著名演讲摘录或⼀⾸歌词。为⼀个特定的句⼦完成分析阶梯。\n\nQuotation 引⽤: ____________________________________________________\nDescribe What? _________________________________________________\nAnalyze How? ___________________________________________________\nInterpret So What? ______________________________________________\n\n\fTask 3 Draft an Analytical PEEL Paragraph\nUsing your work from Task 2, write a full PEEL Paragraph analyzing the author's choice.\n使⽤你在任务2中的⼯作，写⼀个完整的PEEL段落来分析作者的选择。\n\nP Point 论点: ______________________________________________________\n(E) Evidence 证据: ____________________________________________________\n(E) Explanation 解释 (Your Analysis): ___________________________________\nL Link 连接: _______________________________________________________\n\nHomework: The Analyst's Lab - Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points and will contribute to your overall\nCoursework average Weight: 25% of your final grade).\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement 0 4\npts)\n\nTask 1\nSummary vs.\nAnalysis\n\nSummary is concise and\naccurate. Analysis is insightful,\nclearly moving beyond\nsummary to examine a specific\nauthorial choice and its\neffect/purpose.\n\nSummary is accurate.\nAnalysis identifies an\nauthorial choice but the\nexplanation of its effect is\nsomewhat vague or\nunderdeveloped.\n\nThe line between\nsummary and analysis is\nblurred. The \"analysis\"\nmay just be a rewording\nof the summary or a\nsimple observation.\n\nSummary is inaccurate or\nanalysis is missing,\nirrelevant, or\ndemonstrates a\nmisunderstanding of the\ntask.\n\nTask 2 Climb\nthe Ladder\n\nThe analytical ladder is fully\nand thoughtfully completed.\nEach step is distinct and builds\nlogically to a nuanced\ninterpretation. The \"So What?\"\nis particularly insightful.\n\nThe ladder is completed\ncorrectly. The steps are\nclear, but the interpretation\ncould be more developed or\ninsightful.\n\nThe ladder is incomplete\nor the steps are confused\n(e.g., analysis is just\ndescription). The\ninterpretation is obvious\nor superficial.\n\nThe ladder is largely\nblank, or the responses\ndo not demonstrate a\ncoherent analytical\nprocess.\n\nTask 3 Draft a\nPEEL Paragraph\n\nThe PEEL paragraph is\nflawlessly structured. The Point\nis specific and arguable, the\nEvidence is well-chosen, the\nExplanation offers deep\nanalysis connecting to the \"So\nWhat?\", and the Link is\neffective.\n\nThe PEEL structure is\ncorrectly used. All\ncomponents are present, but\nthe Explanation could delve\ndeeper into the \"So What?\"\nor the Link could be\nstronger.\n\nThe PEEL structure is\nattempted but\ncomponents are weak or\nmisplaced (e.g., Point is\nfactual, Explanation just\nrestates the evidence).\n\nThe paragraph does not\nfollow the PEEL\nstructure, is summarybased, or is incomplete.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\nTask 1: Summary vs. Analysis\nSource: Excerpt from Martin Luther King Jr.'s \"I Have a Dream\" speech.\nSummary 总结:\nThe speaker describes his dream for a future America where people are judged by their character and not their skin\ncolor. He envisions a place of brotherhood where former slaves and slave owners can coexist peacefully.\n\nAnalysis 分析:\nKing repeatedly uses the powerful, concrete metaphor of a \"dream\" to transform an abstract political goal into a\nvisceral and universal human aspiration. This choice makes the vision of racial equality feel both deeply personal and",
  "11": "Chapter 11: The Problem-Solution Essay\n\n第⼗⼀章：问题解决型⽂章 (Wèntí jiějué xíng wénzh ng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond identifying problems and learn to propose,\nevaluate, and convincingly argue for viable, well-reasoned solutions.\n\n超越识别问题，学习提出、评估并有说服⼒地论证可⾏、合理的解决⽅案。\n\nLesson 11.1: Beyond Complaining - The Anatomy of a Solution\n\n第⼀课：超越抱怨——解决⽅案的剖析 (Ch oyuè bàoyuàn——Jiějué f ng'àn de p ux )\n\nPart 1: Defining a True Problem\n\n\f定义⼀个真正的问题 (Dìngyì y gè zh nzhèng de wèntí)\n\nA problem 问题 (wèntí) for an essay is not just a bad situation. It is a specific issue with consequences 后果 (hòuguǒ) that\nhas potential for change 改变的潜⼒ (gǎibiàn de qiánlì).\n\nVague \"Problem\": \"Social media is bad.\"\n\n模糊的“问题”: “社交媒体不好。”\n\nWell-Defined Problem: \"The constant, algorithmically-driven comparison to curated lives on social media is linked to\nrising anxiety and decreased self-esteem among adolescents, creating a public health concern.\"\n定义清晰的问题: “在社交媒体上持续地、由算法驱动地与经过修饰的⽣活进⾏⽐较，与⻘少年⽇益增⻓的焦虑和下降的⾃尊有\n关，这造成了⼀个公共健康问题。”\n\nA good problem statement makes your reader care and understand why a solution is necessary.\n\n⼀个好的问题陈述能让你的读者关⼼并理解为什么需要解决⽅案。\n\nPart 2: Qualities of a Strong Solution\n\n优秀解决⽅案的特质 (Y uxiù jiějué f ng'àn de tèzhì)\n\nA solution 解决⽅案 (jiějué f ng'àn) is not just an idea. It is a concrete proposal that is:\n解决⽅案不只是⼀个想法。它是⼀个具体的提议，具有以下特点：\n\nFeasible 可⾏的 (Kěxíng de): It is practical and possible to implement. Who will do it? What will it cost? Is it legal?\n它是实⽤且可以实施的。（谁来做？成本是多少？合法吗？）\n\nEffective 有效的 (Yǒuxiào de): It directly addresses the root cause of the problem and will likely make a significant\nimpact.\n它直接解决问题的根本原因，并可能产⽣重⼤影响。\n\nDefensible 可辩护的 (Kě biànhù de): Its benefits outweigh its potential drawbacks. You can argue for it against other\noptions.\n它的好处⼤于潜在的缺点。你可以为其辩护，反对其他选项。\n\nLesson 11.2: Structuring the Argument\n第⼆课：构建论证 (Gòujiàn lùnzhèng)\n\nThe problem-solution essay follows a powerful and logical structure.\n问题解决型⽂章遵循⼀个强⼤且符合逻辑的结构。\n\n\fPart 1: Making the Case - The Problem Section\n\n提出理由——问题部分 (Tích\n\nlǐyóu——Wèntí bùfèn)\n\nThis section must convince the reader the problem is serious and worth solving. Use your research to provide evidence of:\n这⼀部分必须说服读者问题很严重，值得解决。⽤你的研究提供证据证明：\n\nScope 范围 (Fànwéi): How widespread is the problem? Statistics, data)\n问题有多普遍？（统计数据）\n\nSeverity 严重性 (Yánzhòng xìng): How bad is it? What are the negative consequences? Case studies, examples)\n它有多严重？有什么负⾯后果？（案例研究，例⼦）\n\nCauses 原因 (Yuány n): What is the root cause? Expert analysis, reports)\n根本原因是什么？（专家分析，报告）\n\nPart 2: Proposing the Fix - The Solution Section\n提出解决⽅案——解决⽅案部分 (Tích\n\njiějué f ng'àn——Jiějué f ng'àn bùfèn)\n\nThis is where you become a problem-solver. You must explain:\n这是你成为问题解决者的地⽅。你必须解释：\n\nThe Plan 计划 (Jìhuà): What, specifically, should be done? Be concrete.\n具体应该做什么？要具体。\n\nFeasibility 可⾏性 (Kěxíng xìng): Why can this be done? Discuss cost, time, logistics, and existing examples.\n为什么这可以做得到？讨论成本、时间、物流和现有例⼦。\n\nEffectiveness 有效性 (Yǒuxiào xìng): Why should this be done? How will it directly solve the problem you outlined?\n\nPredict the positive outcomes.\n\n为什么应该这样做？它将如何直接解决你概述的问题？预测积极的结果。\n\nPart 3: Anticipating Objections - The Counterargument\n预测反对意⻅——反论部分 (Yùcè fǎnduì yìjiàn——Fǎnlùn bùfèn)\n\n\fA strong solution acknowledges its own potential weaknesses. A dedicated paragraph strengthens your credibility.\n\n⼀个强⼤的解决⽅案会承认⾃⼰潜在的弱点。⼀个专门写反论的段落会增强你的可信度。\n\nThey Say... \"Some may argue that this solution is too expensive to implement.\"\n\n他们说... “有些⼈可能认为这个解决⽅案实施起来太昂贵了。”\n\nI Say... \"However, a study by the Economic Policy Institute shows that the long-term healthcare and productivity\nsavings would far outweigh the initial investment. Furthermore, the cost of inaction is far greater.\"\n\n我说... “然⽽，经济政策研究所的⼀项研究表明，⻓期的医疗保健和⽣产效率节省将远远超过初始投资。此外，不采取⾏动的代\n价要⼤得多。”\n\nLesson 11.3: Language for Change\n\n第三课：推动改变的语⾔ (Tu dòng gǎibiàn de yǔyán)\n\nUse powerful and persuasive language to frame your argument.\n\n使⽤有⼒和有说服⼒的语⾔来构建你的论证。\n\nEmphasizing the Problem 强调问题:\n\nThe critical issue of X demands immediate attention...\"\nX这个关键问题需要⽴即关注...”\n\n\"\n“\n\nUnless addressed, this problem will lead to...\"\n\n\"\n\n“除⾮得到解决，否则这个问题将导致...”\n\nThe data reveals a troubling trend...\"\n\n\"\n\n“数据揭⽰了⼀个令⼈不安的趋势...”\n\nProposing the Solution 提出解决⽅案:\n\nA viable and effective solution would be to...\"\n\n\"\n\n“⼀个可⾏且有效的解决⽅案是...”\n\nTo mitigate this issue, we must...\"\n\n\"\n\n“为了缓解这个问题，我们必须...”\n\nImplementing [solution] would address the root cause by...\"\n\n\"\n\n“实施[解决⽅案]将通过...解决根本原因”\n\nArguing for Feasibility/Effectiveness 论证可⾏性/有效性:\n\nThis approach is not only practical but also cost-effective...\"\n\n\"\n\n“这种⽅法不仅实⽤，⽽且具有成本效益...”\n\nPilot programs in Location] have demonstrated success in...\"\n\n\"\n\n“在[地点]的试点项⽬已在...⽅⾯取得了成功”\n\nThe primary benefit of this solution is its ability to...\"\n\n\"\n\n“这个解决⽅案的主要好处是它能够...”\n\nCall to Action ⾏动号召:\n\nIt is imperative that [government/schools/companies] take action by...\"\n\n\"\n\n“[政府/学校/公司]必须采取⾏动...”\n\nWe must urge our representatives to prioritize this issue.\"\n\n\"\n\n“我们必须敦促我们的代表优先处理这个问题。\n”\n\nBy working together, we can solve this problem and create a better...\"\n\n\"\n\n“通过共同努⼒，我们可以解决这个问题，并创造⼀个更美好的...”\n\nHomework: The Solution Architect\n\n作业：解决⽅案架构师 (Jiějué f ng'àn jiàgòu sh )",
  "12": "Chapter 12: The Reflective Essay\n第⼗⼆章：反思性⽂章 (Fǎns xìng wénzh ng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To look inward and analyze your own learning process,\n\nexperiences, and personal growth. The goal is not to report what you did, but to discover and articulate what you learned\nand how you changed.\n\n向内看，分析你⾃⼰的学习过程、经历和个⼈成⻓。⽬标不是报告你做了什么，⽽是发现并阐明你学到了什么以及你是如何改变的。\n\nLesson 12.1: What is Reflection?\n\n第⼀课：什么是反思？(Shénme shì fǎns ?)\n\nPart 1: Experience vs. Insight\n\n经历与洞⻅ (J nglì yǔ dòngjiàn)\n\nReporting 报告 (Bàogào): Listing what you did. This is summary.\n列出你做了什么。这是总结。\n\n\fExample: \"I wrote three essays this semester. I learned about thesis statements and fallacies.\"\n例⼦: “我这学期写了三篇⽂章。我学习了论⽂陈述和逻辑谬误。”\n\nReflecting 反思 (Fǎns ): Analyzing what you learned from what you did and how it changed you. This is insight.\n分析你从所做的事情中学到了什么，以及它如何改变了你。这是洞⻅。\n\nExample: \"The process of crafting a thesis statement taught me that my initial opinion is often just a starting point.\nBy researching and confronting counterarguments, my ideas became more complex and nuanced. I learned to value\ndoubt as a tool for finding stronger truths.\"\n例⼦: “构建论⽂陈述的过程教会我，最初的观点往往只是⼀个起点。通过研究和⾯对反论点，我的想法变得更加复杂和微\n妙。我学会了将怀疑视为寻找更强⼤真理的⼯具。”\n\nReflection transforms experience into meaningful learning.\n反思将经历转化为有意义的学习。\n\nPart 2: The \"What? So What? Now What?\" Model\n\n“是什么？那⼜怎样？现在怎样？”模型 (“Shì shénme? Nà yòu zěnyàng? Xiànzài zěnyàng?” móxíng)\n\nThis is a simple but powerful framework to structure your thinking.\n这是⼀个简单⽽强⼤的框架来构建你的思维。\n\nWhat? 是什么？ Describe the experience objectively. What happened? What did you do, see, read, or hear?\n客观地描述经历。发⽣了什么？你做了什么、看了什么、读了什么或听了什么？\n\nSo What? 那⼜怎样？ Analyze the experience. Why did it matter? What did you learn? How did it challenge your\nassumptions? How did it make you feel? This is the most important part.\n\n分析经历。它为什么重要？你学到了什么？它如何挑战了你的假设？它让你感觉如何？这是最重要的部分。\n\nNow What? 现在怎样？ Look to the future. How will you apply this learning? How has it changed your future thinking or\n\nactions?\n\n展望未来。你将如何应⽤这个学习？它如何改变了你未来的思维或⾏动？\n\nLesson 12.2: The Language of Self-Analysis\n第⼆课：⾃我分析的语⾔ (Zìwǒ f nx de yǔyán)\n\nReflective writing uses a specific vocabulary to explore inner thoughts and feelings.\n反思性写作使⽤特定的词汇来探索内⼼的想法和感受。\n\nPart 1: Verbs of Thinking and Feeling\n\n思考和感受的动词 (S kǎo hé gǎnshòu de dòngcí)\n\nVerb 动词\n\nrealised 意识到\n\nfelt 感觉\n\nwondered\n\n想知道\n\nExample 例⼦\n\n\"I realised that my first draft is just a way to figure out what I think.\"\n\"I felt frustrated at first, but then I understood the value of the feedback.\"\n\"I wondered if my argument was too simplistic.\"\n\nrecognised 认识到 \"I recognised a pattern in my logical errors.\"\nquestioned 质疑\n\nlearned 学会\n\nappreciated 欣赏\n\n\"I questioned my own initial bias on the topic.\"\n\n\"I learned that strong writing requires even stronger thinking.\"\n\"I now appreciate how structure sets my ideas free.\"\n\nPart 2: Sentence Starters for Depth\n\n⽤于深度的句⼦开头 (Yòngyú sh ndù de jùzi k itóu)\n\nUse these to move beyond simple description and into analysis.\n\n\f使⽤这些来超越简单的描述，进⼊分析。\n\nThe most significant thing I learned was... 我学到的最重要的事情是...\nThis was challenging because... 这很有挑战性，因为...\nI overcame this by... 我通过...克服了这⼀点\n\nThis changed my understanding of... 这改变了我对...的理解\nI now see that... 我现在明⽩了...\n\nI surprised myself by... 我让⾃⼰感到惊讶的是...\n\nThis will change how I approach... in the future. 这将改变我未来处理...的⽅式\n\nLesson 12.3: Structuring Reflection\n\n第三课：构建反思的结构 (Gòujiàn fǎns de jiégòu)\n\nA reflective essay is less rigid than an argumentative essay, but it still needs a clear structure to guide the reader.\n\n反思性⽂章不像议论⽂那么严格，但它仍然需要⼀个清晰的结构来引导读者。\n\nPart 1: The Reflective Thesis\n\n反思性论⽂陈述 (Fǎns xìng lùnwén chénshù)\n\nYour thesis is the central insight you discovered. It is the answer to your \"So What?\" question.\n你的论⽂陈述是你发现的核⼼洞⻅。它是你的“那⼜怎样？”问题的答案。\n\nWeak 薄弱: \"This semester I learned about writing essays.\"\n“这学期我学习了写⽂章。”\n\nStrong 强⼤: \"Through the iterative process of drafting and revision, I learned that true clarity of thought emerges not\nfrom getting it right the first time, but from having the courage to engage with my own confusion.\"\n“通过起草和修改的迭代过程，我了解到，思想的真正清晰并⾮来⾃第⼀次就做对，⽽是来⾃有勇⽓⾯对⾃⼰的困惑。”\n\nPart 2: Narrative Flow\n\n叙事流 (Xùshì liú)\n\nYour essay can follow a narrative timeline, but each part of the story must include analysis.\n你的⽂章可以遵循⼀个叙事时间线，但故事的每个部分都必须包含分析。\n\nIntroduction 引⾔: Set the context. What is the experience you will be reflecting on? End with your reflective thesis.\n\n设定背景。你要反思的经历是什么？以你的反思性论⽂陈述结束。\n\nBody Paragraphs 主体段落: Don't just tell the story chronologically. Organize your paragraphs by key insights or themes.\n\n不要只是按时间顺序讲故事。按关键的洞⻅或主题来组织你的段落。\n\nParagraph 1 Insight about your initial struggles and what they taught you.段落1： 关于你最初挣扎的洞⻅以及它们教会了你\n\n什么。\n\nParagraph 2 Insight about a moment of change or understanding.段落2： 关于改变或理解时刻的洞⻅。\n\nParagraph 3 Insight about feedback, collaboration, or seeing things differently.段落3： 关于反馈、合作或以不同⽅式看问\n题的洞⻅。\n\nConclusion 结论: Look forward. Answer the \"Now What?\" question. How has this learning changed you? How will you carry\nit into the future?\n\n向前看。回答“现在怎样？”的问题。这个学习如何改变了你？你将如何将其带⼊未来？\n\nHomework: The Reflective Practitioner\n\n作业：反思实践者 (Fǎns shíjiàn zhě)",
  "13": "Chapter 13: Advanced Research Techniques\n第⼗三章：⾼级研究技巧 (G ojí yánji\n\njìqiǎo)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond basic Google searches and learn the\nprofessional strategies that will empower you to find high-quality, academic sources efficiently and effectively.\n超越基本的⾕歌搜索，学习专业策略，使你能够⾼效、有效地找到⾼质量的学术资源。\n\nLesson 13.1: Mastering the Digital Library\n\n第⼀课：掌握数字图书馆 (Zhǎngwò shùzì túsh guǎn)\n\nPart 1: Why Academic Databases?\n\n为什么使⽤学术数据库？(Wèishéme shǐyòng xuéshù shùjùkù?)\n\nSearch engines like Google are great for everyday questions, but they are not curated. Academic databases are collections\nof scholarly, peer-reviewed 同⾏评审的 (tóngháng pǐnshěn de) work that has been evaluated by experts for quality and\naccuracy.\n\n\f像⾕歌这样的搜索引擎很适合⽇常问题，但它们不是精选的。学术数据库是学术性的、同⾏评审的作品的集合，这些作品已经由专家\n评估过质量和准确性。\n\nThink of it this way 可以这样想:\nGoogle: A giant, messy warehouse. You might find a priceless painting next to a stack of old newspapers.\n⼀个巨⼤、混乱的仓库。你可能会在⼀堆旧报纸旁边找到⼀幅⽆价的画。\n\nAcademic Database: A highly organized art museum or library. Everything there has been selected for its value and\nrelevance.\n\n⼀个组织⾼度有序的艺术博物馆或图书馆。那⾥的每⼀样东⻄都是根据其价值和相关性被挑选出来的。\n\nPart 2: Key Databases to Know\n\n需要了解的关键数据库 (X yào liǎojiě de gu njiàn shùjùkù)\n\nYou will access these through your school or local library website.\n你将通过你的学校或当地图书馆⽹站访问这些。\n\nDatabase 数据库\n\nWhat It's For ⽤途\n\nBest For 最适合\n\nA simple way to search across many scholarly\nsources. Good for starting out. 跨众多学术资源搜索的简\n\nFinding a few key sources on a topic. \"Citation\nchasing\" (see below). 找到⼀个主题的⼀些关键资\n\nJSTOR JSTOR\n\nA huge digital library of academic journals, books, and\nprimary sources. ⼀个巨⼤的学术期刊、书籍和主要来源\n\nHumanities, Social Sciences, History. Excellent for\nfoundational research. ⼈⽂、社会科学、历史。⾮常适\n\nProject MUSE Project\nMUSE\n\nSimilar to JSTOR, with a strong focus on humanities\nMore recent scholarship than JSTOR. High-quality\nand social sciences. 与JSTOR类似，⾮常注重⼈⽂和社会\njournals. ⽐JSTOR更新的学术成果。⾼质量的期刊。\n\nPubMed / MEDLINE\nPubMed / MEDLINE\n\nThe primary database for life sciences and biomedical\ntopics. ⽣命科学和⽣物医学主题的主要数据库。\n\nGoogle Scholar ⾕歌学术\n\n单⽅法。适合初学者。\n\n的数字图书馆。\n\n科学。\n\nIEEE Xplore IEEE Xplore The main database for engineering and computer\nscience. ⼯程和计算机科学的主要数据库。\n\n源。“引⽤追踪”（⻅下⽂）。\n\n合基础研究。\n\nMedicine, Biology, Biochemistry, Nursing. 医学、⽣物\n\n学、⽣物化学、护理学。\n\nElectrical Engineering, Computer Science, Electronics.\n电⽓⼯程、计算机科学、电⼦学。\n\nLesson 13.2: The Researcher's Toolkit\n第⼆课：研究者的⼯具包 (Yánji\n\nzhě de g ngjù b o)\n\nPart 1: Boolean Operators - Power Searching\n\n布尔运算符——⾼级搜索 (Bù'ěr yùnsuàn fú——G ojí s usuǒ)\n\nThese are simple words (AND, OR, NOT) that act as commands to make your database searches incredibly precise.\n这些简单的词（AND, OR, NOT）作为命令，使你的数据库搜索⾮常精确。\nflowchart TD\nA[Your Search Results]\nA --> B[\"Narrow Search 缩小搜索 Use AND 使用 AND\"]\nA --> C[\"Broaden Search 扩大搜索 Use OR 使用 OR\"]\nA --> D[\"Exclude Terms 排除术语 Use NOT 使用 NOT\"]\nB --> E[\"\"social media\" AND anxiety Finds sources that mention BOTH terms.\"]\nC --> F[\"\"university\" OR \\\\\"college\\\\\" Finds sources that mention EITHER term.\"]\nD --> G[\"\"apple\" NOT fruit Finds sources about the company, excluding the food.\"]\n\nPart 2: Other Search Tricks\n\n其他搜索技巧 (Qít\n\ns usuǒ jìqiǎo)\n\n\fQuotation Marks \" \" 引号: Search for an exact phrase.\n搜索⼀个确切的短语。\n\nExample: \"climate change\" will find those words together, not separately.\n例⼦：“⽓候变化” 将找到这些词在⼀起的结果，⽽不是分开的。\n\nAsterisk 星号: The truncation symbol. Finds different endings of a word.\n截断符号。查找⼀个词的不同结尾。\nExample: teenwill find teen, teens, teenage, teenager.\n例⼦：teen将找到 teen, teens, teenage, teenager。\n\nParentheses ( ) 括号: Group your search terms for complex searches.\n对复杂的搜索进⾏搜索词分组。\n\nExample: (\"social media\" OR Instagram) AND (anxiety OR depression)\n例⼦：(“社交媒体” OR Instagram) AND (焦虑 OR 抑郁)\n\nPart 3: Citation Chasing\n引⽤追踪 (Yǐnyòng zhu z ng)\n\nThis is one of the most powerful research techniques.\n\n这是最强⼤的研究技术之⼀。\n\nBackward Chasing 向后追踪: Look at the References or Works Cited list of a good source you found. Those are the\nsources the author used. Now you have a list of new, relevant sources to find.\n\n查看你找到的⼀个好资源的参考⽂献或引⽤作品列表。那些是作者使⽤的资源。现在你有了⼀个新的、相关的资源列表去找。\n\nForward Chasing 向前追踪: See who has cited the good source you found. This shows you newer research that has\nbuilt upon that original source. In Google Scholar, click \"Cited by\" under a search result.\n\n查看谁引⽤了你找到的好资源。这向你展⽰了基于该原始资源更新的研究。在⾕歌学术中，点击搜索结果下的“被引⽤次数”。\n\nLesson 13.3: From Search to Source Management\n\n第三课：从搜索到资源管理 (Cóng s usuǒ dào z yuán guǎnlǐ)\n\nPart 1: The Annotated Bibliography\n\n带注释的参考⽂献 (Dài zhùshì de c nkǎo wénxiàn)\n\nAn annotated bibliography 带注释的参考⽂献 is a list of your sources where each citation is followed by a short paragraph\n\n(the annotation) that describes and evaluates the source.\n\n带注释的参考⽂献是你的资源列表，其中每个引⽤后⾯都有⼀个简短的段落（注释），描述和评估该资源。\n\nWhy do it? 为什么这么做？\n\nIt forces you to read and understand each source critically.\n\n它迫使你批判性地阅读和理解每个资源。\n\nIt helps you see the conversation between your sources.\n\n它帮助你看到资源之间的对话。\n\nIt makes writing your literature review or essay much, much easier.\n\n它让你写⽂献综述或⽂章变得⾮常、⾮常容易。\n\nWhat to include in the annotation 注释中应包含什么:\nSummary 总结: What are the main arguments? What topics are covered?\n主要论点是什么？涵盖了哪些主题？\n\nEvaluation 评估: Is it a useful source? Is it reliable? How does it compare to other sources? Use RADAR!\n它是⼀个有⽤的资源吗？它可靠吗？与其他资源相⽐如何？（使⽤RADAR！）\n\n\fReflection 反思: How will you use this source in your essay? Does it support or contradict your thesis?\n你将在⽂章中如何使⽤这个资源？它⽀持还是反驳你的论⽂？\n\nPart 2: Citation Managers - Your Research Assistant\n\n引⽂管理器——你的研究助⼿ (Yǐnwén guǎnlǐ qì——Nǐ de yánjiù zhùshǒu)\n\nAs you collect more sources, it becomes hard to organize them. A citation manager 引⽂管理器 is software that does this\nfor you.\n当你收集更多资源时，组织它们变得困难。引⽂管理器是为你做这件事的软件。\n\nWhat it does 它的功能: It stores your sources, generates citations and bibliographies in any style APA, MLA, Chicago),\nand can insert citations directly into your paper.\n它存储你的资源，以任何格式（APA、MLA、Chicago）⽣成引⽂和参考⽂献，并可以直接将引⽂插⼊你的论⽂。\nPopular Tools 流⾏⼯具: Zotero (free and powerful), Mendeley (good for sciences), EndNote.\n\nRecommendation 推荐: Start with Zotero. It is free and excellent for university students.\n从 Zotero 开始。它是免费的，对⼤学⽣⾮常出⾊。\n\nHomework: The Research Apprentice\n\n作业：研究学徒 (Yánjiù xuétú)\n\nTask 1 Database Explorer\n\nGo to your school's library website. Find and explore one of the databases mentioned in this chapter JSTOR, Project\nMUSE, etc.).\n到你学校的图书馆⽹站。找到并探索本章提到的⼀个数据库（JSTOR、Project MUSE等）。\n\nDatabase Explored 探索的数据库: _______________________________________\nSearch Query Used 使⽤的搜索查询: _____________________________________\n\n(Use at least one Boolean operator or search trick!)\n\n（使⽤⾄少⼀个布尔运算符或搜索技巧！）\n\nMost Interesting Source Found 找到的最有趣的资源: _______________________\n\nTitle: _______________________________________________________\n\nTask 2 Citation Chase\n\nPick a source you've already found for a current or past project.\n选择⼀个你为当前或过去项⽬已经找到的资源。\n\nOriginal Source 原始资源: ______________________________________________\nBackward Chase 向后追踪: List one source from its bibliography you would like to find.\n从它的参考⽂献中列出⼀个你想找的资源。\n\nForward Chase 向前追踪: Use Google Scholar to find one source that has cited your original source.\n使⽤⾕歌学术找到⼀个引⽤了你原始资源的资源。\n\nTask 3 Start an Annotation\n\nCreate an entry for one source in the style of an annotated bibliography. Write 3 4 sentences.\n\n以带注释的参考⽂献的⻛格为⼀个资源创建⼀个条⽬。写3 4句话。\n\nCitation 引⽂: _______________________________________________________\nAnnotation 注释: _____________________________________________________",
  "14": "Chapter 14: Writing with Style\n第⼗四章：⽂体与⻛格 (Wéntǐ yǔ f nggé)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond \"correct\" writing to \"powerful\" writing. You will\n\nlearn to refine your sentences for clarity, concision, and impact, making your arguments more persuasive and professional.\n\n超越“正确”的写作，达到“有⼒”的写作。你将学习优化句⼦，使其清晰、简洁、有影响⼒，从⽽使你的论证更有说服⼒、更专业。\n\nLesson 14.1: The Principles of Powerful Prose\n第⼀课：有⼒散⽂的原则 (Yǒulì sǎnwén de yuánzé)\n\nPart 1: Clarity Over Cleverness\n\n清晰胜过巧妙 (Q ngx shèngguò qiǎomiào)\n\nYour first job is to be understood. Complex ideas demand simple language.\n你的⾸要任务是让⼈理解。复杂的思想需要简单的语⾔。\n\nUnclear 不清晰: \"The multi-faceted pedagogical methodologies employed therein ultimately obfuscate the fundamental\nkernel of the intended communicative transmission.\"\n\n“其中采⽤的多⽅⾯教学⽅法最终模糊了预期传播的基本核⼼。”\n\nClear 清晰: \"The teacher's complicated instructions confused the students.\"\n“⽼师复杂的指令让学⽣感到困惑。”\n\nAsk yourself 问⾃⼰: Could I say this more simply?\n我能说得更简单点吗？\n\nPart 2: Conciseness is Confidence\n简洁就是⾃信 (Jiǎnjié jiùshì zìxìn)\n\nWordy writing is often weak writing. It can sound like you are trying to fill space. Concise writing is strong and confident.\n冗⻓的写作往往是乏⼒的写作。它听起来像是你在试图填充空间。简洁的写作是有⼒且⾃信的。\n\nWordy 冗⻓: \"Due to the fact that the experiment was conducted in a manner that was not systematic, it is possible that\nthe results are not completely accurate.\"\n\n“由于实验是以⼀种不系统的⽅式进⾏的，结果可能不完全准确。”\n\nConcise 简洁: \"Because the experiment was unsystematic, the results may be inaccurate.\"\n“因为实验不系统，结果可能不准确。”\n\nHow to be concise 如何做到简洁:\n\nReplace long phrases with strong verbs. (e.g., \"is indicative of\"\n⽤强动词替换⻓短语。（例如，“is indicative of”\n“indicates”）\n\n\"indicates\")\n\nRemove redundant words. (e.g., \"basic fundamentals,\" \"end result\")\n删除冗余的词语。（例如，“basic fundamentals,” “end result”）\nAvoid \"there is/are\" and \"it is\" when you can start with the subject.\n当你可以⽤主语开头时，避免使⽤“there is/are”和“it is”。\n\nLesson 14.2: Surgical Editing - Word and Sentence Level\n\n第⼆课：精准编辑——词语和句⼦层⾯ (J ngzhǔn bi njí——Cíyǔ hé jùzi céngmiàn)\n\nPart 1: Choosing the Right Tool\n\n选择正确的⼯具 (Xuǎnzé zhèngquè de g ngjù)\n\n\fWeak & Vague 弱且模糊\n\nget,\" \"do,\" \"thing,\" \"stuff\" “得\n\n\"\n\n到”、“做”、“东⻄”、“事情”\n\n\"\n\nvery big,\" \"really good\" “⾮常\n\n\"\n\nShe was sad.\" “她很悲伤。”\n\n⼤”、“真的很好”\n\nStrong & Precise 强且精确\n\nWhy It's Better 为什么更好\n\n概念、材料\n\n的词语能创造更清晰的画⾯。\n\nacquire, perform, concept, material 获得、执⾏、\nenormous, immense; excellent, superb 巨⼤的、\n\n⽆边的；优秀的、极好的\n\n\"She was despondent.\" or \"Grief weighed on\nher.\" “她很沮丧。”或“悲伤压垮了她。”\n\nPart 2: Sentence Surgery 句⼦⼿术 (Jùzi shǒushù)\n\n1.\n\nThe precise word creates a clearer picture. 精确\n\nStrong adjectives don't need \"very.\" 强的形容词\n\n不需要“⾮常”。\n\nSpecific emotions or metaphors are more\npowerful. 具体的情感或隐喻更有⼒。\n\nEliminate \"Zombie Nouns\" 消除“僵⼫名词”\n\nZombie nouns are nouns made from verbs (e.g., utilization, implementation, conceptualization). They drain the life out of\nyour sentences.\n僵⼫名词是由动词变来的名词（例如：利⽤、实施、概念化）。它们吸⾛了你句⼦的⽣命⼒。\n\nBefore: \"The implementation of the plan by the committee...\"\n“委员会对计划的实施...”\n\nAfter: \"The committee implemented the plan...\"\n“委员会实施了计划...”\n\n2.\n\nActivate the Passive Voice When Appropriate) 激活被动语态（在适当的时候）Passive voice 被动语态 Emphasises the\n\naction, not the doer. Active voice 主动语态 is stronger and more direct.\n\n被动语态强调动作，⽽不是执⾏者。主动语态更强⼤、更直接。\n\nPassive Weak \"The treaty was signed by the leaders.\" Emphasis on treaty)\n被动（弱）： “条约被领导⼈们签署了。”（强调条约）\n\nActive Strong \"The leaders signed the treaty.\" Emphasis on leaders)\n主动（强）： “领导⼈们签署了条约。”（强调领导⼈们）\n\nUse passive voice only when the doer is unknown or unimportant.仅当执⾏者未知或不重要时才使⽤被动语态。\nGood Passive: \"The solution was heated to 100°C.\" Who heated it? The scientist. It's unimportant.)\n好的被动： “溶液被加热到100°C。”（谁加热的？科学家。这不重要。）\n\n3.\n\nVary Sentence Structure 变换句⼦结构\n\nA series of short, simple sentences sounds choppy. A series of long, complex sentences is hard to follow. Mix them.\n\n⼀连串短⼩的简单句听起来不连贯。⼀连串冗⻓的复杂句很难理解。混合使⽤。\n\nChoppy 不连贯: \"The data was conclusive. The hypothesis was correct. We celebrated. We published the results.\"\n“数据是决定性的。假设是正确的。我们庆祝了。我们发表了结果。”\n\nVaried & Better 多变且更好: \"Because the data was conclusive, we knew the hypothesis was correct. After celebrating,\nwe published the results.\"\n\n“因为数据是决定性的，我们知道假设是正确的。庆祝之后，我们发表了结果。”\n\nLesson 14.3: The Rhythm of Reading\n第三课：阅读的节奏 (Yuèdú de jiézòu)\n\nPart 1: Read It Aloud\n\n⼤声读出来 (Dàsh ng dú ch lái)\n\nThe best editing tool is your ear. If you stumble over a sentence while reading it aloud, your reader will stumble while\nreading it silently.\n最好的编辑⼯具是你的⽿朵。如果你⼤声读⼀个句⼦时结巴了，你的读者在默读时也会结巴。\n\nWhat to listen for 听什么:\nAwkward phrasing: Does it sound natural?\nawkward 的措辞： 听起来⾃然吗？\n\n\fLong sentences: Can you say it in one breath? If not, shorten it.\n⻓句： 你能⼀⼝⽓说完吗？如果不能，就缩短它。\n\nRepetition: Do you use the same word too many times?\n重复： 你是否过多地使⽤了同⼀个词？\n\nPart 2: The Peer Test\n\n同⾏测试 (Tóngháng cèshì)\n\nGive your essay to a friend. Ask them to highlight any sentence that:\n\n把你的⽂章给⼀个朋友。请他们标出任何：\n\nThey had to read twice to understand.\n\n他们必须读两遍才能理解的句⼦。\n\nThat felt clunky or awkward.\n\n感觉笨拙或 awkward 的句⼦。\n\nWhere they lost track of the argument.\n他们跟不上论证的句⼦。\n\nThis is invaluable feedback. If one person is confused, others will be too.\n\n这是宝贵的反馈。如果⼀个⼈感到困惑，其他⼈也会如此。\n\nHomework: The Style Editor\n作业：⽂体编辑 (Wéntǐ bi njí)\n\nTask 1 Sentence Makeover\n\nRewrite the following sentences to make them more concise, active, and clear.\n\n重写下⾯的句⼦，使它们更简洁、主动、清晰。\n\nOriginal: \"It is the opinion of this researcher that a utilisation of more efficient methodologies would be beneficial.\"\n改写: _________________________________________________________\n\nOriginal: \"There are many reasons why the argument that was made by the author is not a persuasive one.\"\n\n改写: _________________________________________________________\n\nOriginal: \"The phenomenon of climate change is one that is having a global impact that is negative on a great number\nof people.\"\n\n改写: _________________________________________________________\n\nTask 2 Self-Audit\n\nTake a paragraph from an old essay. Perform a style edit on it.\n从⼀篇旧⽂章中选⼀个段落。对其进⾏⽂体编辑。\n\nOriginal Paragraph 原始段落: __________________________________________\n\nEdited Paragraph 编辑后的段落: ________________________________________\n\nChanges Made 所做的修改: I replaced ____ with ____ to be more concise. I changed a passive verb to an active one. I\ncombined two short sentences. etc.\n\n我所做的修改： 我⽤ ____ 替换了 ____ 以更简洁。我把⼀个被动动词改为主动。我合并了两个短句。等等。\n\nTask 3 The Ear Test\n\nRecord yourself reading your edited paragraph from Task 2 aloud. Listen to the recording.\n录制⾃⼰⼤声朗读任务2中编辑后的段落。听录⾳。\n\nWhere did you stumble? 你在哪⾥卡顿了？ ________________________________\nHow will you fix it? 你将如何修改它？ ____________________________________",
  "15": "Chapter 15: Introductions & Conclusions\n第⼗五章：引⾔与结论 (Yǐnyán yǔ jiélùn)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To master the art of the first and last impression. You will learn to\nwrite introductions that hook your reader and conclusions that leave them convinced and thoughtful.\n\n掌握第⼀印象和最后印象的艺术。你将学习写出吸引读者的引⾔和令⼈信服且发⼈深省的结论。\n\nLesson 15.1: The Introduction - The First Impression\n第⼀课：引⾔——第⼀印象 (Yǐnyán——Dì y yìnxiàng)\n\nPart 1: The Introduction Funnel\n\n引⾔漏⽃ (Yǐnyán lòudǒu)\n\nA strong introduction moves from general to specific, funnelling your reader's attention toward your thesis.\n⼀个强有⼒的引⾔从⼀般到具体，将读者的注意⼒引导到你的论⽂上。\n\nPart 2: Components of the Introduction\n\n引⾔的组成部分 (Yǐnyán de zǔchéng bùfèn)\n\nThe Hook 引⼦ (Yǐnzi): A compelling first sentence that grabs attention.\n⼀个引⼈⼊胜的开头句，能吸引注意⼒。\n\nStrategies 策略: A surprising statistic, a provocative question, a brief story (anecdote), a relevant quote, or a\ncommon problem.\n⼀个令⼈惊讶的数据、⼀个 provocative 的问题、⼀个简短的故事（轶事）、⼀个相关的引⽤，或⼀个常⻅的问题。\n\nExample 例⼦: \"Did you know that the average person spends over two hours a day on social media? That's over\nfive years of one's life.\"\n\n\f“你知道普通⼈每天花在社交媒体上的时间超过两个⼩时吗？那就是⼀个⼈⼀⽣中的五年多。”\n\nThe Background 背景信息 (Bèijǐng xìnx ): 2 4 sentences that connect the hook to your specific topic. They provide\ncontext, define key terms, or explain why the topic is important.\n2 4个将引⼦与你特定主题连接起来的句⼦。它们提供背景、定义关键术语，或解释该主题为何重要。\n\nExample 例⼦: \"While designed to connect us, these platforms are increasingly linked to feelings of isolation and\nanxiety, particularly among young adults. This has sparked a intense debate among psychologists, researchers, and\nparents about the true cost of our digital lives.\"\n“虽然旨在连接我们，但这些平台越来越与孤⽴感和焦虑感联系在⼀起，尤其是在年轻⼈中。这引发了⼼理学家、研究⼈员和\n家⻓之间关于我们数字⽣活真实成本的激烈辩论。”\n\nThe Thesis Statement 论⽂陈述 (Lùnwén chénshù): The final sentence of your introduction. It is the specific, arguable\nclaim your entire essay will support.\n你引⾔的最后⼀句。它是你的整篇⽂章将要⽀持的具体的、可论证的主张。\n\nExample 例⼦: \"This essay will argue that while social media offers unprecedented connectivity, its algorithmic\ndesign inherently promotes social comparison and curated self-presentation, ultimately damaging genuine selfesteem and well-being.\"\n“本⽂将论证，虽然社交媒体提供了前所未有的连接性，但其算法设计 inherently 促进了社会⽐较和经过修饰的⾃我呈现，最\n终损害了真正的⾃尊和幸福感。”\n\nLesson 15.2: The Conclusion - The Final Word\n第⼆课：结论——最终定论 (Jiélùn——Zuìzh ng dìnglùn)\n\nPart 1: The Conclusion Inverse Funnel\n结论反向漏⽃ (Jiélùn fǎnxiàng lòudǒu)\n\nA strong conclusion moves from specific to general, leaving the reader with a broad takeaway.\n⼀个强有⼒的结论从具体到⼀般，给读者留下⼀个⼴泛的收获。\n\nPart 2: Components of the Conclusion\n\n结论的组成部分 (Jiélùn de zǔchéng bùfèn)\n\nThe Restated Thesis 重述的论⽂陈述 (Chóngshù de lùnwén chénshù): Rephrase your main argument in fresh language.\nDo not just copy-paste it from the introduction.\n\n\f⽤新的语⾔重新表述你的主要论点。不要只是从引⾔中复制粘贴。\n\nOriginal 原句: \"...its algorithmic design inherently promotes social comparison... ultimately damaging genuine selfesteem...\"\n\n“...其算法设计固有地促进了社会⽐较...最终损害了真正的⾃尊...”\n\nRestated 重述: \"The evidence confirms that the very architecture of social media platforms, built on engagementmaximizing algorithms, fosters a cycle of comparison that erodes authentic self-worth.\"\n“证据证实，社交媒体平台的结构，建⽴在最⼤化参与度的算法之上， foster 了⼀个侵蚀真实⾃我价值的⽐较循环。”\n\nThe Summary of Main Points 主要观点总结 (Zhǔyào gu ndiǎn zǒngjié): Synthesise your main arguments. Show how\nthe evidence you presented logically supports the thesis. Avoid introducing new information.\n综合你的主要论点。展⽰你提供的证据如何逻辑地⽀持论⽂。避免引⼊新信息。\n\nExample 例⼦: \"This is achieved through the constant display of idealized lives, the quantification of social worth\nthrough 'likes,' and the creation of echo chambers that reinforce insecurities.\"\n“这是通过不断展⽰理想化的⽣活、通过‘点赞ʼ量化社会价值，以及创造 reinforce 不安全感的回声室来实现的。”\n\nThe Final Thought 最终思考 (Zuìzh ng s kǎo): The \"So What?\" This is your last chance to leave an impact. Answer:\nWhy does this argument matter in a broader context?\n“那⼜怎样？”这是你留下影响的最后机会。回答：为什么这个论证在更⼴泛的背景下很重要？\n\nStrategies 策略:\nCall to Action ⾏动号召: \"Users must become more critical consumers of these platforms, and regulators should\nconsider design ethics in future legislation.\"\n“⽤户必须成为这些平台更批判性的消费者，监管者应在未来的⽴法中考虑设计伦理。”\n\nLook to the Future 展望未来: \"Understanding this dynamic is the first step toward designing healthier digital\n\nspaces for the next generation.\"\n“理解这种动态是为下⼀代设计更健康数字空间的第⼀步。”\n\nLeave a Lasting Idea 留下⼀个持久的想法: \"Ultimately, the quest for digital connection should not come at the\n\ncost of our analog selves.\"\n\n“最终，对数字连接的追求不应以牺牲我们模拟的⾃我为代价。”\n\nLesson 15.3: Common Pitfalls to Avoid\n\n第三课：要避免的常⻅陷阱 (Yào bìmiǎn de chángjiàn xiànjǐng)\n\nPart 1: Introduction Don'ts\n引⾔禁忌 (Yǐnyán jìnjì)\n\nDON'T start too broad: \"Since the beginning of time, humans have communicated...\"不要开头过于宽泛：“⾃古以来，⼈类\n就进⾏交流...”\n\nDON'T use dictionary definitions: \"Webster's Dictionary defines 'social media' as...\"不要使⽤词典定义：“⻙⽒词典将‘社交\n\n媒体ʼ定义为...”\n\nDON'T announce your intentions: \"In this essay, I will write about...\"不要宣布你的意图：“在这篇⽂章中，我将写下关于...”\nDON'T have a weak or missing thesis.不要有⼀个薄弱或缺失的论⽂陈述。\n\nPart 2: Conclusion Don'ts\n\n结论禁忌 (Jiélùn jìnjì)\n\nDON'T introduce new evidence or arguments. The conclusion is for synthesis, not new information.不要引⼊新的证据或\n\n论点。结论是⽤来综合的，不是提供新信息的。\n\nDON'T just repeat your introduction verbatim.不要只是逐字重复你的引⾔。\nDON'T undercut your argument with weak language: \"I may not be an expert, but...\"不要⽤软弱的语⾔削弱你的论点：“我\n可能不是专家，但是...”",
  "16": "Chapter 16: The Literature Review\n\n第⼗六章：⽂献综述 (Wénxiàn zòngshù)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To learn how to Synthesise existing research on a topic,\nidentifying key themes, debates, and gaps in knowledge, rather than simply summarising sources one by one.\n\n\f学习如何综合关于某⼀主题的现有研究，识别关键主题、辩论和知识空⽩，⽽不是简单地逐个总结来源。\n\nLesson 16.1: What is a Literature Review?\n\n第⼀课：什么是⽂献综述？(Shénme shì wénxiàn zòngshù?)\n\nPart 1: More Than a List\n不仅仅是⼀个列表 (Bù jǐnjǐn shì y gè lièbiǎo)\nA Literature Review ⽂献综述 is not an annotated bibliography. It is not a series of paragraphs that each describe one\nsource.\n⽂献综述不是带注释的参考⽂献。它不是⼀系列每个描述⼀个来源的段落。\n\nA literature review is a Synthesised analysis 综合分析 of the most relevant and significant published work on a specific\nresearch question or topic. It tells a story about what is already known and what is still left to discover.\n\n⽂献综述是对关于特定研究问题或主题的最相关和最重要已发表作品的综合分析。它讲述了⼀个关于已知内容和仍有待发现内容的故\n事。\n\nSummary 总结: \"Smith 2020) found X. Jones 2021) found Y. Lee 2022) found Z.\"\n“Smith 2020 发现了 X。Jones 2021 发现了 Y。Lee 2022 发现了 Z。”\n\nSynthesis 综合: \"The relationship between A and B is complex. While some researchers argue for X Smith, 2020; Lee,\n2022 , others have found evidence for Y Jones, 2021 . This discrepancy may be due to methodological differences,\nsuggesting a need for further research that controls for these variables.\"\n“A 和 B 之间的关系是复杂的。虽然⼀些研究⼈员主张 X（Smith, 2020; Lee, 2022），但其他⼈发现了 Y 的证据（Jones,\n2021）。这种差异可能是由于⽅法论的不同，表明需要进⼀步研究来控制这些变量。”\nPart 2: The Purpose of a Literature Review\n⽂献综述的⽬的 (Wénxiàn zòngshù de mùdì)\n\nTo Demonstrate Knowledge 展⽰知识: It shows your reader you have a deep understanding of the existing research in\nyour field.\n它向你的读者展⽰你对你所在领域的现有研究有深刻的理解。\n\nTo Identify a Gap 识别空⽩: It allows you to identify a gap, problem, or unanswered question in the existing research that\nyour own project will address.\n\n它让你能够识别出现有研究中的⼀个空⽩、问题或未解答的问题，⽽你⾃⼰的项⽬将解决这个问题。\n\nTo Provide a Framework 提供⼀个框架: It places your own research within the context of existing work, showing how it\nbuilds upon, challenges, or extends what is already known.\n\n它将你⾃⼰的研究置于现有⼯作的背景下，展⽰它如何建⽴在已知基础上、挑战已知或扩展已知。\n\nLesson 16.2: Organizing the Conversation\n第⼆课：组织对话 (Zǔzh duìhuà)\n\nYou must organize the sources by theme, not by author. Imagine you are hosting a dinner party with all the researchers. You\nwouldn't have each person give a solo speech. You would guide a conversation around topics.\n\n你必须按主题⽽不是按作者来组织资源。想象你正在举办⼀个所有研究⼈员都参加的晚宴。你不会让每个⼈单独发⾔。你会围绕主题\n引导对话。\n\nPart 1: The Synthesis Matrix\n综合矩阵 (Zònghé jǔzhèn)\nThis is your most powerful tool for moving from summary to synthesis. You used it in Chapter 7; now we apply it specifically\nto the literature review.\n这是你从总结转向综合的最强⼤⼯具。你在第七章中使⽤过它；现在我们专门将其应⽤于⽂献综述。\n\nResearch Question: What is the impact of mindfulness meditation on academic anxiety in university students?\n\n\fSmith 2020\nQuantitative Study\nFound significant\nShort-Term vs.\nreduction in anxiety\nLong-Term Effects scores after a 4-week\nprogram.\nThemes / Debates\n\nChen 2021 Qualitative\nStudy\n\nReports students felt\ncalmer during exams but\neffects faded quickly.\n\nGarcia 2022 MetaAnalysis\nConcludes short-term\neffects are strong, but\nlong-term adherence is a\nproblem.\n\nMy Synthesis / Analysis\nAgreement on short-term\nbenefit, but a key gap exists\nin how to sustain these\neffects long-term.\n\nMechanism of\nAction\n\nSuggests meditation\nreduces activity in the\namygdala (fear center).\n\nStudents reported that it\nhelped them \"distance\nthemselves\" from anxious\nthoughts.\n\nSupports both\nResearch points to a\nneurological and cognitive combination of biological and\npsychological models.\npsychological mechanisms.\n\nMethodological\nGaps\n\nUsed self-report\nsurveys, which can be\nbiased.\n\nSmall sample size 15\nstudents).\n\nThe field would benefit from\nNotes a lack of studies\nmore rigorous methods, like\nwith active control groups. fMRI studies and larger,\ncontrolled trials.\n\nPart 2: From Matrix to Outline\n\n从矩阵到提纲 (Cóng jǔzhèn dào tíg ng)\n\nThe \"My Synthesis\" column from your matrix becomes the topic sentences for your literature review paragraphs.\n你矩阵中的“我的综合”栏变成了你⽂献综述段落的主题句。\n\nSample Outline Based on Matrix:\n\nIntroduction: Define academic anxiety and mindfulness. State the purpose of the review.\nBody Paragraph 1 Theme: Efficacy. While research consistently shows short-term reductions in anxiety from\nmindfulness practice, maintaining these benefits long-term remains a significant challenge Smith, 2020; Chen, 2021;\nGarcia, 2022 .\nBody Paragraph 2 Theme: Mechanism. The literature suggests mindfulness operates through a dual mechanism, both\ncalming the neurological fear response and changing one's cognitive relationship with anxiety Smith, 2020; Chen,\n2021 .\nBody Paragraph 3 Theme: Methodological Gaps. Despite promising results, the field is limited by methodological\nissues, including small sample sizes and a reliance on self-report data Chen, 2021; Garcia, 2022 .\nConclusion: Summarise the state of knowledge and explicitly state the gap your research will fill.\n\nLesson 16.3: The Language of Synthesis\n\n第三课：综合的语⾔ (Zònghé de yǔyán)\n\nYou need specific language to show how sources relate to each other.\n你需要特定的语⾔来显⽰资源如何相互关联。\n\nPart 1: Verbs for Signaling Relationships\n表⽰关系的动词 (Biǎoshì gu nxì de dòngcí)\n\nTo Show Agreement 表⽰同意\n\nX confirms Y...\nX's findings support Y's...\nThis is consistent with Y's work...\nX and Y both conclude that...\n\nTo Show Contradiction 表⽰⽭盾 To Show Addition 表⽰补充\n\nX contradicts Y...\nHowever, Y challenges this...\nIn contrast, Y asserts...\nY offers a different view...\n\nSimilarly, Y found...\nBuilding on this, Y argues...\nFurthermore, Y demonstrates...\nY's work complements X's by...\n\nPart 2: Phrases for Discussing Gaps\n\n讨论空⽩的短语 (Tǎolùn kòngbái de duǎnyǔ)",
  "17": "Chapter 17: The Research Proposal\n\n\f第⼗七章：研究计划书 (Yánji\n\njìhuà sh )\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To learn how to design and propose a formal academic research\nproject. A research proposal argues for why your project is worth doing and how you will do it.\n学习如何设计和提出正式的学术研究项⽬。研究计划书论证为什么你的项⽬值得做以及你将如何做。\n\nLesson 17.1: The Blueprint for Research\n第⼀课：研究蓝图 (Yánji\n\nlántú)\n\nPart 1: What is a Research Proposal?\n什么是研究计划书？(Shénme shì yánji\n\njìhuà sh ?)\nA research proposal 研究计划书 is a formal document that presents a plan for a research project. Its purpose is to convince\nothers (like professors or funding committees) that:\n研究计划书是⼀份呈现研究项⽬计划的正式⽂件。其⽬的是说服他⼈（如教授或资助委员会）相信：\n\nYou have identified a significant research problem.\n\n你已识别出⼀个重要的研究问题。\n\nYou are familiar with the existing literature on the topic.\n你熟悉该主题的现有⽂献。\n\nYou have a sound methodology for conducting the research.\n\n你拥有进⾏研究的合理⽅法。\n\nYour project will make an original contribution to knowledge.\n你的项⽬将为知识做出原创性贡献。\n\nIt is an argument for the value and feasibility of your idea.\n它是为你 idea 的价值和可⾏性进⾏的论证。\n\nPart 2: Core Components\n\n核⼼组成部分 (Héx n zǔchéng bùfèn)\n\nMost research proposals contain these key sections:\n\n⼤多数研究计划书包含这些关键部分：\n\nIntroduction & Problem Statement 引⾔与问题陈述: What is the topic and why is it important?\n主题是什么？为什么它重要？\n\nLiterature Review ⽂献综述: What is already known? What gap will your research fill?\n已知什么？你的研究将填补什么空⽩？\n\nResearch Questions & Objectives 研究问题与⽬标: What exactly will you answer or achieve?\n\n你具体要回答或实现什么？\n\nMethodology ⽅法论: How will you conduct the research? This is the most detailed section.)\n你将如何进⾏研究？（这是最详细的部分。）\nSignificance/Implications 意义/影响: Why does this matter? Who will benefit?\n\n这为什么重要？谁将受益？\n\nTimeline & Bibliography 时间线与参考⽂献: A plan for completion and a list of sources.\n完成计划和⼀个来源列表。\n\nLesson 17.2: Arguing for Your Project\n第⼆课：为你的项⽬论证 (Wèi nǐ de xiàngmù lùnzhèng)\n\nPart 1: The Problem Statement\n\n\f问题陈述 (Wèntí chénshù)\n\nThis is the \"why\" of your proposal. It must answer:\n\n这是你计划书的“为什么”。它必须回答：\n\nWhat is the problem? Be specific.\n问题是什么？ 要具体。\n\nWhy is it a problem? What are the negative consequences of this gap in knowledge?\n\n为什么这是个问题？ 这个知识空⽩有什么负⾯后果？\n\nWho cares? Why should others consider this an important problem to solve?\n\n谁在乎？ 为什么其他⼈应该认为这是⼀个需要解决的重要问题？\n\nFormula 公式: \"Although much is known about [general topic], there is a lack of [specific knowledge] regarding [specific\npopulation/context]. This is problematic because [consequence of not knowing]. Therefore, this study proposes to [your\nresearch action].\"\n例⼦: \"Although much is known about the benefits of mindfulness, there is a lack of qualitative data regarding how\ninternational students experience mindfulness apps for managing culture shock. This is problematic because universities\ninvest in these apps without understanding their user experience. Therefore, this study proposes to conduct in-depth\ninterviews to explore this phenomenon.\"\n\nPart 2: Research Questions & Objectives\n\n研究问题与⽬标 (Yánji\n\nwèntí yǔ mùbi o)\nYour research question(s) should be focused, researchable, and directly connected to the gap you identified.\n你的研究问题应该集中、可研究，并且与你识别的空⽩直接相关。\n\nToo Broad 太宽泛: \"How does social media affect people?\"\n\n“社交媒体如何影响⼈们？”\n\nFocused & Researchable 集中且可研究: \"How does daily Instagram use 1+ hours) correlate with self-reported feelings\nof body image satisfaction among female undergraduates in the UK?\"\n“每⽇使⽤ Instagram（1⼩时以上）与英国⼥本科⽣⾃我报告的⾝体形象满意度感觉如何相关？”\n\nObjectives ⽬标 are the specific steps you will take to answer your research question.\n⽬标是你为回答研究问题将采取的具体步骤。\n\nObjective 1 To review the literature on social media and body image.\n⽬标 1： 回顾关于社交媒体和⾝体形象的⽂献。\n\nObjective 2 To administer a survey measuring Instagram usage and body image satisfaction.\n\n⽬标 2： 进⾏⼀项测量 Instagram 使⽤情况和⾝体形象满意度的调查。\n\nObjective 3 To analyze the data for correlational significance.\n\n⽬标 3： 分析数据以获得相关性显著性。\n\nLesson 17.3: The Methodology Section\n\n第三课：⽅法论部分 (F ngfǎ lùn bùfèn)\n\nThis is the \"how\" of your proposal. It must be detailed enough that someone else could replicate your study.\n这是你计划书的“如何”。它必须⾜够详细，以便其他⼈可以复制你的研究。\n\nPart 1: Choosing Your Methods\n选择你的⽅法 (Xuǎnzé nǐ de f ngfǎ)\n\nYour methodology flows directly from your research question.\n你的⽅法论直接源于你的研究问题。\n\n\fIf Your Question Asks About...\nNumbers, trends, relationships, \"how\nmany?\" 数字、趋势、关系、“有多少？”\nExperiences, meanings, perspectives,\n\"why?\" or \"how?\" 经历、意义、观点、“为什\n么？”或“如何？”\n\nYour Method Might Be...\nQuantitative 定量的 Surveys, experiments,\nstatistical analysis of data 调查、实验、数据统计分\n析\n\nQualitative 定性的 Interviews, focus groups, case\nstudies, textual analysis 访谈、焦点⼩组、案例研\n究、⽂本分析\n\nMixed-Methods 混合⽅法 A combination of\nsurveys and interviews 调查和访谈的结合\n\nBoth of the above 以上两者\n\nWhy?\nIt produces numerical data that can\nbe measured and analyzed\nstatistically.\nIt explores deeper understanding,\nreasons, and motivations through\nwords.\nIt provides both statistical trends and\ndeep, contextual understanding.\n\nPart 2: What to Include in Methodology\n\n⽅法论中应包含的内容 (F ngfǎ lùn zh ng y ng b ohán de nèiróng)\n\nResearch Design 研究设计: Is it quantitative, qualitative, or mixed-methods? Is it an experiment? A case study? A\n\nsurvey?\n\n是定量、定性还是混合⽅法？是实验？案例研究？调查？\n\nParticipants/Data Sources 参与者/数据来源: Who or what will you study? How will you select them? (e.g., \"30 first-year\nstudents recruited from the university participant pool,\" or \"an analysis of 50 news articles from X newspaper\").\n你将研究谁或什么？你将如何选择他们？（例如：“从⼤学参与者库中招募的30名⼀年级学⽣”，或“对X报纸的50篇新闻⽂章进⾏\n\n分析”）。\n\nData Collection 数据收集: What will you actually do? (e.g., \"I will conduct 45-minute semi-structured interviews using\nthe following questions...\", \"I will administer a survey using the Likert scale...\").\n\n你实际要做什么？（例如：“我将使⽤以下问题进⾏45分钟的半结构化访谈...”，“我将使⽤李克特量表进⾏调查...”）。\n\nData Analysis 数据分析: How will you make sense of the data? (e.g., \"I will use thematic analysis to identify patterns in\nthe interview transcripts,\" or \"I will use SPSS software to run a correlation analysis.\").\n你将如何理解数据？（例如：“我将使⽤主题分析来识别访谈记录中的模式，”或“我将使⽤SPSS软件进⾏相关性分析。”）。\n\nEthical Considerations 伦理考虑: How will you protect your participants? (e.g., anonymity, informed consent, right to\n\nwithdraw). This is crucial.\n\n你将如何保护你的参与者？（例如：匿名、知情同意、退出权）。这⾄关重要。\n\nHomework: The Proposal Planner\n\n作业：计划书规划者 (Jìhuà sh\n\ngu huà zhě)\n\nTask 1 Draft a Problem Statement\n\nChoose a potential research topic. Write a 3 4 sentence problem statement using the formula from Lesson 2.\n选择⼀个潜在的研究主题。使⽤第⼆课中的公式写⼀个3 4句的问题陈述。\n\nMy Problem Statement 我的问题陈述: ____________________________________\n\nTask 2 Develop a Research Question\n\nBased on your problem statement, write one clear, focused, and researchable main research question.\n\n基于你的问题陈述，写⼀个清晰、集中、可研究的主要研究问题。\n\nMy Research Question 我的研究问题: ____________________________________\n\nTask 3 Outline Your Methodology\n\nAnswer the following questions to plan your methodology.\n回答以下问题来规划你的⽅法论。\n\nResearch Design 研究设计: Will your study be Quantitative, Qualitative, or Mixed-Methods? Why?\n你的研究将是定量、定性还是混合⽅法？为什么？\n\n1.\n\n2. Participants/Data 参与者/数据: Who or what will you study? How many?\n你将研究谁或什么？多少数量？",
  "18": "Chapter 18: The \"They Say / I Say\" Model\n第⼗⼋章：“他们说/我说”模型 (“T men shu\n\n/ Wǒ shu ” móxíng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To master the essential academic skill of entering a conversation\nby summarising others' ideas (\"they say\") and clearly responding with your own (\"I say\"). This model is the core of\npersuasive academic writing.\n掌握进⼊对话的基本学术技能：总结他⼈的观点（“他们说”）并清晰地回应⾃⼰的观点（“我说”）。这种模型是有说服⼒的学术写作的\n核⼼。\n\nLesson 18.1: Joining the Academic Conversation\n第⼀课：加⼊学术对话 (Ji rù xuéshù duìhuà)\n\nPart 1: Writing is a Conversation\n\n写作是⼀场对话 (Xiězuò shì y chǎng duìhuà)\n\n. You wouldn't just walk in and shout your opinion. You would:\n\nImagine academic writing as a lively dinner party discussion\n\n将学术写作想象成⼀场热闹的晚宴讨论。你不会直接⾛进来就⼤喊你的观点。你会：\n\nListen to what others are saying. (\"They say...\")\n倾听别⼈在说什么。（“他们说...”）\n\nRespond thoughtfully to their points. (\"I say...\")\n\n深思熟虑地回应他们的观点。（“我说...”）\nThis is the\n\n.\n\n\"They Say / I Say\" model. It ensures your writing is engaged and responsive, not just a monologue of your\n\nthoughts\n\n这就是 “他们说/我说” 模型。它确保你的写作是投⼊且回应的，⽽不仅仅是你想法的独⽩。\n\nPart 2: Why \"They Say\" Comes First\n\n为什么“他们说”在先 (Wèishéme “t men shu ” zài xi n)\nStarting with\n\n\"they say\" does three crucial things:\n\n以“他们说”开头有三个关键作⽤：\n\nProvides Context 提供背景: It gives your reader a reason to care about your argument. You are responding to a question\nor problem that others care about.\n它让你的读者有关⼼你的论证的理由。你是在回应⼀个他⼈关⼼的问题或难题。\n\nEstablishes Credibility 建⽴可信度: It shows you are knowledgeable about the topic and have done your research.\n它表明你对该主题知识渊博并且做了研究。\n\nCreates Momentum 创造动⼒: It sets up a problem or debate that your \"I say\" will resolve. This makes your argument\nfeel necessary and important.\n它设置了⼀个你的“我说”将要解决的问题或辩论。这使你的论证显得必要且重要。\n\nLesson 18.2: The Templates of Conversation\n\n\f第⼆课：对话的模板 (Duìhuà de múbǎn)\n\nThe authors of They Say/I Say, Gerald Graff and Cathy Birkenstein, provide templates to help you execute this model\nsmoothly.\nThey Say/I Say 的作者 Gerald Graff 和 Cathy Birkenstein 提供了模板来帮助你顺利执⾏这个模型。\nPart 1: Introducing \"They Say\"\n\n引⼊“他们说” (Yǐnrù “t men shu ”)\n\nUse these templates to introduce the views you are responding to.\n使⽤这些模板来引⼊你要回应的观点。\n\nA standard view ⼀个标准观点: \"Many people assume that...\"\n\n“许多⼈认为...”\n\nA specific author ⼀个特定的作者: \"Sociologist Dr. X has argued that...\"\n“社会学家X博⼠认为...”\n\nA current debate ⼀个当前的辩论: \"In discussions of X, one controversial issue has been...\"\n“在关于X的讨论中，⼀个有争议的问题是...”\n\nAn opposing view ⼀个反对观点: \"On the one hand, some scholars argue... On the other hand, others contend...\"\n“⼀⽅⾯，⼀些学者认为...另⼀⽅⾯，其他⼈主张...”\n\nPart 2: Launching \"I Say\"\n\n展开“我说” (Zhǎnk i “wǒ shu ”)\n\nUse these templates to clearly signal your response.\n使⽤这些模板来清晰地表明你的回应。\n\nAgreeing 同意: \"I agree with X that..., because my research shows...\"\n“我同意X的观点，因为我的研究表明...”\nDisagreeing 不同意: \"While X argues..., I disagree because...\"\n“虽然X认为...，但我不同意，因为...”\n\nAgreeing and Disagreeing 同意和不同意: \"Although I grant that..., I still maintain that...\"\n\n“尽管我承认...，但我仍然坚持认为...”\n\nMaking a concession 做出让步: \"Proponents of X are right to argue..., but they are overly simplistic in claiming...\"\n“X的⽀持者认为...是对的，但他们声称...过于简单化了。”\n\nLesson 18.3: Weaving the Model into Your Writing\n第三课：将模型融⼊你的写作 (Ji ng móxíng róngrù nǐ de xiězuò)\n\nThe \"They Say / I Say\" model isn't just for introductions. It is the basic unit of academic argumentation throughout your\nessay.\n“他们说/我说”模型不仅仅⽤于引⾔。它是贯穿你⽂章的基本学术论证单元。\n\nPart 1: The Naysayer Paragraph\n\n反对段 (Fǎnduì duàn)\n\nA powerful way to use this model is to dedicate a whole paragraph to addressing a counterargument.\n使⽤这个模型的⼀个有⼒⽅式是专门⽤⼀个段落来处理反论点。\n\nThey Say: Introduce the strongest objection to your argument.\n\n他们说： 引⼊对你的论证最强烈的反对意⻅。\n\nI Say: Refute that objection with evidence and reasoning.\n\n我说： ⽤证据和推理反驳那个反对意⻅。\n\nExample 例⼦:\n\n\fThey Say: \"Some might object that my focus on individual solutions to climate change lets large corporations off the\nhook for their disproportionate role in creating the problem.\"\n\n“有些⼈可能反对说，我关注⽓候变化的个体解决⽅案让⼤公司摆脱了它们在制造问题中扮演的不成⽐例⾓⾊的责任。”\n\nI Say: \"While this criticism is valid, it overlooks the fact that consumer demand drives corporate behaviour. Widespread\nindividual adoption of sustainable practices creates a powerful economic incentive for corporations to change, making\nindividual and systemic action two sides of the same coin.\"\n\n“虽然这个批评是合理的，但它忽略了消费者需求驱动企业⾏为的事实。⼴泛采⽤可持续的个体实践为企业变⾰创造了强⼤的经济\n激励，使个体和系统⾏动成为同⼀枚硬币的两⾯。”\n\nPart 2: Putting It All Together - A Worked Example\n\n综合应⽤——⼀个完整的例⼦ (Zònghé yìngyòng——Y gè wánzhěng de lìzi)\n\nTopic: Should AI be used in university grading?主题：⼈⼯智能应该⽤于⼤学评分吗？\nStep 步骤\n\n1. They Say\n\nExample 例⼦\n\n\"Many educators and technologists enthusiastically\nsupport using AI for grading. They argue that it can\nsave instructors countless hours of tedious work,\n\nallowing them to focus on more meaningful student\ninteraction Smith, 2023 .\"\n\nTemplate Used 使⽤的模板\n\n\"Many people assume that...\" \"They argue that...\"\n\n2. I Say\n\n\"While I agree that reducing teacher workload is a\nworthy goal, I contend that replacing human graders\nwith AI undermines the very purpose of education,\nwhich is to understand the unique human mind behind\neach assignment.\"\n\n\"While I agree that..., I contend that...\"\n\n3. Because\n\n\"An AI can scan for grammar and check for plagiarism,\nbut it cannot understand nuance, creativity, or a\nstudent's intellectual journey. It cannot provide the\nempathetic encouragement or the insightful 'why' that a\nhuman teacher can.\"\n\nThis is the evidence and reasoning for my \"I say\")\n\n4. Therefore\n\n\"Therefore, we should view AI as a tool to assist\nteachers with administrative tasks, not as a\n\nThis concludes the point and reinforces my argument)\n\nreplacement for their essential role in evaluating\nstudent learning.\"\n\nHomework: The Conversationalist\n作业：对话者 (Duìhuà zhě)\n\nTask 1 Identify the \"They Say\"\n\nFind an opinion piece or academic article. Read the first few paragraphs.\n找⼀篇观点⽂章或学术⽂章。阅读前⼏段。\n\nSource 来源: _______________________________________________________\nThe \"They Say\" 该⽂的“他们说”: What view, debate, or standard assumption is the author responding to?\n作者在回应什么观点、辩论或标准假设？\n\nTask 2 Practice with Templates\n\nComplete the following sentences using the templates from this chapter.\n\n使⽤本章的模板完成以下句⼦。\n\nThey Say Disagreeing): \"Although some critics argue ,\n\nI believe\n\n___________ because .\"\n\n他们说（不同意）： “虽然⼀些批评者认为，但我相信，因为___________。”\n\nThey Say Agreeing): \"I agree with the author's point that ___________; indeed, my own experience shows that .\"\n他们说（同意）： “我同意作者关于___________的观点；事实上，我⾃⼰的经历表明。”",
  "19": "Chapter 19: Discipline-Specific Writing\n第⼗九章：学科特定写作 (Xuék\n\ntèdìng xiězuò)\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To understand that academic writing has different \"dialects\"\ndepending on the field of study. You will learn to identify and adapt to the key conventions of writing in the Sciences, Social\nSciences, and Humanities.\n理解学术写作根据研究领域有不同的“⽅⾔”。你将学习识别并适应科学、社会科学和⼈⽂学科写作的关键惯例。\n\nLesson 19.1: The Three Academic Cultures\n第⼀课：三种学术⽂化 (S n zhǒng xuéshù wénhuà)\n\nWhile all academic writing values evidence and logic, different disciplines have different ways of arguing, presenting\nevidence, and structuring documents.\n虽然所有学术写作都重视证据和逻辑，但不同学科有不同的论证、呈现证据和构建⽂档的⽅式。\n\nPart 1: The Sciences (e.g., Biology, Physics, Engineering)\n科学 (例如：⽣物学、物理学、⼯程学)\n\nPrimary Goal 主要⽬标: To discover and report objective facts about the natural world. To prove a hypothesis.\n发现和报告关于⾃然世界的客观事实。证明⼀个假设。\nKey Values 核⼼价值: Objectivity 客观性, reproducibility, precision, conciseness.\n客观性、可重复性、精确性、简洁性。\n\nCommon Structure 常⻅结构: IMRaD Introduction, Methods, Results, and Discussion.\nIMRaD 引⾔、⽅法、结果和讨论。\nTone 语⽓: Impersonal, neutral, and direct. Avoids personal opinion.\n客观的、中⽴的、直接的。避免个⼈观点。\n\nEvidence 证据: Quantitative data, statistics, experimental results. Presented in figures, tables, and graphs.\n定量数据、统计数据、实验结果。以图表形式呈现。\n\nExample Sentence 例句:\n\n\"The results indicate a statistically significant (p < .05 correlation between variable X and variable Y.\"\n“结果表明变量X和变量Y之间存在统计学上显著的（p < .05）相关性。”\n\nPart 2: The Social Sciences (e.g., Psychology, Sociology, Economics)\n\n\f社会科学 (例如：⼼理学、社会学、经济学)\n\nPrimary Goal 主要⽬标: To understand human behaviour, societies, and systems. To analyze patterns and causes.\n理解⼈类⾏为、社会和社会系统。分析模式和原因。\n\nKey Values 核⼼价值: Rigor 严谨性, clarity, interpretation of data, connection to theory.\n严谨性、清晰度、数据解释、与理论的联系。\n\nCommon Structure 常⻅结构: Often uses IMRaD, but the Discussion section is heavier, focusing on interpreting results\nin the context of existing theories.\n通常使⽤IMRaD，但讨论部分分量更重，侧重于在现有理论背景下解释结果。\nTone 语⽓: Analytical and objective, but may use more interpretive language than the sciences.\n\n分析性和客观性，但可能⽐科学使⽤更多解释性语⾔。\n\nEvidence 证据: Mix of quantitative data (surveys, statistics) and qualitative data (interviews, case studies).\n定量数据（调查、统计）和定性数据（访谈、案例研究）的结合。\n\nExample Sentence 例句:\n\"This study applies Bandura's theory of social learning to analyze the impact of media models on adolescent\nbehaviour, suggesting a need for further research into protective factors.\"\n“本研究应⽤班杜拉的社会学习理论来分析媒体模型对⻘少年⾏为的影响，表明需要进⼀步研究保护性因素。”\n\nPart 3: The Humanities (e.g., History, Literature, Philosophy)\n\n⼈⽂学科 (例如：历史、⽂学、哲学)\n\nPrimary Goal 主要⽬标: To interpret texts, events, and ideas. To construct a persuasive argument based on evidence\n\nand logical analysis.\n\n解释⽂本、事件和思想。基于证据和逻辑分析构建有说服⼒的论证。\n\nKey Values 核⼼价值: Interpretation 阐释, persuasion, nuance, critical thinking, originality of analysis.\n阐释、说服⼒、细微差别、批判性思维、分析的原创性。\n\nCommon Structure 常⻅结构: Often a thesis-driven essay. Less rigid than IMRaD. Structure is built around the logic of\nthe argument.\n\n通常是论⽂驱动的⽂章。不如IMRaD严格。结构围绕论证的逻辑构建。\n\nTone 语⽓: Can be more personal and authoritative (\"I will argue...\"). Values elegant prose and a strong authorial voice.\n可以更个⼈化和权威（“我将论证...”）。重视优雅的散⽂和强烈的作者声⾳。\nEvidence 证据: Quotations from primary sources (the text, historical document), close reading, and logical reasoning.\n来⾃主要来源（⽂本、历史⽂献）的引⽤、细读和逻辑推理。\n\nExample Sentence 例句:\n\"By close reading the imagery of decay in Eliot's poem, I argue that the work does not merely describe a crisis of faith,\nbut enacts it formally through its fragmented structure.\"\n“通过细读艾略特诗中腐朽的意象，我论证该作品不仅仅描述了⼀场信仰危机，⽽且通过其碎⽚化的结构在形式上呈现了它。”\n\nLesson 19.2: Decoding Disciplinary Conventions\n第⼆课：解读学科惯例 (Jiědú xuék\n\nguànlì)\n\nPart 1: Citation Styles 引⽤⻛格 (Y nyòng f nggé)\nǐ\n\nThe way you cite sources is a quick indicator of the discipline.\n\n你引⽤来源的⽅式是学科的快速指标。\n\nAPA American Psychological Association) 美国⼼理学会格式: Used in Social Sciences Psychology, Education).\nEmphasises author and date Smith, 2023 , highlighting the timeliness of the research.\n⽤于社会科学（⼼理学、教育学）。强调作者和⽇期(Smith, 2023)，突出研究的时效性。\n\n\fMLA Modern Language Association) 现代语⾔协会格式: Used in Humanities Literature, Languages). Emphasises\nauthor and page number Smith 45 ,⽅便读者查找原⽂。\n⽤于⼈⽂学科（⽂学、语⾔）。强调作者和⻚码(Smith 45)，⽅便读者查找原⽂。\n\nChicago/Turabian 芝加哥/图拉宾格式: Used in History and sometimes Humanities. Often uses footnotes¹ for citations.\n⽤于历史学，有时也⽤于⼈⽂学科。通常使⽤脚注¹进⾏引⽤。\nVancouver/AMA 温哥华/美国医学会格式: Used in Medical and Physical Sciences. Uses superscript numbers¹ that\ncorrespond to a numbered reference list.\n\n⽤于医学和物理科学。使⽤上标数字¹，对应编号的参考⽂献列表。\n\nPart 2: Voice and Persona 声⾳与⼈格 (Sh ngy n yǔ réngé)\n\nSciences 科学: Passive voice is often used to create objectivity and focus on the action, not the researcher. (\"The\nsolution was heated\" rather than \"I heated the solution.\").\n\n被动语态通常⽤于创造客观性并聚焦于动作，⽽不是研究者。（“溶液被加热”⽽不是“我加热了溶液。”）。\n\nHumanities ⼈⽂学科: Active voice and first-person (\"I argue,\" \"This essay demonstrates\") are common and\nacceptable to show your authoritative interpretation.\n\n主动语态和第⼀⼈称（“我论证，” “本⽂表明”）很常⻅且可接受，以显⽰你权威的阐释。\n\nSocial Sciences 社会科学: Often a middle ground. May use first person to describe the research process but passive\nvoice for methods. (\"I designed a survey. The data were analyzed using SPSS.\").\n\n通常是中间⽴场。可能使⽤第⼀⼈称描述研究过程，但使⽤⽅法时使⽤被动语态。（“我设计了⼀项调查。数据使⽤SPSS进⾏了分\n析。”）。\n\nLesson 19.3: Becoming a Flexible Writer\n\n第三课：成为灵活的作者 (Chéngwéi línghuó de zuòzhě)\n\nYour task is not to memorize every rule, but to learn to analyze the writing in your field.\n\n你的任务不是记住每⼀条规则，⽽是学会分析你所在领域的写作。\n\nPart 1: How to Analyze a Journal Article\n\n如何分析期刊⽂章 (Rúhé f nx q k n wénzh ng)\n\nWhen you are assigned to write in a new discipline, find a key journal in that field and ask:\n\n当你被要求写⼀个新学科的⽂章时，找到该领域的关键期刊并问：\n\nStructure 结构: How is the article organized? Does it use IMRaD or something else?\n⽂章是如何组织的？它使⽤IMRaD还是其他结构？\n\nVoice 声⾳: Does the author use \"I\" or \"we\"? Is the language personal or impersonal?\n作者使⽤“我”或“我们”吗？语⾔是个⼈的还是客观的？\n\nEvidence 证据: What kind of evidence is used? Data? Quotes? Logical arguments? How is it presented?\n使⽤了什么类型的证据？数据？引⽤？逻辑论证？它是如何呈现的？\n\nCitations 引⽤: What citation style is used? APA, MLA, Chicago? .\n使⽤了什么引⽂格式？（APA、MLA、Chicago？）。\n\nHomework: The Discipline Detective\n\n作业：学科侦探 (Xuék\n\nzh ntàn)\n\nTask 1 Article Analysis\n\nFind one journal article from a field you are interested in (e.g., Psychology, Computer Science, History). Analyze it using the\nquestions above.\n找⼀个你感兴趣领域（例如：⼼理学、计算机科学、历史）的期刊⽂章。⽤上述问题分析它。\n\nJournal/Field 期刊/领域: ______________________________________________\n1. Structure 结构: ___________________________________________________",
  "2": "Chapter 2: The Power of a Single Paragraph\n第⼆章：⼀个段落的⼒量 (Y gè duànluò de lìliàng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To master the PEEL method and build strong, stand-alone\nparagraphs that form the foundation of all your essays.\n掌握PEEL⽅法，构建构成所有论⽂基础的、独⽴完整的强⼤段落。\n\nLesson 2.1: The PEEL Building Block\n\n第⼀课：PEEL结构模块 (PEEL jiégòu mókuài)\n\nPart 1: One Brick at a Time\n\n⼀砖⼀⽡地建造 (Y zhu n y wǎ de jiànzào)\n\nThink back to the Master Blueprint from Chapter 1. Every great structure is built one strong brick at a time. In essay writing,\nthe single, strong paragraph 段落 (duànluò) is your brick.\nIf you can write one excellent paragraph, you can write ten. And ten excellent paragraphs form an excellent essay.\n\n\fToday, you will learn a simple but powerful formula to build perfect paragraphs every time. Itʼs called the PEEL method\n\nPEEL⽅法 (PEEL f ngfǎ).\n\nPart 2: Deconstructing PEEL\n\n解析PEEL Jiěx PEEL\n\nPEEL is an acronym that stands for Point 论点 (Lùndiǎn), Evidence 证据 (Zhèngjù), Explanation 解释 (Jiěshì), Link 连接\n(Liánji ).\nImagine your paragraph is a mini-essay. It needs to introduce an idea, prove it, explain it, and connect it to the bigger\npicture.\n\nLet's break it down 让我们解析⼀下 (Ràng wǒmen jiěx y xià):\nP POINT 论点 (Lùndiǎn)\nThis is your topic sentence 主题句 (zhǔtí jù). It is the most general sentence in your paragraph.\nIt tells the reader exactly what the paragraph will prove.\n\nIt must directly support your main thesis statement 论⽂陈述 (lùnwén chénshù).\nExample 例⼦ (Lìzi): \"One of the main benefits of school uniforms is that they can reduce peer pressure and bullying\n同伴压⼒和欺凌 (tóngbàn y lì hé q líng).\"\n\nE EVIDENCE 证据 (Zhèngjù)\nThis is your proof 证明 (zhèngmíng). You cannot just state your point; you must support it.\n\n\fThis can be a fact 事实 (shìshí), a statistic 数据 (shùjù), a quote 引⽤ (yǐnyòng) from an expert, or a logical example\n\n例⼦ (lìzi).\n\nYou must introduce your evidence and cite it if it's from a source.\nExample 例⼦ (Lìzi): \"For instance, a 2022 study from the National Education Association found that schools with\nuniform policies reported 30% fewer bullying incidents related to clothing.\"\nE EXPLANATION 解释 (Jiěshì)\nThis is the most important part of your paragraph. This is where you show your thinking 思考 (s kǎo) and analysis\n分析 (f nx ).\nYou must explain how and why your evidence proves your point. Do not assume the reader makes the connection.\nExample 例⼦ (Lìzi): \"This statistic suggests that when students wear the same clothing, there are fewer\nopportunities for them to be judged based on their economic status or fashion choices, which are common sources\nof conflict.\"\nL LINK 连接 (Liánji )\nThis sentence concludes your paragraph and connects 连接 (liánji ) it to the main argument or to the next\nparagraph.\nIt creates flow 流畅度 (liúchàng dù) and shows how each paragraph builds your case.\n\nExample 例⼦ (Lìzi): \"Therefore, by reducing these superficial conflicts, uniforms can help create a school\nenvironment where students feel safer and more focused on their studies.\"\n\nPart 3: See It In Action\n实际应⽤ (Shíjì yìngyòng)\n\nTopic 主题 (Zhǔtí): Should homework be banned? 应该禁⽌作业吗？\nThesis 论⽂论点 (Lùnwén lùndiǎn): Homework should be significantly reduced because it negatively impacts student wellbeing 幸福感 (xìngfú gǎn).\n\nThe PEEL Paragraph:\nP Firstly, excessive homework infringes on crucial family time and personal relationships. E Renowned psychologist Dr.\n\nLinda Palmer asserts, \"The hours spent on homework after a long school day are hours lost from meaningful family\ninteraction, which is a key pillar of emotional development\" 2023 . E This expert opinion highlights that homework\ndoesn't just take time; it steals time from the very activities that build social and emotional skills. When a student is\nconstantly stressed about assignments, they are more likely to withdraw from family dinners or conversations, damaging\ntheir support system. L Consequently, the pressure to complete homework can ironically weaken the emotional stability\nthat students need to succeed academically in the first place.\nLabel the PEEL parts in the paragraph above 在上⾯的段落中标注PEEL部分:(A blank space is provided for students to write\nP, E, E, L next to the corresponding sentences in the example)\n\nLesson 2.2: Building Your Own Paragraph\n第⼆课：构建你⾃⼰的段落 (Gòujiàn nǐ zìjǐ de duànluò)\n\nPart 1: Hands-On Workshop\n\n实践⼯作坊 (Shíjiàn g ngzuò f ng)\n\nInstructions 说明 (Shu míng): Let's build a PEEL paragraph together. We will use the topic from your diagnostic essay.\n让我们共同构建⼀个PEEL段落。我们将使⽤你诊断⽂章的主题。\nStep 1 Choose Your Point. 选择你的论点 (Xuǎnzé nǐ de lùndiǎn)\nTopic 主题 (Zhǔtí): A school rule I would change.\nMy Thesis 我的论点 (Wǒ de lùndiǎn): [Student writes their thesis from Chapter 1 here]\n\n\fMy Point for this paragraph 本段落的论点 (Běn duànluò de lùndiǎn): (Your first reason that supports your thesis)\nExample: Allowing phone use at designated times would actually teach students valuable time management skills 时间管\n理技能 (shíji n guǎnlǐ jìnéng).\n\nStep 2 Find Your Evidence. 找到你的证据 (Zhǎodào nǐ de zhèngjù)\nHow can you prove your point? What kind of evidence could you use?\nA logical example 逻辑例⼦ (luójí lìzi)\n\nA quote from an article ⽂章引⽤ (wénzh ng y nyòng)\nData or a statistic 数据或统计 (shùjù huò t ngjì)\nǐ\n\nǒ\n\nA personal observation 个⼈观察 (gèrén gu nchá) (use carefully!)\n\nMy Evidence 我的证据 (Wǒ de zhèngjù):\n\nExample: For example, if students are given a 20-minute period to use their phones, they must learn to prioritize their tasks\n—checking messages, connecting with family, or relaxing—within a fixed timeframe 固定时间范围 (gùdìng shíji n fànwéi).\nStep 3 Write Your Explanation. 写出你的解释 (Xiěch nǐ de jiěshì)\nThis is your analysis 分析 (f nx ). Why does your evidence matter? How does it prove your point?\nSentence Starter 句⼦开头 (Jùzi k itóu): This example shows that... This is important because...\n\nExample: This is a direct practical lesson in budgeting a limited resource—time. This skill is far more transferable to the real\nworld than simply following a rule without understanding its purpose.\n\nStep 4 Create Your Link. 创建你的连接 (Chuàngjiàn nǐ de liánji )\nConnect your paragraph back to your main argument.\nSentence Starter 句⼦开头 (Jùzi k itóu): Therefore,... This demonstrates that... As a result,...\n\nExample: Therefore, modifying the phone rule would transform it from a simple restriction into a tool for preparing students\nfor the demands of the modern workforce 现代劳动⼒需求 (xiàndài láodònglì x qiú).\n\nPart 2: Put It All Together 整合所有部分 (Zhěng hé suǒyǒu bùfèn)\n\nNow, write your complete PEEL paragraph in the space below. Use the sentences you just crafted.\n\n现在，在下⾯的空⽩处写出你完整的PEEL段落。使⽤你刚才创作的句⼦。\n\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\nPart 3: Peer Review 同伴评审 (Tóngbàn píngshěn)\n\nSwap your paragraph with a partner. Use the checklist below to review their work. Give them one piece of praise 表扬\n\n(biǎoyáng) and one suggestion 建议 (jiànyì).\n\nPEEL Checklist PEEL检查清单 (PEEL jiǎnchá q ngd n):\n\nP Is the Point clear? Does it state the main idea of the paragraph?\n\n论点清晰吗？它陈述了段落的主旨吗？\n\nE Is the Evidence relevant? Does it directly support the point?\n\n证据相关吗？它直接⽀持论点吗？\n\nE Is the Explanation effective? Does it connect the evidence to the point?\n\n解释有效吗？它将证据与论点连接起来了吗？\n\n\fL Does the Link sentence conclude the idea or connect it to a larger topic?\n\n连接句是否总结了观点或将其连接到更⼤的主题？\n\nPraise 表扬 (Biǎoyáng): One thing I liked about your paragraph was...\n我喜欢你段落的⼀点是...\n\nSuggestion 建议 (Jiànyì): One thing you could make even stronger is...\n你可以做得更强的⼀点是...\n\nHomework: Practice Makes Perfect 作业：\n熟能⽣巧 (Shú néng sh ng qiǎo)\n\nTask 任务 (Rènwù): Write two different PEEL paragraphs on the topics below. Use the AI tools to help you brainstorm\nevidence if you get stuck.\n就以下主题写两个不同的PEEL段落。如果卡住了，使⽤AI⼯具来帮助你头脑⻛暴证据。\nParagraph 1 Topic 段落1主题: Zoos do more harm than good. 动物园弊⼤于利。\n(P)\nE\nE\nL\nParagraph 2 Topic 段落2主题: Social media platforms should have stricter age verification. 社交媒体平台应有更严格的年龄验\n\n证。\n(P)\n\nE\nE\nL\nRemember 记住 (Jìzhù): You are practicing the structure. Use your AI tool as a brainstorming helper to find facts or\nexamples, but the writing and thinking must be your own.\n你正在练习结构。使⽤AI⼯具作为头脑⻛暴的助⼿来寻找事实或例⼦，但写作和思考必须是你⾃⼰的。\nDeveloping your idea\n\n\fHow to find your Essay idea.\n\nTASK:\nThink of a topic you are interested in and write in in the middle of your page.\n(e.g. Social Media)\nCreate at least 5 10 subtopic ideas about that main topic. You can use deepseek to help.\n(e.g. Mental health in social media, Privacy online, Social Apps, Fake news…)\nSelect the one sub topic that is the most interesting to you.\n\n(e.g. I think “Fake News” is interesting)\n\nNow you have the title of your essay. TITLE Main Topic + Subtopic Social Media and fake news)\nCreate 5 10 paragraph ideas about the subtopic\n(e.g. What can I write about fake news? Moderation filters, Motivation why?, Consequences of posting fake news, why\nwe share fake news…). Again, you can use Deepseek to help you find ideas.\nCreate P.E.E.L paragraphs for each idea.\nTIP Consider using a mindmap tool like above.\n\nNOTION Template\n\nTOPIC\n\ne g Social Media)\n\n( . .\n\nSubtopic\n\nCreate 5 Subtopics and pick the most interesting one\n1)e.g. Fake News\n\nDevelop the idea\n\nPick your favourite subtopic and write down paragraph ideas, then add PEEL to each paragraph.\n\nSubtopic\n\nParagraph idea\n\nPEEL Ideas\n\ne.g. Fake News\n\ne.g. Role of Algorithms\n\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\nParagraph idea\n\nPEEL Ideas\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\nParagraph idea\n\nPEEL Ideas\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\nParagraph idea\n\nPEEL Ideas\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\n\fParagraph idea\n\nPEEL Ideas\nP\nE\nE\nL\n\nExample Homework:\nThe PEEL Paragraph Builder – Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points and will contribute to your overall\nCoursework average Weight: 20% of your final grade).\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement 0 4\npts)\n\nTask 1 Write PEEL\nParagraphs\n\nBoth paragraphs flawlessly\nfollow the PEEL structure.\nPoints are clear and arguable,\nevidence is relevant and wellintegrated, explanations are\ninsightful, and links are\nstrong. Language is precise\nand academic.\n\nBoth paragraphs correctly\nuse the PEEL structure. All\ncomponents are present,\nbut some may be less\ndeveloped (e.g., evidence\ncould be more specific,\nexplanation slightly\nvague).\n\nParagraphs attempt the\nPEEL structure but\ncomponents are weak\nor misplaced (e.g.,\npoint is factual,\nexplanation just\nrestates evidence). One\ncomponent may be\nmissing.\n\nParagraphs do not follow\nthe PEEL structure, are\nsummary-based, or are\nincomplete. Major\ncomponents missing.\n\nTask 2 Peer Review\n& Reflection\n\nPeer review feedback is\nspecific, constructive, and\ndemonstrates a clear\nunderstanding of the PEEL\ncriteria. Reflection shows\ndeep metacognitive insight\ninto the writing process and\npeer learning.\n\nPeer review is completed\nwith relevant feedback for\neach PEEL component.\nReflection addresses the\nquestions but could be\nmore detailed.\n\nPeer review is vague or Peer review is missing or\nsuperficial. Reflection is irrelevant. Reflection is\nbrief and lacks depth.\nmissing or off-topic.\n\nTask 3 Paragraph\nRevision\n\nRevision significantly\nimproves the original\nparagraph. Changes directly\naddress feedback and\nstrengthen the argument,\nevidence, or analysis. The\nrevised paragraph is polished\nand professional.\n\nRevision addresses the\nfeedback and shows clear\nimprovement. The\nparagraph is stronger but\nmay still have minor\nissues.\n\nRevision is attempted\nbut changes are\nminimal or do not\neffectively address the\nfeedback.\n\nRevision is missing, or the\nrevised paragraph is\nweaker than the original.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\nTask 1: Write Two PEEL Paragraphs\nParagraph 1 Topic: Zoos do more harm than good.\nP Modern zoos, despite their conservation claims, ultimately cause more psychological and physical harm to animals than\n\ngood.\nE A 2021 study by the Animal behaviour Society found that captive elephants in accredited zoos exhibit stereotypical\nbehaviours such as pacing and head-bobbing at a rate 300% higher than their wild counterparts, indicating severe\npsychological distress.\n\n\fE These repetitive, functionless behaviours are recognised signs of poor welfare and mental suffering in captive animals,\nsuggesting that even the most well-designed enclosures cannot meet the complex cognitive and spatial needs of intelligent\nspecies.\nL Therefore, the ethical cost of keeping such animals in captivity for public education may outweigh the potential\nconservation benefits.\nParagraph 2 Topic: Social media platforms should have stricter age verification.\nP Implementing rigorous age-verification systems on social media platforms is essential to protect minors from harmful\ncontent and predatory behaviour.\nE According to a 2023 report by the Cyberbullying Research Center, 42% of adolescents aged 12 15 have encountered\nsevere cyberbullying or inappropriate adult contact on platforms with weak age gates.\nE This statistic reveals a direct link between lax verification and increased exposure to psychosocial risks during a critical\ndevelopmental period, as anonymous or falsified adult profiles can easily bypass current \"click-to-enter\" safeguards.\nL Consequently, robust age verification is not just a privacy measure but a necessary duty of care to create safer online\nspaces for young users.\n\nTask 2: Peer Review & Reflection\nPeer Review for Partnerʼs Paragraph Topic: Zoos):\nPraise: Your point is very clear and arguable. The evidence from the Animal behaviour Society is strong and recent.\nSuggestion: The link could connect more directly to the \"education vs. harm\" debate. Maybe add: \"This calls into\nquestion the educational value of observing distressed animals.\"\nReflection:\n\nThe PEEL structure forced me to justify every part of my argument. I noticed that finding the right evidence took the most\ntime, but it made my explanation much stronger. Reviewing my partnerʼs work helped me see how a strong link can tie the\nparagraph back to a bigger thesis.\n\nTask 3: Develop the idea\n\nPick your favourite subtopic and write down paragraph ideas, then add PEEL to each paragraph.\nSubtopic: Fake News\nParagraph idea 1 Role of Social Media Algorithms\nPEEL Ideas\nP Social media algorithms play a pivotal role in the spread of fake news by actively amplifying content that triggers strong\nemotional reactions, regardless of its veracity.\n\nE For instance, a 2023 MIT study on content virality found that false news stories are 70% more likely to be retweeted than\ntrue ones, because they often evoke surprise, fear, or disgust—emotions that algorithms are designed to prioritise for\nincreased user engagement.\nE This demonstrates that the algorithmic design does not merely distribute information neutrally; it creates a powerful\nincentive structure. When a post receives rapid engagement, the platformʼs system interprets it as \"valuable\" and pushes it\nto larger audiences, creating a feedback loop where sensational falsehoods can outpace careful, factual reporting.\nL Therefore, the architecture of social media itself acts as an unintentional but powerful accelerator for misinformation,\nmaking the problem a systemic one rather than merely a failure of individual judgment.\nParagraph idea 2 The Financial and Political Motivation Behind Creation\nPEEL Ideas\n\n\fP A primary driver of fake news creation is not misinformation but deliberate disinformation, fuelled by clear financial or\n\npolitical incentives.\nE Investigative reports, such as from The New York Times on the \"Macedonian teenagers\" phenomenon, revealed\nindividuals running entire websites filled with fabricated viral news about U.S. politics, generating substantial advertising\nrevenue through clickbait. Similarly, state-sponsored actors create and seed false narratives to sow discord, influence\nelections, or destabilize geopolitical rivals.\nE This evidence shows that fake news is often a calculated product, not an accidental error. The creators are adept at\nidentifying divisive societal fissures and crafting stories that exploit them, knowing that outrage and conflict are highly\nmarketable commodities in the digital attention economy.\nL Consequently, combating fake news requires addressing these underlying incentives, such as through stricter\nregulations on political ad transparency and disrupting the ad-revenue models for blatantly fraudulent sites.\nParagraph idea 3 Erosion of Public Trust in Institutions\nPEEL Ideas\nP The pervasive circulation of fake news fundamentally erodes public trust in traditional institutions like journalism,\n\nscience, and government.\nE The repeated exposure to contradictory and manipulative information leads to a state of \"truth decay,\" where citizens\nbecome cynical and retreat into information silos. A landmark study by the RAND Corporation documents this correlation,\nshowing a marked decline in trust in factual, evidence-based sources coinciding with the rise of the digital misinformation\necosystem.\nE This erosion is dangerous because a functioning democracy relies on a shared basis of facts to debate policies and hold\nleaders accountable. When people cannot agree on basic realities—from election results to public health measures—\ncollective problem-solving becomes impossible, paving the way for polarisation and authoritarianism.\nL Thus, the damage inflicted by fake news extends beyond individual false beliefs to a crippling of the foundational trust\nnecessary for societal cohesion and democratic governance.\nParagraph idea 4 The Psychological Factors in Sharing Why We Believe & Spread It)\n\nPEEL Ideas\nP Beyond algorithms and bad actors, the human psychology of information processing makes individuals susceptible to\n\nbelieving and sharing fake news.\nE Cognitive biases like confirmation bias (favoring information that fits our existing beliefs) and the illusory truth effect\n(repeating a statement makes it seem more true) are key factors. Research in the Journal of Experimental Psychology has\nshown that even when people encounter a correction, the initial false impression can persist in their reasoning.\nE This means that fake news is sticky because it often aligns with our pre-existing worldviews, and its simple, repetitive\nmessaging is cognitively easier to accept than complex, nuanced truths. Sharing it can also be a social signal, reinforcing\ngroup identity and belonging.\nL Therefore, effective media literacy education must go beyond fact-checking to include training in recognising these\ninnate cognitive biases, equipping people to be critical of their own thought processes.\nParagraph idea 5 Solutions and Countermeasures: Media Literacy and Platform Accountability\nPEEL Ideas\nP A dual-pronged solution focusing on individual media literacy and robust platform accountability offers the most viable\n\npath to mitigating the fake news crisis.\nE Successful initiatives, like Finland's national media literacy program integrated into school curricula from an early age,\nhave demonstrably increased resilience to misinformation. On the platform side, measures such as Facebook's Meta",
  "20": "Chapter 20: Capstone Project Launch\n第⼆⼗章：顶点项⽬启动 (Dǐngdiǎn xiàngmù qǐdòng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To Synthesise all the skills you have learned this year by\nproposing, planning, and initiating your final capstone project. This is your chance to demonstrate mastery as an academic\nwriter and thinker.\n综合你今年学到的所有技能，提出、规划并启动你的最终顶点项⽬。这是你展⽰作为学术作家和思想家掌握能⼒的机会。\n\nLesson 20.1: What is a Capstone?\n\n第⼀课：什么是顶点项⽬？(Shénme shì dǐngdiǎn xiàngmù?)\n\nPart 1: The Culminating Experience\n\n巅峰体验 (Di nf ng tǐyàn)\n\nA capstone project 顶点项⽬ is a multifaceted assignment that serves as a culminating academic and intellectual\nexperience. It is not just a longer essay; it is a demonstration of your comprehensive skills:\n\n顶点项⽬是⼀个多⽅⾯的任务，是学术和智⼒经验的巅峰。它不仅仅是⼀篇更⻓的⽂章；它是你综合技能的展⽰：\n\n\fResearch 研究: Formulating a question, finding and evaluating sources.\n提出问题，寻找和评估资源。\n\nAnalysis 分析: Synthesizing information and applying disciplinary methods.\n综合信息并应⽤学科⽅法。\n\nArgumentation 论证: Building a complex, sustained argument.\n构建⼀个复杂的、持续的论证。\n\nWriting 写作: Producing a substantial, polished piece of academic writing.\n产出实质性的、精美的学术写作。\n\nThink of it as your academic masterpiece—the project that proves you are ready for the next level.\n将其视为你的学术杰作——证明你已为下⼀阶段做好准备的项⽬。\n\nPart 2: Choosing Your Path\n\n选择你的路径 (Xuǎnzé nǐ de lùjìng)\n\nYou will typically choose one of two tracks for your capstone:\n\n你通常将为你的顶点项⽬选择以下两种路径之⼀：\n\nThe Research Track 研究路径: You conduct deep research on a specific question and write a long-form essay (e.g.,\n3000 5000 words) that includes a full literature review, original analysis, and a sophisticated argument.\n\n你对⼀个具体问题进⾏深⼊研究，并写⼀篇⻓⽂（例如：3000 5000词），包括完整的⽂献综述、原创分析和复杂的论证。\n\nThe Applied Track 应⽤路径: You apply your skills to a real-world problem. This could involve creating a portfolio,\ndesigning a curriculum, writing a business plan, or conducting a community-based project, accompanied by a reflective\nessay explaining your process and choices.\n\n你将技能应⽤于现实世界的问题。这可能涉及创建作品集、设计课程、撰写商业计划或进⾏基于社区的项⽬，并附上⼀篇解释你\n的过程和选择的反思性⽂章。\n\nLesson 20.2: The Project Proposal\n第⼆课：项⽬提案 (Xiàngmù tí'àn)\n\nYour first formal step is to write a proposal. This is your plan and your contract for the project.\n\n你的第⼀个正式步骤是写⼀份提案。这是你的计划和项⽬合同。\n\nPart 1: Components of a Proposal\n\n提案的组成部分 (Tí'àn de zǔchéng bùfèn)\n\nA strong proposal includes the following elements. Use this as a checklist.\n\n⼀个强有⼒的提案包含以下要素。将其⽤作检查清单。\n\nComponent 组成部分\n\n1. Working Title 暂定标题\n\n2. Research Question 研究\n\n问题\n\n3. Rationale ⽴项理由\n\n4. Literature Review ⽂献综\n\n述\n\n5. Methodology ⽅法论\n\n6. Tentative Outline 初步提\n\n纲\n\n7. Timeline 时间线\n\nDescription 描述\n\nExample Question to Answer 需要回答的⽰例问题\nDoes the title clearly signal my topic and\nA clear, descriptive title for your project.\napproach?\nIs my question focused, complex, and\nThe central question your project will answer.\nresearchable?\nWhy is this question important and interesting? The \"So Why should anyone care about the answer to my\nWhat?\")\nquestion?\nA brief summary of the key sources and the gap your\nWhat is already known, and what will my project\nproject will fill.\nadd?\nHow you will conduct your research or execute your\nWhat specific steps will I take to answer my\nproject.\nquestion?\nA basic structure for your final paper or project.\n\nHow will I organize my ideas and evidence?\n\nA realistic schedule for completing each stage of the\n\nIs my plan feasible given the deadline?\n\n\fComponent 组成部分\n\nDescription 描述\nproject.\n\nExample Question to Answer 需要回答的⽰例问题\n\n8. Bibliography 参考⽂献\n\nA preliminary list of 5 10 key sources you will use.\n\nHave I found credible, relevant sources to build\non?\n\nPart 2: Drafting Your Research Question\n起草你的研究问题 (Qǐcǎo nǐ de yánji\n\nwèntí)\nYour research question is the engine of your entire project. Use the \"Question Funnel\" from Chapter 3 to refine it.\n\n你的研究问题是你整个项⽬的引擎。使⽤第三章的“问题漏⽃”来完善它。\n\nBroad Topic ⼴泛主题: Artificial Intelligence in Education\n教育中的⼈⼯智能\n\nNarrowed Topic 缩⼩主题: AI tools for helping ESL students with writing\n帮助ESL学⽣写作的AI⼯具\n\nSpecific Research Question 具体研究问题: \"To what extent can AI grammar checkers like Grammarly and Quillbot improve\nthe writing fluency and accuracy of intermediate-level ESL students, and what are the potential limitations of these tools in\nan academic context?\"\n“像Grammarly和Quillbot这样的AI语法检查器能在多⼤程度上提⾼中级ESL学⽣的写作流利度和准确性，以及这些⼯具在学术环境中\n\n的潜在局限性是什么？”\n\nThis question is focused (on specific tools and a specific group), complex (asks \"to what extent\" and \"what are\nlimitations\"), and researchable (can be explored through source analysis or original research).\n\n这个问题集中（于特定⼯具和特定群体）、复杂（询问“在多⼤程度上”和“局限性是什么”）且可研究（可以通过资源分析或原创研究进\n⾏探索）。\n\nLesson 20.3: Planning for Success\n\n第三课：为成功做计划 (Wèi chéngg ng zuò jìhuà)\n\nPart 1: The Capstone Timeline\n\n顶点项⽬时间线 (Dǐngdiǎn xiàngmù shíji nxiàn)\n\nA major project can feel overwhelming. The solution is to break it down into small, manageable steps.\n\n⼀个⼤型项⽬可能让⼈不知所措。解决⽅案是将其分解为⼩的、可管理的步骤。\ngantt\ntitle Example Capstone Timeline (8 Weeks)\ndateFormat YYYY-MM-DD\naxisFormat %m/%d\n\nsection Research & Planning\nFinalize Proposal & Annotated Bib :crit, 2024-10-01, 7d\nDeep Reading & Note-Taking\n:2024-10-08, 14d\nComplete Detailed Outline\n:2024-10-22, 7d\nsection Drafting\nWrite First Draft (Get ideas down) :2024-10-29, 14d\nsection Revision & Polishing\nRevise for Argument & Structure\nEdit for Clarity & Style\nProofread & Format Final Draft\nSubmit Capstone Project\n\n:2024-11-12, 7d\n:2024-11-19, 7d\n:2024-11-26, 5d\n:milestone, 2024-12-01, 0d\n\n\fPart 2: Using Your Tools\n\n使⽤你的⼯具 (Shǐyòng nǐ de g ngjù)\n\nRemember the tools you've mastered. This is when they become essential.\n\n记住你掌握的⼯具。此时它们变得⾄关重要。\n\nPerplexity/DeepSeek: For initial exploration and source discovery\n\n.\n\n⽤于初步探索和资源发现。\n\nZotero: To manage all your sources and generate citations automatically\n\n.\n\n管理所有资源并⾃动⽣成引⽂。\n\nThe Synthesis Matrix: To organize your notes from your reading and find connections\n\n组织你的阅读笔记并找到联系。\n\n.\n\nThe Master Flowchart & Outlines: To structure your argument\n\n.\n\n构建你的论证结构。\n\nQuillbot Grammar Checker: For a final polish but never for generating ideas\n⽤于最终润⾊（但绝不⽤于⽣成想法！）。\n\n(\n\n! .\n\nHomework: The Proposal Draft\n\n作业：提案草稿 (Tí'àn cǎogǎo)\n\nTask 1 Choose Your Track and Topic\n\nDecide if you are following the Research Track or the Applied Track. Then, use the space below to brainstorm three\npossible topics.\n\n决定你是选择研究路径还是应⽤路径。然后，使⽤下⾯的空间进⾏头脑⻛暴，想出三个可能的主题。\n\nMy Track 我的路径:\nTopic Idea 1 主题想法 1\nTopic Idea 2 主题想法 2\nTopic Idea 3 主题想法 3\nMy Chosen Topic 我选择的主题:\n\n__________________________________________________\n_____________________________________________\n_____________________________________________\n_____________________________________________\n_________________________________________\n\nTask 2 Draft Your Core Components\n\nFor your chosen topic, draft the two most critical parts of your proposal.\n\n为你选择的主题，起草提案中两个最关键的部分。\n\nMy Research Question 我的研究问题:\n\n____________________________________\n\nMy Rationale The \"So What?\") 我的⽴项理由（“那⼜怎样？”）:\n\n_______________",
  "21": "Chapter 21: Capstone Work I - Research & Outlining\n第⼆⼗⼀章：顶点项⽬⼯作 I - 研究与提纲 (Dǐngdiǎn xiàngmù g ngzuò I\n\nYánji yǔ tíg ng)\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move from your approved proposal into the active research\nphase. You will learn strategies for deep, efficient research and how to structure your findings into a detailed outline, which\nis the blueprint for your first draft.\n从你已批准的提案进⼊积极的研究阶段。你将学习深⼊、⾼效研究的策略，以及如何将你的发现构建成⼀个详细的提纲，这是你初稿\n的蓝图。\n\nLesson 21.1: Strategic Deep Research\n\n第⼀课：战略性深度研究 (Zhànlüè xìng sh ndù yánji )\n\nPart 1: Moving Beyond the Basics\n超越基础 (Ch oyuè j chǔ)\n\nYour initial research found sources that helped you write your proposal. Now you need sources that will help you write your\npaper. This requires a deeper, more targeted approach.\n\n你初步的研究找到了帮助你撰写提案的资源。现在你需要能够帮助你撰写论⽂的资源。这需要更深⼊、更有针对性的⽅法。\n\nShift Your Search Terms 转变你的搜索词:\n\nFrom Broad 从宽泛: \"social media and mental health\"\n“社交媒体与⼼理健康”\n\nTo Specific 到具体: \"Instagram AND self-esteem AND longitudinal study AND adolescents\"\n“Instagram AND ⾃尊 AND 纵向研究 AND ⻘少年”\n\nUse the advanced search functions in databases to filter by:\n使⽤数据库中的⾼级搜索功能来按以下条件筛选：\n\nPublication Date 出版⽇期: Get the most recent research.\n\n获取最新的研究。\n\nSubject Terms 主题词: Find sources that are precisely categorized.\n找到精确分类的资源。\n\nScholarly/Peer-Reviewed Journals 学术/同⾏评审期刊: Ensure academic rigor.\n\n确保学术严谨性。\n\n\fPart 2: The Source Triage System\n\n资源筛选系统 (Z yuán sh ixuǎn xìtǒng)\n\nNot all sources are created equal. As you find them, sort them into three categories:\n\n并⾮所有资源都是平等的。当你找到它们时，将其分为三类：\n\nKeystone Sources 核⼼资源: The 3 5 most important articles or books that are directly central to your argument. You\nwill read these word-for-word and cite them frequently.\n3 5篇最重要的⽂章或书籍，与你的论证直接核⼼相关。你将逐字阅读这些内容并频繁引⽤。\n\nSupporting Sources ⽀持性资源: Sources that provide useful evidence for a specific point or section. You might only\n\nread a key chapter or section.\n\n为特定观点或部分提供有⽤证据的资源。你可能只阅读⼀个关键章节或部分。\n\nBackground Sources 背景资源: Sources that help you understand the general context but may not be cited directly.\nEncyclopedias, textbooks, general overviews.\n\n帮助你理解总体背景但可能不会直接引⽤的资源。百科全书、教科书、总体概述。\n\nThis system prevents you from getting overwhelmed and ensures you spend your time on what matters most.\n\n这个系统可以防⽌你不知所措，并确保你的时间花在最重要的事情上。\n\nLesson 21.2: The Detailed Outline - Your Draft's Blueprint\n第⼆课：详细提纲——你草稿的蓝图 (Xiángxì tíg ng——Nǐ cǎogǎo de lántú)\n\nA detailed outline is not a list of topics. It is the fully planned structure of your essay, complete with your evidence\nintegrated. Writing from a strong outline is faster and produces a more coherent draft.\n\n详细的提纲不是主题列表。它是你⽂章完全规划好的结构，并整合了你的证据。根据⼀个强⼤的提纲写作更快，并能产⽣更连贯的草\n稿。\n\nPart 1: The Components of a Detailed Outline\n\n详细提纲的组成部分 (Xiángxì tíg ng de zǔchéng bùfèn)\n\nYour outline should go down to the paragraph level. For each body paragraph, plan:\n你的提纲应该细化到段落级别。对于每个主体段落，规划：\n\nTopic Sentence 主题句: The point you are making in this paragraph. It should support your thesis.\n你在本段中要阐述的论点。它应该⽀持你的论⽂。\n\nEvidence 证据: The specific quotes, data, or paraphrased ideas from your sources that support your topic sentence.\nInclude author names and page numbers.\n来⾃你资源的特定引⽂、数据或释义观点，⽤以⽀持你的主题句。包含作者姓名和⻚码。\n\nExplanation/Analysis 解释/分析: Your voice. A note on how the evidence proves your point. Why does this matter? How\n\ndoes it connect to the next idea?\n\n你的声⾳。关于证据如何证明你的观点的注释。这为什么重要？它如何连接到下⼀个观点？\n\nLink 连接: How this paragraph leads to the next one.\n这个段落如何引导到下⼀个段落。\n\nPart 2: Outline Format Example\n\n提纲格式⽰例 (Tíg ng géshì shìlì)\n\nThesis: While AI writing tools offer valuable support for ESL students in improving surface-level accuracy, their overuse\n\ncan hinder the development of deeper critical thinking and authentic voice in academic writing.\n论⽂： 虽然AI写作⼯具为ESL学⽣提⾼表⾯准确性提供了宝贵的⽀持，但过度使⽤会阻碍学术写作中更深层次批判性思维和真实声⾳\n的发展。\n\nI. Introduction\n\nA. Hook: Statistic on AI tool usage in universities.\n\n\fB. Background: Rise of Grammarly, Quillbot, etc.\nC. Thesis: See above).\n\nII. Body Paragraph 1 The Benefits for Surface-Level Accuracy\nA. Topic Sentence: AI tools can significantly reduce grammatical and mechanical errors for intermediate ESL writers.\nB. Evidence: - Smith 2023) study: 40% reduction in errors in student essays using tool X (p. 15).\n\n- \"The automated feedback provides immediate correction, which is crucial for acquisition\" Chen, 2022, p. 8 .\nC. Analysis: This shows these tools are effective as a digital proofreader, freeing up student mental energy.\nD. Link: However, this focus on error correction does not address higher-order writing skills.\n\nIII. Body Paragraph 2 The Limitation for Critical Thinking\nA. Topic Sentence: The convenience of AI suggestions can bypass the crucial cognitive process of self-editing and critical\nevaluation.\nB. Evidence: - Lee 2024) interviews: students \"just accept the changes\" without understanding why they were wrong (p.\n\n5.\n- Garcia 2023) argues that the struggle with grammar is part of the learning process itself (p. 102).\nC. Analysis: If a student doesn't engage with the mistake, they are less likely to learn from it, creating a dependency.\nD. Link: Furthermore, the impact goes beyond grammar to the writer's own voice.\n\nThe outline would continue like this for all paragraphs, including the counterargument and conclusion.)\n\nLesson 21.3: Managing Your Research\n\n第三课：管理你的研究 (Guǎnlǐ nǐ de yánji )\n\nPart 1: The Annotated Bibliography Revisited\n\n重温带注释的参考⽂献 (Chóngw n dài zhùshì de c nkǎo wénxiàn)\n\nNow is the time to build a formal Annotated Bibliography 带注释的参考⽂献 for your Keystone and Supporting sources. This\nis different from your synthesis matrix. Each source gets its own entry with:\n现在是时候为你的核⼼和⽀持性资源建⽴⼀个正式的带注释的参考⽂献了。这与你的综合矩阵不同。每个资源都有其⾃⼰的条⽬，包\n含：\n\nAPA/MLA Citation APA/MLA引⽂: The formal citation.\n\n正式的引⽂。\n\nSummary 3 4 sentences) 总结 3 4句): What is the source's main argument and findings?\n资源的主要论点和发现是什么？\n\nRelevance 1 2 sentences) 相关性 1 2句): How will you use this source in your capstone? Which section does it\nsupport?\n\n你将如何在你的顶点项⽬中使⽤这个资源？它⽀持哪个部分？\n\nThis process solidifies your understanding of each source and makes writing your draft infinitely easier.\n这个过程巩固你对每个资源的理解，并使撰写草稿变得⽆限容易。\n\nPart 2: Avoiding the \"Writing Wall\"\n\n避免“写作墙” (Bìmiǎn “xiězuò qiáng”)\n\nWhen faced with a blank page, it's easy to freeze. Your detailed outline and annotated bibliography are your solutions. You\nare not starting from scratch. You are simply translating your outline into prose.\n\n当⾯对⼀个空⽩⻚⾯时，很容易卡住。你的详细提纲和带注释的参考⽂献就是你的解决⽅案。你不是从零开始。你只是在将你的提纲\n翻译成散⽂。\n\nIf you get stuck on a section, move to another one. You do not have to write the draft in order.\n如果你在某⼀部分卡住了，就转到另⼀部分。你不必按顺序写草稿。\n\nHomework: The Architect's Plan\n\n作业：建筑师的计划 (Jiànzhù sh de jìhuà)",
  "22": "Chapter 22: Capstone Work II - Drafting & Peer Review\n\n第⼆⼗⼆章：顶点项⽬⼯作 II - 起草与同⾏评审 (Dǐngdiǎn xiàngmù g ngzuò II\n\nQǐcǎo yǔ tóngháng pǐnshěn)\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To transform your detailed outline into a complete first draft and\nto use peer feedback to identify strengths and weaknesses before you begin revising.\n\n将你的详细提纲转化为完整的初稿，并在开始修改之前利⽤同⾏反馈识别优点和缺点。\n\nLesson 22.1: From Outline to Draft\n第⼀课：从提纲到草稿 (Cóng tíg ng dào cǎogǎo)\n\n\fPart 1: The \"Vomit Draft\" Mentality\n“呕吐草稿”⼼态 (“Ǒutù cǎogǎo” x ntài)\n\nYour first draft does not need to be perfect. Its only job is to exist.\n\n你的初稿不需要完美。它唯⼀的任务就是存在。\n\nA \"vomit draft\" is a messy, imperfect, but complete version of your paper. You get all your ideas out of your head and onto\nthe page without stopping to edit, perfect sentences, or fix every citation. This frees you to focus on the flow of your\nargument.\n\n“呕吐草稿”是⼀个混乱、不完美但完整的论⽂版本。你将所有想法从脑中倾泻到⻚⾯上，⽽不停下来编辑、完善句⼦或修改每个引\n⽤。这让你能够专注于论证的流畅性。\n\nRules for the Vomit Draft 呕吐草稿规则:\nDon't Edit 不要编辑: If you can't think of the perfect word, write a placeholder word BETTER WORD and keep going.\n如果你想不到最完美的词，写⼀个占位词 [更好的词] 然后继续。\n\nDon't Stop 不要停⽌: Don't go back to research mid-sentence. If you need a fact, mark it FIND STAT and keep writing.\n不要在写句⼦时回去研究。如果你需要⼀个事实，标记它 [查找数据] 然后继续写。\nFollow Your Outline 遵循你的提纲: Your detailed outline is your roadmap. Your job is to turn each bullet point into\nsentences.\n\n你的详细提纲是你的路线图。你的⼯作是将每个要点变成句⼦。\n\nPart 2: Starting Your Engine\n\n启动你的引擎 (Qǐdòng nǐ de yǐnqíng)\n\nThe blank page can be intimidating. Start with the section you feel most confident writing—it doesn't have to be the\nintroduction. Many writers start with the body paragraphs.\n空⽩⻚⾯可能令⼈⽣畏。从你最有信⼼写的部分开始——不⼀定是引⾔。许多作者从主体段落开始。\n\nIf you get stuck 如果你卡住了:\nTalk it out 说出来: Explain your argument to a friend, pet, or even a rubber duck. Explain why your evidence matters.\nThen, write down what you just said.\n\n向朋友、宠物甚⾄橡⽪鸭解释你的论证。解释为什么你的证据重要。然后，写下你刚刚说的话。\n\nSet a timer 设置计时器: Write for 25 minutes without stopping. Take a 5-minute break. Repeat.\n不停笔地写25分钟。休息5分钟。重复。\n\nSkip around 跳着写: If a paragraph isn't working, jump to a different one. You can connect them later.\n如果⼀个段落写不下去，就跳到另⼀个段落。你可以稍后连接它们。\n\nLesson 22.2: The Power of Peer Review\n\n第⼆课：同⾏评审的⼒量 (Tóngháng pǐnshěn de lìliàng)\n\nYou are too close to your own writing to see its flaws clearly. A peer reviewer acts as a fresh set of eyes, representing your\nfuture reader.\n你对⾃⼰的写作过于熟悉，⽆法清晰看到其缺陷。同⾏评审者代表你未来的读者，提供新鲜的视⾓。\n\nPart 1: How to Be a Helpful Reviewer\n\n如何成为有帮助的评审者 (Rúhé chéngwéi yǒu b ngzhù de pǐnshěn zhě)\n\nWhen reviewing someone else's work, your goal is to be constructive 建设性的, not cruel.\n在评审他⼈的⼯作时，你的⽬标是建设性的，⽽不是残酷的。\n\nThe \"Feedback Sandwich\" 反馈三明治技巧:\nCompliment 表扬: Start with something you genuinely liked. (\"Your thesis is very clear and specific!\").\n以你真正喜欢的东⻄开始。（“你的论⽂⾮常清晰和具体！”）。\n\n\fCritique 批评: Offer specific, actionable suggestions for improvement. (\"I got a bit lost in this paragraph. Could you add\na topic sentence to make the main point clearer?\").\n\n提供具体的、可操作的改进建议。（“我在这个段落有点困惑。你能加⼀个主题句让要点更清晰吗？”）。\n\nEncourage ⿎励: End with positive reinforcement. (\"This is a really strong start. With a few tweaks, this argument will be\n\npowerful!\").\n\n以积极的强化结束。（“这是⼀个⾮常强⼤的开始。稍作调整，这个论证将会⾮常有⼒！”）。\n\nFocus on \"Higher Order\" Concerns First ⾸先关注“更⾼层次”的问题:\nThesis 论⽂: Is it clear and arguable?\n它是否清晰且可论证？\n\nStructure 结构: Does the organization make sense? Does each paragraph support the thesis?\n组织结构是否合理？每个段落是否⽀持论⽂？\nEvidence 证据: Is the evidence convincing? Is it integrated smoothly?\n证据是否令⼈信服？是否整合得流畅？\n\nClarity 清晰度: Where did you get confused as a reader?\n作为读者，你在哪⾥感到困惑？\n\nSave \"Lower Order\" Concerns for Later 将“较低层次”的问题留到后⾯:\n\nGrammar, spelling, punctuation, and citation format. These are easy to fix later. Don't focus on them in an early draft.\n语法、拼写、标点和引⽤格式。这些以后很容易修复。在初稿中不要专注于这些。\n\nPart 2: How to Receive Feedback\n如何接收反馈 (Rúhé ji sh u fǎnkuì)\n\nReceiving criticism is hard, but it is the fastest way to improve.\n\n接受批评很难，但这是提⾼最快的⽅法。\n\nListen, Don't Defend 倾听，不要辩护: Your job is to understand the reader's confusion, not to argue why they are\nwrong. If they are confused, a future reader will be too.\n\n你的⼯作是理解读者的困惑，⽽不是争论他们为什么错了。如果他们感到困惑，未来的读者也会如此。\n\nTake Notes 记笔记: Write down all feedback. You don't have to accept every suggestion, but you should consider it.\n记下所有反馈。你不必接受每⼀个建议，但你应该考虑它。\n\nAsk Clarifying Questions 提出澄清问题: \"Can you tell me more about why that part was unclear?\" \"What did you think\n\nthe main point of that paragraph was?\"\n“你能多告诉我⼀点那部分为什么不清楚吗？” “你认为那段落的要点是什么？”\n\nThank Your Reviewer 感谢你的评审者: They spent time and energy trying to help you.\n他们花了时间和精⼒试图帮助你。\n\nLesson 22.3: Creating a Peer Review Guide\n\n第三课：创建同⾏评审指南 (Chuàngjiàn tóngháng pǐnshěn zhǐnán)\n\nA structured guide ensures reviewers give you the specific feedback you need.\n⼀个结构化的指南确保评审者给你需要的具体反馈。\n\nSample Peer Review Form 同⾏评审表⽰例\nReviewer's Name 评审者姓名: ____________________\nAuthor's Name 作者姓名: ____________________\nInstructions: Please read the draft once through. Then, answer the following questions.说明：请通读草稿⼀遍。然后，回答\n以下问题。\n\n\f1.\n\nThesis and Focus 论⽂与焦点\n\nWhat is the main argument of the paper in your own words?\n\n⽤你⾃⼰的话说明论⽂的主要论点是什么？\n\nIs the thesis clear and specific? Is it maintained throughout the paper?\n\n论⽂是否清晰具体？是否在整个论⽂中得以保持？\n\n2.\n\nOrganization and Flow 组织与流畅性\n\nIs the paper logically organized? Do the ideas flow smoothly from one to the next?\n\n论⽂组织是否有逻辑？观点是否流畅地从⼀个过渡到下⼀个？\n\nList the main point of each body paragraph:列出每个主体段落的要点：\nPara 1 _________________________________________________________\n\nPara 2 _________________________________________________________\nPara 3 _________________________________________________________\nIs there any place where you got lost or confused?\n\n有没有哪⾥让你感到迷失或困惑？\n\n3.\n\nEvidence and Analysis 证据与分析\n\nIs the evidence (quotes, data, examples) convincing and relevant?\n\n证据（引⽂、数据、例⼦）是否令⼈信服且相关？\n\nDoes the author explain how the evidence supports their point? Look for analysis, not just summary).\n作者是否解释了证据如何⽀持他们的观点？（寻找分析，⽽不仅仅是总结）。\n\n4.\n\nBiggest Strength 最⼤优点\n\nWhat is the single best thing about this draft?\n这份草稿最好的⼀点是什么？\n5.\n\nOne Suggestion for Improvement ⼀项改进建议\n\nWhat is the one most important thing the author should work on for the next draft?\n\n作者在下⼀稿中最应该做的⼀件最重要的事是什么？\n\nHomework: The Drafting Lab\n\n作业：起草实验室 (Qǐcǎo shíyàn shì)\n\nTask 1 The Writing Sprint\n\nSet a timer for 45 minutes. Using your detailed outline, write non-stop. Do not edit. Do not go back. Just write. The goal is\nto get as much of your draft onto the page as possible.\n设置⼀个45分钟的计时器。使⽤你的详细提纲，不停笔地写。不要编辑。不要回头。只管写。⽬标是尽可能多地将草稿写到纸上。\n\nWhat I accomplished 我完成了什么: ______________________________________\n\nTask 2 Peer Review Exchange\n\nSwap your vomit draft with a partner. Use the Sample Peer Review Form above to review their work. Provide kind, specific,\nand helpful feedback.\n与伙伴交换你的呕吐草稿。使⽤上⾯的同⾏评审表⽰例来评审他们的⼯作。提供友好、具体和有帮助的反馈。\n\nThe most helpful suggestion I received 我收到的最有帮助的建议: _______________\n\nTask 3 Revision Plan\n\nBased on the feedback you received and your own re-reading, list the top 3 things you need to fix or improve in your next\ndraft.\n根据你收到的反馈和你⾃⼰的重读，列出你在下⼀稿中需要修改或改进的3个⾸要事项。",
  "23": "Chapter 23: Capstone Work III – Synthesizing Research & The\nFormal Outline\n第⼆⼗三章：核⼼成果 III - 研究与正式⼤纲的合成 (Héx n chéngguǒ III\n\nYánji yǔ zhèngshì dàg ng de héchéng)\n\nChapter Introduction:\n\nOver the past two chapters, you've defined your research question and gathered your sources. Now, the real synthesis\nbegins. This chapter is about moving from a collection of notes to a structured, logical blueprint for your research paper. A\nstrong outline is the key to a clear, persuasive, and well-organized argument.\n\n在之前的两个章节中，你们定义了研究问题并收集了资料。现在，真正的合成开始了。本章旨在将零散的笔记转化为研究论⽂的结构\n化、逻辑化的蓝图。⼀个强⼤的提纲是写出清晰、有说服⼒且组织良好的论⽂的关键。\n\nLesson 23.1: From Notes to Structure (40 mins)\n第23.1课：从笔记到结构 (Cóng bǐjì dào jiégòu)\n\nGoal: To organize research notes into thematic groups that will form the main points of the paper.\n\n⽬标： 将研究笔记组织成主题组，这些主题组将构成论⽂的要点。\n\nPart A: The Sorting Process\n\n整理过程 (Zhěnglǐ guòchéng)\n\nYour digital or physical notecards are your raw material. Your first task is to sort them into piles based on recurring themes,\nideas, or arguments that support your thesis. Don't force it; let the categories emerge from your research.\n你的数字或实体笔记卡是你的原材料。你的第⼀个任务是根据重复出现的主题、想法或⽀持你论点的论证将它们分类。不要强求；让\n类别从你的研究中⾃然浮现。\n\nTip: Use different coloured highlighters or digital tags to colour-code your notes by theme.\n提⽰： 使⽤不同颜⾊的荧光笔或数字标签按主题为你的笔记进⾏颜⾊编码。\n\nPart B: Identifying Main Arguments\n\n识别主要论点 (Shíbié zhǔyào lùndiǎn)\n\nLook at your sorted piles. Each major thematic group has the potential to become a main point (a Roman Numeral in your\noutline). Ask yourself:\n看看你整理好的分类。每个主要的主题组都有可能成为⼀个要点（你⼤纲中的罗⻢数字）。问⾃⼰：\n\nDoes this group of evidence directly support my thesis?\n这组证据是否直接⽀持我的论点？\n\nIs this point substantial enough to be a major section of my paper?\n这个要点是否⾜够重要，可以成为论⽂的⼀个主要部分？\n\nTry to draft a topic sentence for each pile—a claim that this group of evidence proves.\n尝试为每⼀组草拟⼀个主题句——即这组证据所能证明的⼀个主张。\n\n\fTask 1 任务⼀ (Rènwù y ) (10 mins):\n\nTake your research notes from Chapter 22. Actively sort them into 3 4 thematic groups. For each group, write a onesentence description of what that group is about (e.g., “Economic benefits of remote work,” “Social challenges of remote\nwork”).\n\n拿出你在第22章的研究笔记。主动将它们分为3 4个主题组。为每个组写⼀句话描述该组的内容（例如，“远程⼯作的经济效益”、“远\n程⼯作的社会挑战”）。\n\nLesson 23.2: Building the Formal Outline (40 mins)\n第23.2课：构建正式⼤纲 (Gòujiàn zhèngshì dàg ng)\n\nGoal: To construct a detailed formal outline using standard alphanumeric formatting.\n\n⽬标： 使⽤标准的字⺟数字格式构建⼀个详细的正式⼤纲。\n\nPart A: The Rules of the Road\n规则指引 (Gu zé zhǐyǐn)\n\nA formal outline uses a specific structure to show the hierarchy of your ideas:\n正式⼤纲使⽤特定的结构来显⽰你观点的层次结构：\n\nI, II, III Main Points Body Paragraphs/Sections) 要点 (Yàodiǎn)\nA, B, C Sub-points or specific claims within a main point 分论点 (F n lùndiǎn)\n\nEvidence, examples, and data (e.g., a specific statistic or quote) 证据 (Zhèngjù)\na, b, c: Further analysis or explanation of that evidence 分析 (F nx )\n1, 2, 3\n\nPrinciples to Follow:需遵循的原则：\nCoordination 并列关系 (Bìngliè gu nxì): Items at the same level (all the 'A's under a 'I') must be of equal importance.\nSubordination 从属关系 (Cóngshǔ gu nxì): Information at each level must be more specific than the level above it. Your\n'A' explains your 'I'; your '1' provides evidence for your 'A'.\n\nPart B: Integrating Your Sources\n\n整合资料源 (Zhěnghé z liào yuán)\n\nWithin your outline, note which source provides evidence for each point. This makes drafting infinitely easier.\n\n在你的⼤纲中，注明哪个资料源为每个要点提供了证据。这会让起草论⽂变得⽆⽐容易。\n\nExample: Under II.A.2, you might write: \"Data on songbird population decline in North America - National Audubon\nSociety, 2023 .\"\n例⼦： 在 II.A.2 下⾯，你可以写：“关于北美鸣禽数量下降的数据 - (National Audubon Society, 2023)。”\n\nTask 2 任务⼆\nRènwù èr)\n\nUsing your thematic groups from Lesson 23.1, build the skeleton of your formal outline. Draft your main points as complete\nsentences I, II, III . Under each, add 2 3 sub-points A, B, C) that state what you will argue in that section.\n使⽤你在第23.1课整理的主题组，构建你的正式⼤纲的框架。将你的要点草拟为完整的句⼦（I, II, III）。在每个要点下，添加2 3个分\n论点（A, B, C），说明你将在该部分论证的内容。\n\nLesson 23.3: The Roadmap to Your First Draft (40 mins)\n第23.3课：通往初稿的路线图 (T ngwǎng ch gǎo de lùxiàntú)\n\nGoal: To refine the outline and use it to begin drafting the paper's introduction.\n⽬标： 完善⼤纲，并利⽤它开始起草论⽂的引⾔。\n\n\fPart A: The Reverse Outline Check\n反向⼤纲检查 (Fǎnxiàng dàg ng jiǎnchá)\n\nA powerful way to test your outline is to read only the points labelled I, II, and III (your main topic sentences). Do they flow\nlogically from one to the next? Do they, together, provide a complete and compelling argument for your thesis? If not,\nrearrange or reword them.\n测试你的⼤纲的⼀个有效⽅法是只阅读标有 I, II 和 III 的要点（你的主要主题句）。它们之间逻辑流畅吗？它们是否共同为你的论点提\n供了⼀个完整且令⼈信服的论证？如果没有，重新排列或改写它们。\n\nPart B: Drafting from the Outline - The Introduction\n根据⼤纲起草 - 引⾔ (G njù dàg ng qǐcǎo - Yǐnyán)\n\nYour outline isn't just for the body. It informs your entire paper. Use it to draft your introduction.\n\n你的⼤纲不仅仅适⽤于正⽂。它为你的整篇论⽂提供信息。⽤它来起草你的引⾔。\n\nHook 引⼦ (Yǐnzi): Start with a compelling fact, question, or anecdote from your research.\n\nBackground 背景信息 (Bèijǐng xìnx ): Provide context necessary to understand the argument (drawn from your initial\nresearch).\nThesis Statement 论点陈述 (Lùndiǎn chénshù): Insert your refined thesis from Chapter 22. It is the engine of your\npaper.\n\nRoadmap 路线图 (Lùxiàntú): Briefly Summarise the main points I, II, III) that you will use to prove your thesis. Example:\n\n\"This paper will first analyze X, before arguing Y, and finally proposing Z.\"\n\nTask 3 任务三 (Rènwù s n) (15 mins):\n\nPerform a \"reverse outline check\" on your partner's outline. Provide feedback on the logical flow of their main points. Then,\nwrite a first draft of your paper's introduction, including a clear roadmap sentence.\n对你伙伴的⼤纲进⾏“反向⼤纲检查”。就他们要点的逻辑流畅性提供反馈。然后，撰写你论⽂引⾔的第⼀稿，包括⼀个清晰的路线图\n句⼦。\n\nChapter 23: Tasks & Homework\n\n第23章：任务与作业 (Rènwù yǔ zuòyè)\n\nIn-Class Tasks 课堂任务 (Kètáng rènwù):\n\nTask 1 Thematic sorting of research notes. 研究笔记的主题分类。\n\nTask 2 Construction of a detailed alphanumeric outline skeleton. 构建详细的字⺟数字⼤纲框架。\nTask 3 Peer review of outlines and drafting of the introduction. 同伴互评⼤纲并起草引⾔。\n\nHomework 作业 (Zuòyè):\n\nComplete Your Formal Outline 完成正式⼤纲 (Wánchéng zhèngshì dàg ng): Flesh out your outline from class into its\nfull, detailed form. Every sub-point A, B, C) must have at least two pieces of supporting evidence 1, 2) noted beneath\nit, with the source identified in parentheses.\n将你在课堂上完成的⼤纲充实为完整、详细的形式。每个分论点（A, B, C）下⾯必须⾄少有两个⽀持证据（1, 2），并在括号中注\n\n明来源。\n\nSubmit Your Blueprint 提交你的蓝图 (Tíji o nǐ de lántú): Your completed formal outline is your primary deliverable for\nthis chapter.\n你完成的正式⼤纲是本章的主要交付成果。",
  "24": "Chapter 24: Presentation Skills\n第⼆⼗四章：演讲技巧 (Yǎnjiǎng jìqiǎo)\n\nChapter Introduction:\n\nA vital part of academic and professional life is communicating your ideas clearly and persuasively to an audience. This\nchapter will equip you with the skills to design and deliver a compelling presentation based on your research paper.\n\n章节介绍： 学术和职业⽣活中⾄关重要的⼀部分是向听众清晰且有说服⼒地传达你的想法。本章将为你提供基于研究论⽂设计和进⾏\n引⼈⼊胜的演讲所需的技能。\n\nLesson 24.1: Distilling Your Argument (40 mins)\n第24.1课：提炼你的论点 (Tíliàn nǐ de lùndiǎn)\n\nGoal: To adapt a written paper into a concise, oral presentation format.\n⽬标： 将书⾯论⽂改编成简洁的⼝头演讲格式。\n\nPart A: The Elevator Pitch\n\n电梯游说 (Diànt yóushuì)\n\nYou have 3 minutes to explain your research question, thesis, and most important finding. How do you do it? This is your\ncore message.\n你只有3分钟时间来解释你的研究问题、论点和最重要的发现。你会怎么做？这就是你的核⼼信息。\n\nPart B: Structuring for the Ear\n\n为听觉⽽设计的结构 (Wèi t ngjué ér shèjì de jiégòu)\n\nListeners can't re-read a complex sentence. Simplify your structure:\n听众⽆法重读复杂的句⼦。简化你的结构：\n\nTell them what you'll tell them 告知演讲内容 (Gàozh yǎnjiǎng nèiróng): (Introduction: Hook, Thesis, Roadmap)\nTell them 展开内容 (Zhǎnk i nèiróng): 2 3 main points, with one clear example each)\nTell them what you told them 总结内容 (Zǒngjié nèiróng): (Conclusion: Restate thesis, significance, Q&A)\n\nTask 1 任务⼀ (Rènwù y ) (10 mins):\n\nWrite a 3-minute \"elevator pitch\" for your research paper. Practice delivering it to a partner.\n为你的研究论⽂写⼀个3分钟的“电梯游说”。练习向⼀位伙伴进⾏演讲。\n\nLesson 24.2: Visual Aids & Slide Design (40 mins)\n\n第24.2课：视觉辅助与幻灯⽚设计 (Shìjué fǔzhù yǔ huànd ngpiàn shèjì)\n\nGoal: To create visual aids that support, rather than distract from, your presentation.\n⽬标： 创建能够⽀持⽽不是分散演讲注意⼒的视觉辅助⼯具。\n\nPart A: Less is More\n\n少即是多 (Shǎo jí shì du )\n\n\fThe best slides are minimalist.\n最好的幻灯⽚是极简的。\n\nRule of Thumb 经验法则 (J ngyàn fǎzé): One idea per slide. Use keywords, not full sentences.\nUse visuals 使⽤视觉元素 (Shǐyòng shìjué yuánsù): A powerful graph, chart, or image is more memorable than text.\nAvoid clutter 避免杂乱 (Bìmiǎn záluàn): No complicated animations or busy templates.\n\nPart B: Practicing Delivery\n\n练习演讲 (Liànxí yǎnjiǎng)\n\nHow you speak is as important as what you say.\n你说话的⽅式和你说什么⼀样重要。\n\nPace 语速 (Yǔsù): Speak slowly and clearly. Pause for emphasis.\nPosture 姿态 (Z tài): Stand tall, make eye contact with your audience.\nNotes 笔记 (Bǐjì): Use your note cards for keywords, not a full script.\n\nTask 2 任务⼆ (Rènwù èr) (15 mins):\n\nUsing your elevator pitch, storyboard 3 4 slides that would accompany it Title, Thesis, Main Point 1 + visual, Conclusion).\n\n使⽤你的电梯游说，为其故事板化3 4张幻灯⽚（标题、论点、要点1 + 视觉元素、结论）。\n\nLesson 24.3: Mastering Q&A and Peer Workshop (40 mins)\n\n第24.3课：掌握问答与同伴研讨会 (Zhǎngwò wèndá yǔ tóngbàn yántǎohuì)\n\nGoal: To prepare for audience questions and refine presentations through feedback.\n⽬标： 准备听众提问，并通过反馈完善演讲。\n\nPart A: Anticipating Questions\n\n预测问题 (Yùcè wèntí)\n\nWhat are the weak points in your argument? What might someone disagree with? Brainstorm 3 5 potential questions and\npractice your answers.\n你论证中的弱点是什么？有⼈可能会不同意什么？头脑⻛暴3 5个潜在问题并练习你的回答。\n\nPart B: The Feedback Loop\n反馈循环 (Fǎnkuì xúnhuán)\n\nUse a feedback rubric to evaluate peers. Focus on:\n\n使⽤反馈量表评估同伴。关注：\n\nClarity of thesis 论点清晰度 (Lùndiǎn q ngx dù)\nStructure and pacing 结构与节奏 (Jiégòu yǔ jiézòu)\n\nEffectiveness of visual aids 视觉辅助的效果 (Shìjué fǔzhù de xiàoguǒ)\nSpeaker presence 演讲者⻛范 (Yǎnjiǎngzhě f ngfàn) (eye contact, voice)\n\nTask 3 任务三 (Rènwù s n) (20 mins):\n\nIn groups, deliver your 3-minute elevator pitch with your storyboarded slides. Participate in the feedback loop, giving and\nreceiving constructive criticism.\n\n分组进⾏，⽤你故事板化的幻灯⽚发表你的3分钟电梯游说。参与反馈循环，给予和接受建设性的批评。",
  "25": "Chapter 24: Tasks & Homework\n\n第24章：任务与作业 (Rènwù yǔ zuòyè)\n\nHomework 作业 (Zuòyè):\n\nCreate a full slide deck 5 7 slides) for your presentation. 为你的演讲创建⼀个完整的幻灯⽚⽂档（5 7张幻灯⽚）。\nWrite a one-page presenter script with key talking points, not a full transcript. 写⼀份⼀⻚的演讲者脚本，包含关键讲话要\n\n点，⽽不是完整的⽂字稿。\n\nPractice your presentation aloud at least three times. ⼤声练习你的演讲⾄少三遍。\n\nChapter 25: Course Wrap-up & Future-Proofing\n\n第⼆⼗五章：课程总结与未来保障 (Kèchéng zǒngjié yǔ wèilái bǎozhàng)\n\nChapter Introduction: Congratulations on nearing the completion of this course. This final chapter is designed to help you\nreflect on your growth, consolidate the skills you've learned, and apply them to your future academic and professional\nendeavours.\n\n章节介绍： 恭喜你们即将完成本课程。这最后⼀章旨在帮助你们反思⾃⼰的成⻓，巩固所学的技能，并将它们应⽤到未来的学术和职\n业努⼒中。\n\nLesson 25.1: The Portfolio & Reflective Practice (40 mins)\n第25.1课：作品集与反思实践 (Zuòpǐn jí yǔ fǎns shíjiàn)\n\nGoal: To create a writing portfolio and articulate the skills acquired in the course.\n\n⽬标： 创建⼀个写作作品集，并清晰说明在课程中获得的技能。\n\nPart A: What is a Writing Portfolio?\n\n什么是写作作品集？(Shénme shì xiězuò zuòpǐn jí?)\n\nA portfolio is a curated collection of your work that demonstrates your skills and development. It should include final drafts\nand, importantly, earlier drafts and outlines to show your process.\n\n作品集是展⽰你技能和发展的精选作品集合。它应包括最终稿，重要的是，还应包括早期的草稿和提纲以展⽰你的过程。\n\nPart B: The Reflective Statement\n反思陈述 (Fǎns chénshù)\n\nWrite a brief letter to your future self. Answer:\n\n给你未来的⾃⼰写⼀封简短的信。回答：\n\nWhat was the most significant writing skill you gained?\n你获得的最重要的写作技能是什么？\n\nWhat are you most proud of in your research paper?\n你的研究论⽂中最让你⾃豪的是什么？\n\nWhat would you do differently next time?\n下次你会有什么不同的做法？\n\nHow can you use these skills in your next class?\n你如何在下⼀次课程中使⽤这些技能？\n\nTask 1 任务⼀ (Rènwù y ) (20 mins):\n\n\fAssemble your course work. Select 2 3 key pieces that show your growth. Begin drafting a one-paragraph reflective\nstatement for your portfolio.\n整理你的课程作业。选择2 3件能展⽰你成⻓的关键作品。开始为你的作品集起草⼀段反思陈述。\n\nLesson 25.2: The Transferable Skills Toolkit (40 mins)\n第25.2课：可转移技能⼯具箱 (Kě zhuǎnyí jìnéng g ngjù xi ng)\n\nGoal: To explicitly identify and plan for the use of course skills in other contexts.\n⽬标： 明确识别并规划在其它情境中运⽤课程技能。\n\nPart A: Skill Mapping\n\n技能图谱 (Jìnéng túpǔ)\n\nThe skills you practiced are not just for \"English class.\"\n\n你练习的技能不仅仅适⽤于“英语课”。\n\nResearch & Analysis 研究与分析 (Yánji yǔ f nx ): For history, science, business reports.\nFormal Argumentation 正式论证 (Zhèngshì lùnzhèng): For debate, law, policy proposals.\nOutline & Structure ⼤纲与结构 (Dàg ng yǔ jiégòu): For planning any complex project.\nPresentation Skills 演讲技巧 (Yǎnjiǎng jìqiǎo): For job interviews, team meetings, conferences.\n\nPart B: Looking Forward\n\n展望未来 (Zhǎnwàng wèilái)\n\nWhere will you use these skills next? In your next year of study? In a potential job? Discuss how these skills are valued\nacross different fields.\n接下来你将在哪⾥使⽤这些技能？在下⼀学年的学习中？在⼀个潜在的⼯作中？讨论这些技能在不同领域如何受到重视。\n\nTask 2 任务⼆ (Rènwù èr) (20 mins):\n\nCreate a \"Skills Map.\" List the 5 most important skills from this course and brainstorm one specific way you could use each\none in another subject or real-world scenario next year.\n\n创建⼀个“技能图谱”。列出本课程中5项最重要的技能，并头脑⻛暴明年你在另⼀门课程或现实世界场景中运⽤每项技能的⼀种具体⽅\n式。\n\nChapter 25: Tasks & Homework\n第25章：任务与作业 (Rènwù yǔ zuòyè)\n\nFinal Course Homework 最终课程作业 (Zuìzh ng kèchéng zuòyè):\nFinalize Your Portfolio 最终确定你的作品集 (Zuìzh ng quèdìng nǐ de zuòpǐn jí):\n\nCompile your final research paper, all drafts and outlines, your presentation slides, and your best work from earlier in\nthe course.\n汇编你的最终研究论⽂、所有草稿和提纲、你的演讲幻灯⽚以及你之前课程中的最佳作品。\n\nWrite a Full Reflective Letter 撰写完整的反思信 (Zhuànxiě wánzhěng de fǎns xìn):\n\n500 words) addressed to your instructor or yourself, detailing your journey through the course and your development\nas a writer and thinker.\n500字）写给你的导师或你⾃⼰，详细说明你在课程中的历程以及你作为写作者和思考者的成⻓。\n\nLooking Ahead 展望未来 (Zhǎnwàng wèilái):\n\nSubmit your Skills Map, outlining your plan to apply these skills in the future.\n\n提交你的技能图谱，概述你未来应⽤这些技能的计划。\n\n\fReferences\nCore Material\n\nAlston, C.S. 2024 . Academic Writing & Nonfiction: G12 Student Book English & Chinese). [online] Notion. Available at:\nhttps://whispering-tibia-11e.notion.site/Academic-Writing-Nonfiction-G12 Student-Book-English-Chinese264926ae7d1b80b6841ced89d2529418\nThe provided Notion site is a detailed curriculum and student guide for a Grade 12 Academic Writing and Nonfiction course.\nIts primary goal is to equip students with the skills to write a sophisticated, university-level research paper. The content is\nbilingual English and Chinese), designed for a target audience of Chinese-speaking students preparing for English-medium\nhigher education.\nThe key principles of the content can be broken down and connected to established academic theory and peer-reviewed\nresearch as follows:\n\nPrinciple 1: The Writing Process as Iterative and Structured\n\nContent Analysis: The guide heavily emphasises a structured, multi-stage writing process. It moves systematically from\n\nfoundational concepts (e.g., \"What is Academic Writing?\") through topic selection, research, outlining, drafting, and\nrevision. This demystifies a complex task and makes it manageable for students.\n\nSupporting Scholarly Justification:\n\nThis approach is strongly supported by the concept of \"Process Writing,\" which has been a dominant pedagogical model\nsince the 1970s. It counters the \"product-focused\" approach that only values the final text.\n\nConnecting Source: Flower, L. and Hayes, J.R. 1981 . A Cognitive Process Theory of Writing. College Composition and\nCommunication, 32 4 , pp.365 387.\nJustification: This seminal article breaks down writing into planning, translating, and reviewing processes, which\nare recursive and interactive. The Notion guide's structure (e.g., separate sections for \"Developing a Research\nQuestion,\" \"Outlining,\" and \"Drafting & Revision\") directly mirrors this cognitive model, teaching students to manage\nthese distinct but overlapping mental tasks.\nConnecting Source: Murray, D.M. 1972 . Teach Writing as a Process Not Product.\nJustification: Murray's famous argument is the philosophical bedrock of this guide. By focusing on stages like\nrevision and multiple drafts, the guide teaches writing as a \"process of discovery\" rather than the mere transcription\nof a pre-formed idea, exactly as Murray advocated.\n\nPrinciple 2: Genre-Based Pedagogy and Rhetorical Awareness\n\nContent Analysis: The guide explicitly teaches the conventions of a specific genre: the academic research paper. It covers\nessential elements like thesis statements, literature reviews, and incorporating sources. The bilingual aspect is crucial here,\nas it addresses the \"contrastive rhetoric\" challenge—helping students navigate the different rhetorical expectations\nbetween Chinese and English academic writing.\nSupporting Scholarly Justification:\nThis aligns with Genre Theory and the pedagogical work of John Swales, who analysed the structural patterns of academic\nwriting.\n\nConnecting Source: Swales, J.M. 1990 . Genre Analysis: English in Academic and Research Settings. Cambridge:\nCambridge University Press.\n\n\fJustification: Swales' concept of the \"Create a Research Space\" CARS) model for research paper introductions is\n\na standard tool for teaching academic writing. The guide's instruction on how to establish context and present a\nthesis is a practical application of this model, helping students understand the moves they need to make to sound\nlike a member of the academic community.\n\nConnecting Source: Connor, U. 1996 . Contrastive Rhetoric: Cross-Cultural Aspects of Second-Language Writing.\n\nCambridge: Cambridge University Press.\nJustification: Connor's work is foundational in understanding how writing conventions differ across cultures. The\nguide's very existence, being bilingual, implicitly acknowledges this challenge. It helps bridge the gap for students\nwhose first language Chinese) may employ different patterns of organisation, argumentation, and writer-reader\nresponsibility.\n\nPrinciple 3: The Importance of Critical Source Engagement\n\nContent Analysis: A significant portion of the guide is dedicated to research skills: evaluating sources, summarising,\nparaphrasing, and quoting effectively. It rightly frames these not as mechanical tasks but as critical engagement with\nexisting scholarship, which is essential for developing a student's own voice and argument.\nSupporting Scholarly Justification:\n\nThis reflects the core academic value of entering a scholarly conversation, a concept popularised by Gerald Graff and\nCathy Birkenstein.\n\nConnecting Source: Graff, G. and Birkenstein, C. 2021 . \"They Say / I Say\": The Moves That Matter in Academic\nWriting. 5th ed. New York: W.W. Norton & Company.\nJustification: The entire premise of Graff and Birkenstein's work is that academic writing is a response to what\nothers have said (\"they say\") so that the writer can then present their own argument (\"I say\"). The guide's focus on\nintegrating sources through summary and paraphrase is a direct method for teaching students how to effectively set\nup this \"they say / I say\" structure.\n\nPrinciple 4: Metacognition and Self-Regulated Learning\n\nContent Analysis: The guide includes elements that encourage students to reflect on their learning process, such as selfassessment checklists and prompts for revision. This fosters metacognition—the ability to think about one's own thinking\nand learning strategies.\n\nSupporting Scholarly Justification:\n\nResearch in educational psychology strongly links metacognitive skills with improved academic performance, particularly in\ncomplex tasks like writing.\n\nConnecting Source: Zimmerman, B.J. 2002 . Becoming a Self-Regulated Learner: An Overview. Theory into Practice,\n41 2 , pp.64 70.\n\nJustification: Zimmerman's model of self-regulated learning involves forethought, performance control, and selfreflection. The guide's structured process encourages forethought (planning, outlining) and performance control\n(drafting). The inclusion of revision guides and self-assessment tools directly promotes the final, crucial phase of\nself-reflection, helping students transition from dependent to independent learners.\n\nSummary\n\nThe Academic Writing & Nonfiction: G12 Student Book is a pedagogically sound resource that aligns with established best\npractices in composition theory. Its structure is supported by Process Writing theory Flower & Hayes; Murray), its focus on\nform by Genre Analysis Swales , its bilingual approach by Contrastive Rhetoric Connor , its research component by the\nconcept of entering a scholarly conversation Graff & Birkenstein), and its reflective elements by theories of SelfRegulated Learning Zimmerman). It effectively prepares students for the demands of university-level academic discourse\nby making its underlying processes and conventions explicit and teachable.\n\n\fAcademic Writing and AI - Nonfiction G11-12 Student Book - English Chinese Feb 2026 (2nd Ed.)",
  "3": "Chapter 3: The Power of a Question\n\n第三章：问题的⼒量 (Wèntí de lìliàng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To understand how the questions we ask shape the answers we\nfind. You will learn to deconstruct essay prompts and generate your own powerful, researchable questions.\n理解我们提出的问题如何塑造我们找到的答案。你将学习解析论⽂提⽰，并⽣成⾃⼰强⼤的、可供研究的问题。\n\nLesson 3.1: The Engine of Inquiry\n第⼀课：探究的引擎 (Tànji\n\nde yǐnqíng)\n\nPart 1: Why Questions Matter\n\n为什么问题重要 (Wèishéme wèntí zhòngyào)\n\nEvery piece of academic writing, every essay, every discovery, begins with a question. The quality of your question\ndetermines the quality of your answer.\n\n每⼀篇学术写作、每⼀篇⽂章、每⼀个发现都始于⼀个问题。你问题的质量决定了你答案的质量。\n\nA poor question leads to a poor answer.\n⼀个差劲的问题会导致⼀个差劲的答案。\n\nWeak Question 薄弱的问题 (Bóruò de wèntí): \"What is climate change?\" This leads to a simple summary, not an\nargument.)\n\n“什么是⽓候变化？”（这会导致简单的总结，⽽不是论证。）\n\nStrong Question 强⼤的问题 (Qiángdà de wèntí): \"To what extent should governments in developing economies be held\nresponsible for reducing carbon emissions, compared to developed nations?\" This leads to a complex, argumentdriven essay.)\n“与发达国家相⽐，发展中国家政府应在多⼤程度上承担减少碳排放的责任？”（这会引出⼀篇复杂的、论证驱动的⽂章。）\n\nYour ability to ask a strong question is your most powerful academic skill.\n提出⼀个强⼤问题的能⼒是你最强⼤的学术技能。\n\nPart 2: Deconstructing Essay Prompts\n\n解析论⽂提⽰ (Jiěx lùnwén tíshì)\n\nBefore you can answer a question, you must understand what it is really asking. Most essay prompts contain a command\n\nword 指令词 (zhǐlìng cí) that tells you what to do.\n\n在回答⼀个问题之前，你必须理解它真正在问什么。⼤多数论⽂提⽰包含⼀个告诉你该做什么的指令词。\n\nMatch the Command Word to Its Meaning 将指令词与其含义匹配:\n\n\fCommand Word 指令词\nZh lìng cí)\n\nWhat It Is Asking You To Do 它要求你做什么\n\nExample 例⼦ (Lìzi)\n\nAnalyze 分析 (F nx )\n\nBreak down a topic into its parts and explain how they\nwork together. 将⼀个主题分解成部分，并解释它们如何协同\n\nAnalyze the impact of social media on political\ncampaigns. 分析社交媒体对政治活动的影响。\n\nCompare & Contrast ⽐较\n与对⽐ (B jiào yǔ duìb )\n\nExamine the similarities and differences between two or\nmore things. 检查两个或更多事物之间的相似性和差异性。\n\nCompare and contrast the economic policies of\ntwo world leaders. ⽐较和对⽐两位世界领导⼈的经\n\nEvaluate 评估 (Píngg )\n\nMake a judgment about the value or success of\nsomething. Provide criteria for your judgment. 对某物的价\n\nEvaluate the effectiveness of the United Nations\nin maintaining global peace. 评估联合国在维护全\n\nArgue 论证 (Lùnzhèng)\n\nTake a position on a debatable topic and support it with\nevidence. 就⼀个可辩论的话题采取⽴场，并⽤证据⽀持它。\n\n(\n\nǐ\n\nǐ\n\nǐ\n\n⼯作。\n\n值或成功做出判断。为你的判断提供标准。\n\n济政策。\n\n球和平⽅⾯的有效性。\n\nArgue for or against the use of animal testing in\nmedical research. 论证⽀持或反对在医学研究中使\n⽤动物试验。\n\nGive a brief overview of the main points of a topic without\nSummarise the key events of the American Civil\nSummarise 总结 (Z ngjié) your own opinion or analysis. 简要概述⼀个主题的要点，不 War. 总结美国内战的关键事件。\nǒ\n\nDefine 定义 (Dìngyì)\n\n要加⼊⾃⼰的观点或分析。\n\nExplain the meaning of a concept, often by outlining its\nDefine the concept of 'sustainable development'\nkey characteristics. 解释⼀个概念的含义，通常通过概述其关 and its core principles. 定义“可持续发展”的概念及\n\n键特征。\n\n其核⼼原则。\n\nFlow Diagram Mind Map: Understanding Command Words\n\n\fHow to Read and Use This Mind Map:\nThe diagram shows a logical flow from basic comprehension to complex critical thinking.\n\nStart at the Top: You begin with a task or question.\nIdentify the Core Instruction: The first step is to identify the key command word in your prompt. This sends you down\nthe correct path.\nFollow the Path:\nDefine & Summarise Left Branch): These are foundational tasks focused on understanding and restating\ninformation. They are often the first step before more complex tasks.\n\n\fAnalyze & Compare & Contrast Center Branch): These are core critical thinking tasks. They require you to dissect\nand examine information. Notice how both of these tasks lead to a new question: \"Now what?\" This is because\n\nanalysis and comparison are often done in order to do something else.\n\nSynthesise and Persuade Right Branch): The most advanced tasks build upon the others.\nEvaluate: After you have analyzed or compared something, you are often in a position to make a judgment about its\nvalue, effectiveness, or success.\n\nArgue: Evaluation naturally leads to argumentation. Once you have formed a judgment, you can take a position and\npersuade others of its validity using the evidence gathered from your analysis, comparison, and evaluation.\nThis map demonstrates that these command words are not isolated; they are interconnected tools for building a strong and\nlogical response.\n\nActivity: Identify the Command 活动：识别指令\n\nFor each prompt below, circle the command word and write what you think you are being asked to do.\n对于下⾯的每个提⽰，圈出指令词并写下你认为被要求做什么。\n\nCritique 评论 the author's use of symbolism in Chapter 3.\nI need to 我需要: _________________________________________________________\nDiscuss 讨论 the causes of the Great Depression.\nI need to 我需要: _________________________________________________________\nTo what extent 在多⼤程度上 do you agree that technology has improved communication?\nI need to 我需要: _________________________________________________________\n\nLesson 3.2: The Power Of Questions\n第⼆课：提出⾃⼰的问题 (Tích\n\nzìj de wèntí)\nǐ\n\nPart 1: The Question Funnel\n\n问题漏⽃ (Wèntí lòudǒu)\n\nHow do you move from a broad topic to a powerful, focused question? You use a Question Funnel 问题漏⽃ (Wèntí lòudǒu).\n你如何从⼀个⼴泛的主题过渡到⼀个强⼤的、聚焦的问题？你可以使⽤问题漏⽃。\n\n\fLet's Practice 让我们练习:\n\nStart with this broad topic: Artificial Intelligence AI ⼈⼯智能\n\nNarrow it down 缩⼩范围: Choose one specific aspect of AI.\n选择⼈⼯智能的⼀个具体⽅⾯。\n\nExample: AI in education, AI and privacy, AI and art, self-driving cars.\nMy narrowed topic 我缩⼩后的主题: _________________________________\nFind a specific issue 找到⼀个具体问题: What is a problem, debate, or recent development within your narrowed topic?\n在你的缩⼩主题中，存在什么问题、争论或最新发展？\n\nExample: How AI grading software affects student learning.\nMy specific issue 我的具体问题: _________________________________\n\n\fForm a research question 形成⼀个研究问题: Use a command word to turn your issue into a question.\n使⽤⼀个指令词将你的问题转化为⼀个问题。\n\nExample: \"Evaluate the effectiveness of AI grading software in providing meaningful feedback to students.\"\nMy research question 我的研究问题: _______________________________\n\nRecap - Choosing a research question\n\nPart 2: Using AI to Fuel Inquiry\n\n使⽤AI助⼒探究 (Shǐyòng AI zhùlì tànji )\n\nAI is a powerful tool for exploring questions. It can help you quickly understand the basics of a complex topic.\nAI是探索问题的强⼤⼯具。它可以帮助你快速理解⼀个复杂主题的基础知识。\nActivity: Question Storming 活动：问题⻛暴 (Wèntí f ngbào)Your Topic 你的主题 (N de zhǔtí): Choose a topic you are\ninterested in (e.g., a hobby, a current event, a historical figure).\nǐ\n\n选择⼀个你感兴趣的主题（例如：爱好、时事、历史⼈物）。\n\nWrite your topic here 在这⾥写下你的主题: _________________________________\nOpen Perplexity or DeepSeek. Ask it: \"What are some current debates or unanswered questions about [your topic]?\"\n打开Perplexity或DeepSeek。询问它：“关于[你的主题]⽬前有哪些争论或未解答的问题？”\n\nSkim the results 浏览结果. Find one or two questions that seem interesting and complex.\n找到⼀两个看起来有趣且复杂的问题。\n\nWrite them below 在下⾯写下它们:\nQuestion 1 问题⼀: _________________________________________________________\nQuestion 2 问题⼆: _________________________________________________________\nReflect 反思: Which of these questions could be the basis for a good essay? Why?\n哪个问题可以成为⼀篇好⽂章的基础？为什么？\n\nPart 3: The \"So What?\" Test\n\n“那⼜怎样？”测试 (“Nà yòu zěnyàng?” cèshì)\n\nA good academic question must pass the \"So What?\" test. If your question is answered, does it matter? Does it have\nimplications?\n⼀个好的学术问题必须通过“那⼜怎样？”测试。如果你的问题得到了解答，它重要吗？它具有意义吗？\n\n\fFails the Test 未通过测试: \"How many planets are in our solar system?\" The answer is a fact; it doesn't lead to debate\nor deeper understanding.)\n\n“太阳系有多少颗⾏星？”（答案是⼀个事实；它不会引发辩论或更深的理解。\n）\n\nPasses the Test 通过测试: \"How should we define a planet, and what does the debate over Pluto's status tell us about\nthe nature of scientific classification?\" The answer has implications for how we understand science itself.)\n\n“我们应如何定义⾏星，关于冥王星地位的争论告诉我们科学分类的什么本质？”（答案对我们理解科学本⾝具有意义。\n）\n\nApply the Test 应⽤测试: Look back at the research question you wrote in Part 1.\n回头看你在第⼀部分写的研究问题。\n\nAsk yourself 问⾃⼰: \"So what? Why does the answer to this question matter?\"\n\n“那⼜怎样？这个问题的答案为什么重要？”\n\nWrite your answer 写下你的答案:\n\n_________________________________________________________\n\nIf you can't answer the \"So what?\" clearly, you may need to refine your question to make it more significant.\n如果你不能清晰地回答“那⼜怎样？”，你可能需要改进你的问题，使其更重要。\n\nHomework: The Art of the Question\n\n作业：提问的艺术 (Tíwèn de yìshù)\n\nTask 1: Deconstruct 解构\nLook at the essay prompts below. For each one:\n\n在⽹上或从其他课程中找到两个论⽂提⽰。对于每个提⽰：\n\nCircle the command word. 圈出指令词。\n\nParaphrase what the prompt is asking you to do. 解释该提⽰要求你做什么。\n\nExample\n\nAnalyze how the narrative structure of a non-linear novel (such as Slaughterhouse-Five by Kurt Vonnegut or The God of\nSmall Things by Arundhati Roy) contributes to the development of its central themes.\n\n1.\n\nCircle the command word: Analyze\nParaphrase: This prompt asks me to break down the complex narrative structure of a chosen novel (one that doesn't\n\ntell the story in a straight chronological line). I need to examine its components (e.g., flashbacks, time jumps, parallel\nstorylines) and explain in detail how this specific structure shapes, reinforces, and deepens the reader's understanding\nof the book's main ideas or messages.\n\nYour Turn\n\n2. Compare and contrast the economic policies of Keynesianism and Monetarism, focusing on their core principles, their\napproaches to government intervention, and their proposed solutions for managing inflation.\n3. Evaluate the effectiveness of international sanctions as a tool for compelling political change in authoritarian regimes.\nSupport your position with specific historical or contemporary examples.\n4. Argue for or against the proposition that advancements in artificial intelligence and automation will ultimately lead to a net\nincrease in societal well-being, rather than widespread unemployment and inequality.\n\n\f5. Summarise the central arguments of Thomas Hobbes' Leviathan regarding the necessity of a powerful sovereign, and\nexplain how his view of the \"state of nature\" justifies this conclusion.\n6. Drawing from philosophical and sociological sources, define the concept of \"social capital.\" In your essay, differentiate it\nfrom other forms of capital (e.g., economic, cultural) and discuss its role in fostering community resilience.\n\nTask 2: Create 创造\nChoose one of the broad topics below and use the Question Funnel to create one strong, argument-driven research\nquestion.\n从下⾯的⼴泛主题中选择⼀个，使⽤问题漏⽃创建⼀个强⼤的、论证驱动的研究问题。\n\nBroad Topics ⼴泛主题:\nSocial Media 社交媒体,\nClimate Change ⽓候变化,\nGlobalisation 全球化,\nEducation Technology 教育科技,\nMental Health ⼼理健康\n\nMy Chosen Topic 我选择的主题: _________________________________\nMy Research Question 我的研究问题: _______________________________\n\nTask 3: Evaluate 评估\nRun your research question through the \"So What?\" test. Explain why the answer matters.\n⽤“那⼜怎样？”测试来检验你的研究问题。解释为什么答案很重要。\n\nExample Example Homework: The Question Craft – Grading Rubric & Example\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points.\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nTask 1 Deconstruct\nPrompts\n\nAll command words are\ncorrectly identified.\nParaphrases are accurate,\ninsightful, and demonstrate a\n\nCommand words are\ncorrectly identified.\nParaphrases are\n\nSome command words\nare misidentified.\nParaphrases are vague\nor partially inaccurate.\n\nNeeds Improvement 0 4\npts)\nCommand words are\nlargely incorrect.\nParaphrases are missing,",
  "4": "Chapter 4: The Power of Good Logic\n\n第四章：逻辑的⼒量 I Luójí de lìliàng I\n\n\fYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To identify the most common logical fallacies that weaken\narguments. You will learn to spot flawed reasoning in others' writing and avoid it in your own.\n\n识别削弱论证的最常⻅逻辑谬误。你将学会在别⼈的写作中发现有缺陷的推理，并在⾃⼰的写作中避免它。\n\nLesson 4.1: Why Logic Matters\n\n第⼀课：为什么逻辑重要 (Wèishéme luójí zhòngyào)\n\nWhat is logic?\n\nAt its core, logic is the study of correct reasoning. It provides a systematic framework for distinguishing good arguments\nfrom bad ones.\nThink of it as the \"science of correct thinking.\"\nIt doesn't primarily focus on what people actually think (that's psychology) or what is factually true (that's the sciences),\nbut rather on whether a conclusion comes from a correct line of thinking.\n\nPart 1: The Architecture of Argument\n论证的架构 (Lùnzhèng de jiàgòu)\n\nThink back to our metaphor: writing is architecture. If your evidence 证据 (zhèngjù) and explanation 解释 (jiěshì) are the\nbricks and mortar of your paragraph, then logic 逻辑 (luójí) is the foundation. It's what holds your entire argument together\nand makes it strong enough to withstand criticism.\nWeak logic is like a weak foundation. Your whole argument can collapse.\n\nPart 2: What is a Logical Fallacy?\n\n什么是逻辑谬误？(Shénme shì luójí miùwù?)\n\nA logical fallacy 逻辑谬误 (luójí miùwù) is an error in thinking. It's a flaw in the structure of an argument that makes it\ninvalid, misleading, or unfair. Fallacies often seem persuasive because they appeal to our emotions or biases, but they don't\nprovide good evidence for a claim.\nLearning about fallacies is like learning the tricks of a magician. Once you know how the trick works, you can't be fooled by\nit anymore.\n\nCommon types of faulty logic (logical fallacies).\n1.\n\nHasty Generalisation\n\nDefinition: Drawing a broad conclusion based on a small, unrepresentative, or insufficient sample size.\nBad Logic: \"My two roommates from Country X were messy, so everyone from Country X is messy.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: It makes a sweeping generalization about an entire population based on only two examples, which are\nnot necessarily representative.\n2.\n\nAd Hominem (Against the Person)\n\nDefinition: Attacking the character, motive, or other personal attributes of the person making an argument instead of\naddressing the substance of the argument itself.\nBad Logic: \"Dr. Smith argues for climate change action, but he was divorced last year, so his opinion can't be trusted.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: The personal life of the speaker is irrelevant to the scientific evidence for climate change. The\nargument is dismissed based on who said it, not on its merits.\n3.\n\nStraw Man\n\n\fDefinition: Misrepresenting, exaggerating, or oversimplifying an opponent's argument to make it easier to attack.\nBad Logic:\n\nPerson A \"We should consider more funding for renewable energy sources.\"\nPerson B \"So you want to shut down all coal plants tomorrow and leave thousands unemployed? That's a terrible\nplan.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: Person B has distorted Person A's moderate proposal into an extreme, unrealistic position that is easy\nto criticize.\n\n4. False Cause (Post Hoc Ergo Propter Hoc)\n\nDefinition: Assuming that because one event occurred after another, the first event must have caused the second.\nBad Logic: \"I wore my lucky socks and then aced my exam. Therefore, my lucky socks caused me to ace the exam.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: It confuses correlation with causation. The two events happened sequentially, but there is no proven\ncausal link; studying was the more likely cause.\n\n5. Slippery Slope\n\nDefinition: Arguing that a relatively small first step will inevitably lead to a chain of related (and extreme) negative events.\nBad Logic: \"If we allow students to redo this assignment, next they'll demand to redo every assignment, and then they'll\nexpect to pass the course without doing any work, completely destroying academic standards.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: It presents a series of hypothetical events as an inevitable outcome without evidence for each step in\nthe chain.\n\n6. Appeal to Authority\n\nDefinition: Using the opinion of an authority figure as evidence for an argument in an area outside of their expertise.\nBad Logic: \"A famous actor and action star endorses this brand of vitamins, so it must be the most scientifically\neffective.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: The actor is an authority on acting, not on nutrition or biochemistry. Their endorsement is not valid\nevidence for the product's efficacy.\n\n7. False Dilemma (Either/Or Fallacy)\n\nDefinition: Presenting only two possible options or outcomes when in reality there are more nuances or alternatives.\nBad Logic: \"You're either with us in this war, or you're with the terrorists.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: It frames a complex geopolitical issue as a binary choice, ignoring the possibility of neutral stances,\ndiplomatic solutions, or other alternatives.\n\n8. Circular Reasoning (Begging the Question)\n\nDefinition: An argument where the conclusion is implicitly or explicitly assumed in one of the premises. It restates the claim\nrather than proving it.\nBad Logic: \"The Bible is the word of God because it says so in the Bible.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: The argument offers no independent evidence; it simply uses the claim itself as proof for the claim.\n\n9. Red Herring\n\nDefinition: Introducing an irrelevant topic or piece of evidence to divert attention from the original issue.\nBad Logic:\n\nPerson A \"The mayor's economic policy has failed to reduce unemployment.\"\nPerson B \"But let's not forget that the mayor volunteers at an animal shelter on weekends. He's a good man.\"\n\n\fWhy it's Faulty: The mayor's character is a distraction from the specific criticism of his economic policy.\n\n10. Appeal to Emotion\n\nDefinition: Manipulating an emotional response (pity, fear, anger, nationalism) in place of a valid or compelling argument.\nBad Logic: \"This university should not cut the arts program. Think of the sad, disappointed children who will never get\nto paint again.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: While the emotional appeal is powerful, a strong argument should focus on the educational value, costbenefit analysis, or statistical impact of the arts program, not just the emotional reaction to its loss.\n\n11. Bandwagon Fallacy (Appeal to Popularity)\n\nDefinition: Arguing that a claim must be true or good simply because it is popular or many people believe it.\nBad Logic: \"Millions of people believe that crystal healing works, so it must be a valid medical treatment.\"\nWhy it's Faulty: Popularity is not proof. The truth of a claim is determined by evidence and logic, not by the number of\npeople who believe it.\n\nBy recognising and avoiding these common fallacies, you can strengthen your academic writing, making your arguments\nmore logical, credible, and persuasive.\n\nLesson 4.2: Spotting Two Common Fallacies\n\n第⼆课：识别两种常⻅谬误 (Shíbié liǎng zhǒng chángjiàn miùwù)\n\nPart 1: Fallacy #1 - Hasty Generalization\n\n谬误 #1 - 草率结论 (Cǎoshuài jiélùn)\n\nWhat it is 是什么: Making a broad claim based on a very small or unrepresentative sample. You are jumping to a conclusion\nwithout enough evidence.\n基于⼀个⾮常⼩或不具代表性的样本得出⼀个⼴泛的主张。你在没有⾜够证据的情况下草率得出结论。\n\nIn simple terms 简单来说: Stereotyping. Assuming what is true for one is true for all.\n刻板印象。认为对⼀个⼈是真的，对所有⼈也是真的。\nEveryday Example ⽇常例⼦:\n\nI met two rude people from City X. Everyone from City X must be rude.\"\nX市的粗鲁的⼈。所有来⾃X市的⼈⼀定都很粗鲁。”\n\n\"\n\n“我遇到了两个来⾃\n\nThis one study says this product works. Therefore, it is proven to work for everyone.\"\nHow to avoid it 如何避免: Use qualifiers like \"may,\" \"often,\"\n\"sometimes,\" or \"in some cases.\" Make sure your evidence is sufficient and representative.\n\"\n\n“这⼀项研究说这个产品有效。因此，它被证明对所有⼈都有效。\n”\n\n使⽤限定词，如“可能”、“通常”、“有时”或“在某些情况下”。确保你的证据是充分且具有代表性的。\n\nResources\nCategory 1: Educational Resources (Defining the Fallacy with Clear Examples)\nThese are excellent for understanding the core concept with simple, constructed examples.\nYourLogicalFallacyIs.com: Hasty Generalization\n\n\fLink: https://yourlogicalfallacyis.com/hasty-generalization\nWhat it demonstrates: This site provides a very concise, easy-to-understand definition and a simple, classic\n\nexample: \"Someone who meets three people from a foreign country and finds them to be quiet and reserved may\nthen conclude that all people from that country are quiet and reserved.\"\n\nThe Fallacy Files: Hasty Generalization\nLink: http://www.fallacyfiles.org/hastygen.html\nWhat it demonstrates: This resource goes into more philosophical depth, explaining the difference between\ninductive generalization and the fallacious \"hasty\" version. It uses historical and literary examples.\n\nPurdue Online Writing Lab OWL Logical Fallacies\nLink: https://owl.purdue.edu/owl/general_writing/academic_writing/logic_in_argumentative_writing/fallacies.html\nWhat it demonstrates: While it covers many fallacies, it includes Hasty Generalization (sometimes under \"Faulty\n\nGeneralization\") with clear academic examples, such as making a broad claim based on a small or unrepresentative\nsample.\n\nCategory 2: Analysis and Opinion Pieces (Real-World Examples)\nThese articles analyze real-world rhetoric and point out where Hasty Generalization occurs, often in politics, media, and\nsocial discourse.\n\nThe Guardian: \"How to spot a hasty generalization – and how to stop making them\"\nLink: https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/mar/26/how-to-spot-a-hasty-generalisation-and-how-tostop-making-them\n\nWhat it demonstrates: This article directly addresses the fallacy in everyday life, discussing how we use it about\nplaces, groups of people, and even in our self-talk. It's a practical guide to recognizing the pattern.\nPsychology Today: \"The Hasty Generalization Fallacy\"\nLink: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/thoughts-thinking/202009/the-hasty-generalization-fallacy\nWhat it demonstrates: This piece connects the logical fallacy to cognitive psychology, explaining how our brains\nare wired to make quick generalizations and how this can lead to errors in judgment, stereotypes, and prejudice.\n\nLogically Fallacious: Hasty Generalization Entry\nLink: https://www.logicallyfallacious.com/logicalfallacies/Hasty-Generalization\nWhat it demonstrates: This site is a comprehensive encyclopedia of fallacies. Its entry on Hasty Generalization\n\nprovides multiple real-world examples, such as \"My grandfather smoked four packs of cigarettes a day since age\nfourteen and lived until age ninety-two. Therefore, smoking really canʼt be that bad for you.\"\n\nCategory 3: Video Explanations (For Visual Learners)\nSometimes, seeing the fallacy in action is the best way to learn.\n\nKhan Academy: \"Hasty Generalization\"\nLink: https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/wi-phi/critical-thinking/v/hasty-generalization\nWhat it demonstrates: This short, animated video clearly explains the fallacy with simple examples, making it\nperfect for students or anyone new to the concept.\n\nHow to Find More Examples Yourself:\nSearch News Sites: Look on sites like The New York Times, The Atlantic, or BBC for articles analyzing political\n\nspeeches, marketing claims, or social media trends. Opinion and analysis sections are where you'll most often find\nfallacy breakdowns.\n\nUse Specific Search Terms: Try searches like:\n\"Hasty generalization in politics example\"\n\n\f\"News article about stereotyping as hasty generalization\"\n\"Analysis of Political Figure's] speech logical fallacies\"\n\nFact-Checking Websites: Sites like Snopes.com or PolitiFact.com often deconstruct claims by pointing out flawed\nreasoning, including hasty generalizations based on insufficient evidence.\nBy reviewing these resources, you'll see that Hasty Generalization is everywhere, from a casual conversation about \"all\npoliticians\" to a news segment making a sweeping claim about a generation. The key is recognizing when a conclusion is\ndrawn from a sample that is too small, biased, or unrepresentative to support it.\n\nPart 2: Fallacy #2 - Loaded Language (LL)\n谬误 #2 - 煽动性语⾔ (Sh ndòng xìng yǔyán)\n\nWhat it is 是什么: Using words with strong positive or negative emotions (connotations) to manipulate an audience instead\nof using facts and reason.\n\n使⽤带有强烈积极或消极情绪（内涵）的词语来操纵听众，⽽不是使⽤事实和理性。\n\nIn simple terms 简单来说: Using slanted or biased words to make something seem better or worse than it is.\n使⽤带有倾向性或偏⻅的词语，使某事看起来⽐实际更好或更糟。\n\nEveryday Example ⽇常例⼦:\nLogic Fallacy: \"My opponent supports the disastrous and heartless policy that will destroy our community.\"\nCorrect Logic: Instead of: \"My opponent supports the policy, which I believe will have negative consequences.\")\n\n“我的对⼿⽀持将会摧毁我们社区的灾难性且⽆情的政策。”（⽽不是：“我的对⼿⽀持该政策，我认为这会带来负⾯后果。”）\n\n\"We must pass this common-sense, patriotic bill for the sake of our children.\"\nInstead of presenting the bill's actual benefits.)\n“为了我们的孩⼦，我们必须通过这项常识性的、爱国的法案。”（⽽不是展⽰法案的实际好处。）\n\nHow to avoid it 如何避免: Use neutral, factual language. Let your evidence create feeling, not your adjectives.\n使⽤中⽴的、事实性的语⾔。让你的证据来创造感觉，⽽不是你的形容词。\nPart 3: Practice: Spot the Fallacy\n练习：发现谬误 (Liànxí: F xiàn miùwù)\n\nInstructions 说明: For each statement below, identify which fallacy being used: Hasty Generalisation HG or Loaded\nLanguage LL .\n对于下⾯的每个陈述，识别所使⽤的谬误：草率结论 (HG) 或 煽动性语⾔ (LL)。\n\"I got food poisoning from one sushi restaurant. I'm never eating sushi again.\"\n“我在⼀家寿司店⾷物中毒了。我再也不吃寿司了。”\n\nFallacy 谬误: _______________________________________\n\"The politician's radical, un-American proposal will crush the dreams of hardworking families.\"\n“这位政客激进的、⾮美国的提案将粉碎勤劳家庭的梦想。”\n\nFallacy 谬误: _______________________________________\n\n\"Everyone knows that social media is a toxic waste of time.\"\n“每个⼈都知道社交媒体是⼀种有毒的浪费时间。”\n\nFallacy 谬误: _______________________________________ (Hint 提⽰: Which words are \"loaded\"? 哪些词是“煽动性的”？)\n\n\"My grandfather smoked a pack a day and lived to be 100. Therefore, smoking isn't bad for you.\"\n“我的祖⽗每天抽⼀包烟，活到了100岁。因此，吸烟对你没有坏处。”\n\n\fFallacy 谬误: _______________________________________\n\nLesson 4.3: Applying Logic to Your Writing\n\n第三课：将逻辑应⽤于写作 (Ji ng luójí yìngyòng yú xiězuò)\n\nPart 1: Revise the Fallacies\n\n修改谬误 (Xi gǎi miùwù)\n\nNow, let's fix the examples from the previous exercise. Rewrite each statement to make it logical and fair.\n现在，让我们修改上⼀练习中的例⼦。重写每个陈述，使其变得逻辑且公平。\n\nOriginal 原句: \"I got food poisoning from one sushi restaurant. I'm never eating sushi again.\"\nRevised 修改后: _________________________________________________________\n\nOriginal 原句: \"The politician's radical, un-American proposal will crush the dreams of hardworking families.\"\nRevised 修改后: _________________________________________________________\n\nPart 2: Analyze a Real-World Argument\n\n分析现实世界的论证 (F nx xiànshí shìjiè de lùnzhèng)\n\nFind a short opinion piece, social media post, or comment online.\n\n找⼀篇短评、社交媒体帖⼦或在线评论。\n\nPaste or describe it here 在这⾥粘贴或描述它:\nAnalyze it 分析它:\nDoes it contain Hasty Generalisation? How? 它是否包含草率结论？如何体现的？\n\nDoes it use Loaded Language? Which words? 它是否使⽤了煽动性语⾔？哪些词？\n\nIs the argument logically strong? Why or why not? 这个论证在逻辑上强⼤吗？为什么？\n\nHomework: Fallacy Detective\n\n作业：谬误侦探 (Miùwù zh ntàn)\n\nTask 1: Find and Identify 发现与识别\nOver the next day, be a \"Fallacy Detective.\" Listen to conversations, read headlines, or scroll through social media.\n在接下来的⼀天⾥，成为⼀名“谬误侦探”。倾听对话，阅读头条新闻，或浏览社交媒体。\n\nFind one example of Hasty Generalisation and one example of Loaded Language. Write them down below.\n找到⼀个草率结论的例⼦和⼀个煽动性语⾔的例⼦。把它们写在下⾯。\n\nHasty Generalisation Example 草率结论例⼦:\nLoaded Language Example 煽动性语⾔例⼦:\n\nTask 2: Revise and Improve 修改与改进\nChoose one of the examples you found above and rewrite it to remove the logical fallacy and make it a stronger, more\n\n\ffactual statement.\n\n选择你上⾯找到的⼀个例⼦，重写它，消除逻辑谬误，使其成为⼀个更强⼤、更符合事实的陈述。\n\nMy Revised Statement 我修改后的陈述:\n\nTask 3: Reflect 反思\nWhy is it important to avoid these fallacies in your own academic writing?\n\n在你⾃⼰学术写作中避免这些谬误为什么很重要？\n\nExample Homework: The Fallacy Detective – Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points.\n\nGrading Rubric\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nTask 1 Find &\nIdentify\n\nBoth examples are clear, realworld instances of the specified\nfallacies. Identification is correct\nand includes a brief explanation\nof why the statement is\nfallacious.\n\nExamples are relevant\nOne example may be weak Examples are missing,\nand correctly identified.\nor incorrectly identified.\nincorrectly identified,\nExplanation is present but\nExplanation is vague.\nor not actual fallacies.\ncould be more detailed.\n\nTask 2 Revise &\nImprove\n\nRevised statements are logical,\nfair, and remove all fallacious\nreasoning. They maintain the\noriginal intent but use evidencebased, nuanced language.\n\nRevised statements\ncorrect the fallacy and\nare logical. They may still\nbe somewhat simplistic.\n\nRevision attempts to\ncorrect the fallacy but is\nincomplete or introduces\nnew logical issues.\n\nRevision is missing, or\nthe statement remains\nfallacious.\n\nTask 3 Reflect\n\nReflection demonstrates a deep,\npersonal understanding of why\navoiding fallacies is critical for\nacademic credibility and ethical\nargumentation.\n\nReflection adequately\nexplains the importance\nof avoiding fallacies in\nacademic writing.\n\nReflection is vague or\ngeneric, lacking personal\nconnection or specific\ninsight.\n\nReflection is missing\nor irrelevant.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\nTask 1: Find and Identify\n\nHasty Generalization Example:\nHeadline from social media \"I saw two teenagers littering in the park today. Kids these days have no respect for the\nenvironment.\"\nIdentification: This is a Hasty Generalization. The speaker draws a sweeping conclusion about all \"kids these days\" based\non the behaviour of only two individuals.\nLoaded Language Example:\nFrom a political comment thread \"My opponent's dangerous, radical plan will bankrupt hardworking families and destroy\nour community's way of life.\"\n:\n\n:",
  "5": "Chapter 5: The Power of Sound Logic II & RADAR\n第五章：逻辑的⼒量 II 与RADAR Luójí de lìliàng II yǔ RADAR\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To master two more logical fallacies and learn the RADAR\nmethod for evaluating the credibility of your sources. A strong argument is built on sound logic and reliable evidence.\n掌握另外两种逻辑谬误，并学习⽤于评估来源可信度的RADAR⽅法。⼀个强⼤的论证建⽴在可靠的逻辑和可靠的证据之上。\n\nLesson 5.1: Two More Tricks of the Trade\n第⼀课：另外两个逻辑陷阱 (Lìngwài liǎng gè luójí xiànjǐng)\n\nActivity:\n\nPresent students with to choices of home work. One has 2 questions, one had 10 question. “Which one would you like?”\n\nPart 1: Fallacy #3 - Either/Or (False Dilemma)\n\n谬误 #3 - ⾮此即彼（错误困境）(F i cǐ jí bǐ Cuòwù kùnjìng))\n\nWhat it is 是什么: Presenting only two possible options or outcomes when there are actually many more. It forces a blackand-white choice on a complex, grey issue.\n\n当实际上存在更多可能性时，只呈现两种可能的选择或结果。它在⼀个复杂的、灰⾊的问题上强加了⼀个⾮⿊即⽩的选择。\n\nIn simple terms 简单来说: \"You're either with us, or against us.\" False simplicity.\n“你要么与我们为伍，要么与我们为敌。”错误的简单化。\nEveryday Example ⽇常例⼦:\n\n\"You either support completely free speech for everyone, no matter what, or you're a supporter of censorship.\" - With\nus or against us statement - This is how wars start.\n“你要么⽀持完全⾃由的⾔论，⽆论如何，要么你就是审查制度的⽀持者。”\n\n\"We must either drastically cut taxes or our economy will collapse completely.\"\n“我们要么⼤幅削减税收，要么我们的经济就会彻底崩溃。”\n\n\fHow to avoid it 如何避免: Acknowledge the complexity of issues. Use phrases like \"we could consider,\" \"another option\nmight be,\" or \"we must balance.\"\n\n承认问题的复杂性。使⽤诸如“我们可以考虑”、“另⼀种选择可能是”或“我们必须平衡”之类的短语。\n\nPart 2: Fallacy #4 - Slippery Slope\n\n谬误 #4 - 滑坡谬误 (Huáp\n\nmiùwù)\nWhat it is 是什么: Arguing that a relatively small first step will inevitably lead to a chain of related (and terrible) events,\nwithout providing evidence for this chain reaction.\n认为⼀个相对较⼩的第⼀步将不可避免地导致⼀系列相关的（且可怕的）事件，⽽没有为这种连锁反应提供证据。\n\nIn simple terms 简单来说: \"If we let this happen, then that will happen, and then something terrible will happen!\" A\nprediction of doom without proof. - Causal gap.\n\n“如果我们让这件事发⽣，那么那件事就会发⽣，然后可怕的事情就会发⽣！”没有证据的厄运预测。\n\nEveryday Example ⽇常例⼦:\n\n\"If we allow students to use calculators in math class, they will forget how to do basic arithmetic. Then they won't be\nable to balance their checkbooks, and the entire financial system will collapse!\"\n“如果我们允许学⽣在数学课上使⽤计算器，他们就会忘记如何做基本算术。然后他们将⽆法平衡他们的⽀票簿，整个⾦融体系就\n会崩溃！”\n\n\"If we pass this law to regulate one type of weapon, soon the government will take all our guns away, and we'll be\nunable to defend ourselves from tyranny.\"\n“如果我们通过这项法律来管制⼀种武器，很快政府就会没收我们所有的枪⽀，我们将⽆法保卫⾃⼰免受暴政。”\n\nHow to avoid it 如何避免: Focus on the direct consequences of an action. Don't make extreme predictions about the far\nfuture without strong, logical evidence for each step in the chain.\n关注⼀个⾏为的直接后果。如果没有强有⼒的、逻辑上的证据来证明链条中的每⼀步，就不要对遥远的未来做出极端预测。\n\nPart 3: Practice: Spot the New Fallacies\n练习：发现新的谬误 (Liànxí: F xiàn x n de miùwù)\n\nInstructions 说明: For each statement below, identify which fallacy is being used: Either/Or EO or Slippery Slope SS .\n对于下⾯的每个陈述，识别所使⽤的谬误：⾮此即彼 (EO) 或 滑坡谬误 (SS)。\n\n\"If you don't get straight A's, you will never get into a good college or get a good job.\"\n“如果你没有全科得A，你就永远进不了好⼤学，也找不到好⼯作。”\nFallacy 谬误: _________\n\n\"We can either invest all our money in renewable energy right now, or we can watch the planet become uninhabitable.\"\n“我们要么现在就把所有的钱都投资于可再⽣能源，要么就眼睁睁地看着地球变得⽆法居住。”\nFallacy 谬误: _________\n\n\"If we start reading this one book that challenges our ideas, soon we won't believe in anything at all, and society will fall\napart.\"\n“如果我们开始阅读这本挑战我们想法的书，很快我们就会什么都不相信，社会就会分崩离析。”\nFallacy 谬误: _________\n\n\"You have a choice: agree with my plan entirely, or you are responsible for this project's failure.\"\n“你有⼀个选择：完全同意我的计划，或者你对这个项⽬的失败负责。”\nFallacy 谬误: _________\n\nLesson 5.2: Your Source Evaluation Toolkit - RADAR\n第⼆课：你的来源评估⼯具 - RADAR Nǐ de láiyuán píngg\n\ng ngjù - RADAR\n\n\fYou've learned to make your own logic strong. Now, you must learn to check the logic and reliability of the sources you use\nfor evidence.\n你已经学会让⾃⼰的逻辑变得严密。现在，你必须学会检查你所使⽤的证据来源的逻辑性和可靠性。\n\nPart 1: What is RADAR?\n\n什么是RADAR？ Shénme shì RADAR?\n\nRADAR is a set of criteria for deciding if a source (a website, article, book, video) is trustworthy and good enough to use in\nyour academic work.\nRADAR是⼀套标准，⽤于判断⼀个来源（⽹站、⽂章、书籍、视频）是否值得信赖且⾜够好，可以⽤于你的学术⼯作。\nIt stands for 它代表:\n\nRelevance 相关性\nAuthority 权威性\nDate ⽇期\nAppearance 外观\nReason for writing 写作原因\n\n\fAcademic Writing and AI - Nonfiction G11-12 Student Book - English Chinese Feb 2026 (2nd Ed.)\n\n\fPart 2: Using the RADAR Checklist\n\n使⽤RADAR检查清单 (Shǐyòng RADAR jiǎnchá q ngd n)\n\nLet's break down what each letter means:\n让我们分解每个字⺟的含义：\n\nR Relevance 相关性:\n\nHow is this information related to my thesis? Who is the intended audience? Is it too simple or too advanced for my\nneeds?\n这些信息与我的论⽂有何关联？⽬标受众是谁？对我的需求来说是否太简单或太⾼级？\n\nA Authority 权威性:\n\nWho is the author/publisher? What are their credentials (education, experience)? Are they an expert in this field?\n作者/出版商是谁？他们的 credentials（教育背景、经验）是什么？他们是这个领域的专家吗？\n\nD Date ⽇期:\n\nWhen was this published? Is the information current enough for my topic? For a science topic, you need very new\nsources. For a history topic, older sources might be okay.\n\n这是什么时候发布的？这些信息对我的主题来说是否⾜够新？对于科学主题，你需要⾮常新的来源。对于历史主题，旧的来源可\n能也可以。\n\nA Appearance 外观:\n\nDoes the source look professional? Is it well-written and free of errors? Does it cite its own sources? Does it have\nspelling mistakes or look sloppy?\n这个来源看起来专业吗？它写得好吗？没有错误吗？它引⽤它⾃⼰的来源了吗？有拼写错误或看起来⻢虎吗？\n\nR Reason for Writing 写作原因:\n\nWhy was this source created? To inform, teach, sell, persuade, or entertain? Is it objective or biased?\n\n这个来源为什么被创建？是为了告知、教导、销售、说服还是娱乐？它是客观的还是带有偏⻅的？\n\nLesson 5.3: Putting It All Together\n\n第三课：综合应⽤ (Zònghé yìngyòng)\n\nPart 1: Practice: Evaluate with RADAR\n\n练习：⽤RADAR评估 (Liànxí: Yòng RADAR píngg )\n\nInstructions 说明: Imagine you are writing an essay on \"The Effects of Social Media on Mental Health.\" You found the\nfollowing source. Evaluate it using the RADAR criteria.\n假设你正在写⼀篇关于“社交媒体对⼼理健康的影响”的⽂章。你找到了以下来源。使⽤RADAR标准评估它。\nSource: A blog post titled \"SOCIAL MEDIA IS A CANCER ON THE SOUL OF OUR YOUTH!\" written by a famous lifestyle\ninfluencer on her personal website. It is full of strong opinions and emotional stories from her followers, but no links to\nscientific studies. It was published last month.\n\n来源： ⼀篇博⽂，标题为“社交媒体是我们⻘年灵魂的毒瘤！”，由⼀位著名⽣活⽅式影响者在她的个⼈⽹站上撰写。⽂章充满了强烈\n的观点和来⾃她粉丝的情感故事，但没有链接到科学研究。它于上个⽉发布。\n\nRelevance 相关性: Is it relevant to the topic\nNotes 笔记:\nAuthority 权威性: Is the author an expert on mental health\nNotes 笔记:\nDate ⽇期: Is it current\nNotes 笔记:\nAppearance 外观: Does it look professional and well researched\nNotes 笔记:\n? ______\n\n_________________________________________\n\n? ______\n\n_________________________________________\n? ______\n\n_________________________________________\n-\n\n? ______\n\n_________________________________________\n\n\fReason 写作原因: Why was it written? To inform, persuade, sell? ______\nNotes 笔记: _________________________________________\nVerdict 最终判断: Would this be a good, credible source for your academic essay? YES / NO\nFinal Reasoning 最终理由: _________________________________________\n\nHomework: The Logical Detective\n作业：逻辑侦探 (Luójí zh ntàn)\n\nTask 1: Find the Fallacies 发现谬误\nFind one example of Either/Or and one example of Slippery Slope in the real world (news, social media, conversation).\n在现实世界（新闻、社交媒体、对话）中找到⼀个⾮此即彼的例⼦和⼀个滑坡谬误的例⼦。\n\nEither/Or Example ⾮此即彼例⼦:\n\nSlippery Slope Example 滑坡谬误例⼦:\n\nTask 2: Be a RADAR Analyst 成为⼀名RADAR分析师\nFind two different sources online about a topic you are interested in. One should be credible, one should be unreliable.\n\n在⽹上找到关于你感兴趣的主题的两个不同来源。⼀个应该是可信的，⼀个应该是不可靠的。\n\nApply the RADAR checklist to both. Write a short paragraph explaining which source is better for academic use and why.\n对两者应⽤RADAR检查清单。写⼀段短⽂，解释哪个来源更适合学术⽤途以及原因。\n\nSource 1 Good or Bad? _______________________________________\nRADAR Analysis RADAR分析: ____________________________________\nSource 2 Good or Bad? _______________________________________\nRADAR Analysis RADAR分析: ____________________________________\nWhich is better? 哪个更好? _______________________________________\nWhy? 为什么? ____________________________________________________\n\nTask 3: Reflect 反思\n\nWhy is it just as important to evaluate your sources as it is to make your own logic strong?\n\n为什么评估你的来源和你让⾃⼰的逻辑变得严密⼀样重要？\n\nExample Homework: The Logical Analyst – Grading Rubric & Example\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points.\n\nGrading Rubric\n\n\fSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nTask 1 Find the\nFallacies\n\nBoth examples are clear, realworld instances of Either/Or and\nSlippery Slope fallacies.\nIdentification is correct and\nincludes a brief explanation.\n\nExamples are relevant and One example may be weak\ncorrectly identified.\nor incorrectly identified.\nExplanation is present.\nExplanation is vague.\n\nExamples are missing\nor incorrectly identified.\n\nTask 2 Be a\nRADAR Analyst\n\nBoth sources are clearly credible\nor unreliable. The RADAR\nanalysis is thorough for all five\ncriteria. The paragraph\nconvincingly explains which\nsource is better and why, using\nspecific RADAR points.\n\nBoth sources are analysed\nwith RADAR. The\nparagraph correctly\nidentifies the better\nsource with logical\nreasoning.\n\nRADAR analysis is\nmissing or incorrect.\nThe comparison is\nabsent or illogical.\n\nTask 3 Reflect\n\nReflection thoughtfully connects\nthe skills of spotting fallacies\nand evaluating sources,\nexplaining how they work\ntogether to build rigorous\nacademic thinking.\n\nReflection adequately\nReflection is brief and lacks\nexplains the importance of\nconnection between the\nboth skills for research\ntwo skills.\nand argumentation.\n\nRADAR analysis is\nincomplete or superficial for\none or both sources. The\ncomparison paragraph is\nvague or lacks justification.\n\nReflection is missing or\noff-topic.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\nTask 1: Find the Fallacies\n\nEither/Or Example:\nFrom a debate on education \"We either completely ban smartphones in schools, or we accept that students will never learn\n:\n\nto focus again.\"\nIdentification: This is an Either/Or False Dilemma) fallacy. It presents only two extreme options, ignoring middle-ground\nsolutions like regulated use or tech-integrated lessons.\n\nSlippery Slope Example:\nFrom an online forum \"If we allow this one history book to be revised, next they'll rewrite all of history, and soon our\n:\n\nchildren won't know any facts at all!\"\nIdentification: This is a Slippery Slope fallacy. It predicts an inevitable chain of extreme events from a single action without\nevidence for each step.\n\nTask 2: Be a RADAR Analyst\n\nSource 1 Credible): Article from Journal of Adolescent Health titled \"Longitudinal Effects of Social Media Use on Teen\nWell-Being\" 2023 .\n\nRADAR Analysis:\nRelevance: Directly addresses mental health and social media.\nAuthority: Published in a peer-reviewed journal; authors are PhDs in psychology.\nDate: 2023 – very current.\nAppearance: Professional layout, academic language, full citations.\nReason: To inform and present research findings. Verdict: Excellent source.\nSource 2 Unreliable): Blog post \"Why Social Media is Satan's Tool\" on a personal conspiracy theory website 2024 .\nRADAR Analysis:\nRelevance: Talks about social media but from a religious/biased angle.\nAuthority: Anonymous author, no credentials.",
  "6": "Chapter 6: The Thesis: The Engine of All Essays\n\n第六章：论⽂陈述：所有⽂章的核⼼ (Lùnwén chénshù: Suǒyǒu wénzh ng de héx n)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To craft a strong, arguable thesis statement that acts as the\ncentral argument and controlling idea for any type of essay.\n为任何类型的⽂章构建⼀个强⼤的、可论证的论⽂陈述，将其作为中⼼论点和核⼼思想。\n\nLesson 6.1: What is a Thesis?\n\n第⼀课：什么是论⽂陈述？(Shénme shì lùnwén chénshù?)\n\nPart 1: The Engine of Your Essay\n\n⽂章的核⼼引擎 (Wénzh ng de héx n yǐnqíng)\n\nIf your essay were a car, the thesis statement 论⽂陈述 (lùnwén chénshù) would be the engine. Every single part of your\nessay—every paragraph, every piece of evidence—connects to and is powered by this one central sentence. Without a\nstrong thesis, your essay won't go anywhere.\nA thesis is more than just a statement of fact; it is a claim 主张 (zhǔzh ng) that needs to be proven. It is the main argument\nyou will support with evidence throughout your entire paper.\nA Fact 事实 (Shìshí): \"The Great Depression was a severe global economic downturn that began in 1929.\"\nA Thesis 论⽂陈述 (Lùnwén chénshù): \"The primary cause of the Great Depression was not the stock market crash itself,\nbut the widespread bank failures that wiped out the life savings of millions of Americans and crushed consumer\nconfidence.\"\n\nPart 2: The Formula for a Strong Thesis\n\n强⼤论⽂陈述的公式 (Qiángdà lùnwén chénshù de g ngshì)\n\nA strong thesis statement usually has three key parts:\n⼀个强⼤的论⽂陈述通常包含三个关键部分：\n\nThe Topic 主题 (Zhǔtí): What are you writing about?\n你要写什么？\n\n\fYour Position/Claim 你的⽴场/主张 (Nǐ de lìchǎng/zhǔzh ng): What is your main argument about the topic?\n你关于这个主题的主要论点是什么？\n\nThe Rationale The \"Because\") 理由（“因为”）(Lǐyóu (“Y nwèi”)): What are the main reasons that support your claim?\n\nThis provides a roadmap for your essay.\n\n⽀持你主张的主要理由是什么？这为你的⽂章提供了路线图。\n\nThesis Statement - Formula 公式:\n\nTopic + Position + Rationale = Strong Thesis\n\n主题 + ⽴场 + 理由 = 强⼤的论⽂陈述\n\nWeak 薄弱: \"This paper is about social media.\" This is only a topic.)\nStrong 强⼤: \"While social media connects people, it ultimately harms teenage mental health because it promotes\n\nunrealistic comparisons, enables cyberbullying, and disrupts sleep patterns.\"\n“虽然社交媒体连接了⼈们，但它最终危害⻘少年⼼理健康，因为它助⻓了不切实际的⽐较、使⽹络欺凌成为可能，并破坏了睡眠模\n式。”\n\nHow to Use the Formula: A Step-by-Step Guide\n\nFollow these steps to build your own thesis statement from the ground up.\n\nStep 1: Start with a Broad Topic\n\nBegin with the general subject you want to write about.\n\nExample Topic: Social media\n\nStep 2: Narrow it Down with a Specific Claim\n\nAsk a question about your topic and form an opinion. This is your argument or position.\nQuestion: Is social media good or bad for teenagers?\n\nYour Position: It is more harmful than helpful.\nCombined so far: Social media has a net negative impact on adolescents.\n\nStep 3: Add the \"Because\" (The Rationale)\n\nThis is the most crucial step. List the key points or reasons that prove your claim. These will become the main body\nparagraphs of your essay.\nReasons: It promotes social comparison, enables cyberbullying, and disrupts sleep patterns.\n\nAdd the Rationale: ...because it promotes social comparison, enables cyberbullying, and disrupts sleep patterns.\n\nStep 4: Combine and Refine\n\nBring all three parts together into one or two clear, complete sentences. Use transition words to make it flow smoothly.\n\nFinal Thesis Statement:\nAlthough social media helps teens stay connected, it ultimately has a net negative impact on adolescents because it\npromotes unhealthy social comparison, facilitates cyberbullying, and disrupts critical sleep patterns.\n\nAnother Example in Action\n\n\fLet's apply the formula to a different subject.\n\nTopic: Distance learning\nClaim: offers more flexibility than traditional education\nRationale: because it allows students to learn at their own pace, reduces commute time, and provides access to a wider\n\nrange of courses.\n\nFinal Thesis Statement:\nDistance learning provides greater flexibility than traditional classroom education by allowing students to learn at their\nown pace, eliminating commutes, and offering access to a diverse array of online courses.\nBy following this formula and diagram, you can ensure your thesis statement is specific, arguable, and provides a clear\nroadmap for your entire essay.\n\nExample: From Bad to Good\nLet's see how the formula transforms a weak thesis into a strong one.\n\nWeak Thesis Statement:\n\"This essay is about video games and violence.\"\n\nWhy it's weak: It only states the topic; it has no claim or rationale. It is not debatable.\nApplying the Formula:\nTopic: Violent video games\nClaim: do not cause real-world violence\nRationale: because they provide a safe outlet for aggression, most players can distinguish between fantasy and reality, and other\nfactors like home environment are better predictors of violent behaviour.\n\nStrong Thesis Statement:\n\"Despite common concerns, violent video games Topic do not cause real-world violence Claim because they offer a\nsafe outlet for aggression, most players distinguish between fantasy and reality, and underlying environmental factors\nare more significant predictors of behaviour Rationale).\"\n\nLesson 6.2: Thesis Statements for Different Essay Types\n第⼆课：不同⽂章类型的论⽂陈述 (Bùtóng wénzh ng lèixíng de lùnwén chénshù)\n\nThe type of essay you are writing changes the way you frame your thesis. The command word in the prompt (from Chapter\n\n3) is your guide.\n\n你写的⽂章类型改变了你构建论⽂陈述的⽅式。提⽰中的指令词（来⾃第三章）就是你的指南。\n\nEssay Type ⽂章类\n型\n\nWhat the Thesis Does 论⽂陈述的作⽤\n\nKey Words in Thesis 论⽂陈述中的关\n\n键词\n\nArgumentative 议论 Takes a debatable position and tries to\nshould, must, ought to, despite,\n⽂\npersuade the reader. 采取⼀个可辩论的⽴ although 应该，必须，尽管\n场并试图说服读者。\n\nExample 例⼦\n\"Despite claims of economic\n\nbenefit, plastic water bottles\nshould be banned because they\nare a major source of pollution\n\n\fEssay Type ⽂章类\n型\n\nWhat the Thesis Does 论⽂陈述的作⽤\n\nKey Words in Thesis 论⽂陈述中的关\n\n键词\n\nExample 例⼦\nand their production wastes\nvaluable resources.\"\n\nComparative ⽐较类 differences between two subjects. 强调\n\nwhereas, while, both, however,\ncompared to ⽽，虽然，两者都，然\n\nWhile both classical and\noperant conditioning are learning\nprocesses, classical conditioning\npairs stimuli whereas operant\nconditioning associates\nbehaviour with consequences.\"\n\nAnalytical 分析类⽂\n\nBreaks down a text/idea to show how it\nworks and what it means. 分解⼀个⽂本/\n\nby examining, through, reveals,\ndemonstrates 通过检验，通过，揭\n\nreveals the corruption of the\nAmerican Dream by examining\n\nProblem-Solution\n\nClearly defines a problem and proposes problem, solution, to address, to\na viable solution. 清晰定义⼀个问题并提出 solve, effective way 问题，解决⽅\n\nThe problem of food waste in\nrestaurants can be solved by\nimplementing composting\nprograms and offering variable\nportion sizes for customers.\"\n\n\"\n\nHighlights key similarities and/or\n\n⽂章\n\n两个主题之间主要的相似点和/或不同点。\n\n章\n\n问题解决类⽂章\n\n想法以展⽰其⼯作原理和含义。\n\n⼀个可⾏的解决⽅案。\n\n⽽，与...相⽐\n\n⽰，展⽰\n\n案，为解决，为解决，有效⽅法\n\n\"\n\nIn 'The Great Gatsby,' Fitzgerald\n\nthe empty lives of the wealthy\nelite.\"\n\"\n\nPart 1: Practice: Identify the Type\n\n练习：识别类型 (Liànxí: Shíbié lèixíng)\n\nInstructions 说明: For each thesis statement below, identify which essay type it is best suited for: Argumentative A ,\nComparative C , Analytical An , or Problem-Solution PS .\n对于下⾯的每个论⽂陈述，判断它最适合哪种⽂章类型：议论⽂ (A), ⽐较类⽂章 (C), 分析类⽂章 (An), 或问题解决类⽂章 (PS)。\n\n\"The key difference between introverts and extroverts lies not in their social skills but in how they recharge their mental\nenergy.\"\n“内向者和外向者之间的主要区别不在于他们的社交技能，⽽在于他们如何补充⼼理能量。”\n\nType 类型: _________\n\n\"To reduce traffic congestion, the city must invest in reliable public transportation and create more bike lanes.\"\n“为了减少交通拥堵，市政府必须投资可靠的公共交通并建设更多⾃⾏⻋道。”\n\nType 类型: _________\n\n\"Shakespeare's 'Macbeth' uses the symbolism of blood to represent the inescapable guilt that consumes Macbeth and\nLady Macbeth after their murderous actions.\"\n\n“莎⼠⽐亚的《⻨克⽩》使⽤⾎的象征来代表⻨克⽩和⻨克⽩夫⼈谋杀⾏为后吞噬他们的⽆法逃避的负罪感。”\n\nType 类型: _________\n\n\"Although both are popular streaming services, Netflix focuses on a vast library of licensed content while Disney+\nleverages its powerhouse proprietary franchises.\"\n“虽然两者都是流⾏的流媒体服务，但Netflix专注于庞⼤的授权内容库，⽽Disney+则利⽤其强⼤的⾃有特许经营权。”\n\nType 类型: _________\n\nLesson 6.3: Crafting and Refining Your Thesis\n\n第三课：构建和完善你的论⽂陈述 (Gòujiàn hé wánshàn nǐ de lùnwén chénshù)\n\nPart 1: The Thesis Generator\n\n论⽂陈述⽣成器 (Lùnwén chénshù sh ngchéng qì)\n\n\fUse this template to draft your own thesis statement.\n\n使⽤这个模板来起草你⾃⼰的论⽂陈述。\n\nMy general topic is: 我的⼤致主题是：\n(e.g., school uniforms, renewable energy, a book you read)\n（例如：校服，可再⽣能源，你读的⼀本书）\n\nMy specific angle/position is: 我的具体⾓度/⽴场是：\nWhat do you want to say about it? Try using a command word: I want to argue that.../compare.../analyse...)\n\n（你想就此说些什么？尝试使⽤⼀个指令词：我想论证.../⽐较.../分析...）\n\nBecause of these key reasons: 因为以下关键理由：\n\na) _____________________________________________________\nb) _____________________________________________________\nc) _____________________________________________________\nThese will become the topics of your body paragraphs!\n\n（这些将成为你主体段的主题！）\n\nNow, combine it into one sentence: 现在，将其组合成⼀个句⼦：\n_____________________________________________________\n_____________________________________________________\n_____________________________________________________\n\nTask\n\nCreate 5 Strong Thesis statements. Each using a different Essay Type.\n\nPart 2: The \"So What?\" Test (Again!)\n\n“那⼜怎样？”测试（再来⼀次！）(“Nà yòu zěnyàng?” cèshì (zài lái y cì!\n\nA good thesis must pass the test. Ask yourself: \"So what?\" Why does your argument matter? If the answer is obvious and\nimportant, you have a strong thesis.\n\n⼀个好的论⽂陈述必须通过这个测试。问⾃⼰：“那⼜怎样？” 为什么你的论点重要？如果答案是显⽽易⻅且重要的，那么你就有了⼀\n个强⼤的论⽂陈述。\n\nWeak Thesis 薄弱论⽂陈述: \"People should exercise.\" So what? This is obvious and boring.)\n“⼈们应该锻炼。”（那⼜怎样？这显⽽易⻅且⽆聊。）\n\nStrong Thesis 强⼤论⽂陈述: \"Implementing a mandatory 30-minute daily exercise period in workplaces would\n\nsignificantly reduce healthcare costs for employers and improve overall employee productivity and well-being.\" This\nmatters because it affects money and health!\n\n“在⼯作场所实施强制性的每⽇30分钟锻炼时间将显著降低雇主的医疗成本，并提⾼员⼯的整体⽣产⼒和幸福感。”（这很重要，因\n为它影响⾦钱和健康！）\n\nApply the test to the thesis you just wrote:对你刚写的论⽂陈述应⽤这个测试：\nSo what? Why does your argument matter?那⼜怎样？为什么你的论点重要？\n\n\fHomework: The Thesis Workshop\n\n作业：论⽂陈述⼯作坊 (Lùnwén chénshù g ngzuò f ng)\n\nTask 1: Analyse 分析\nFind two thesis statements online (in sample essays or articles). For each one:\n在⽹上找两个论⽂陈述（在范⽂或⽂章中）。对每⼀个：\n\nIdentify the topic, position, and rationale.\n\n找出主题、⽴场和理由。\n\nDecide what type of essay it would fit.\n判断它适合哪种⽂章类型。\n\nRun it through the \"So What?\" test.\n\n⽤ “那⼜怎样？”测试来检验它。\n\nThesis 1 ______________________________________________________\nTopic: ____________________________________________________\nPosition: __________________________________________________\nRationale: _________________________________________________\nEssay Type: _______________________________________________\nSo What? __________________________________________________\nThesis 2 ______________________________________________________\nTopic: ____________________________________________________\nPosition: __________________________________________________\nRationale: _________________________________________________\nEssay Type: _______________________________________________\nSo What? __________________________________________________\n\nTask 2: Create 创造\n\nUsing the Thesis Generator from this chapter, write three different thesis statements for three different essay types\nArgumentative, Comparative, Analytical) on topics of your choice.\n\n使⽤本章的论⽂陈述⽣成器，就你⾃选的主题，为三种不同的⽂章类型（议论⽂、⽐较类、分析类）写出三个不同的论⽂陈述。\n\nArgumentative 议论⽂) _________________________________________\n\nComparative ⽐较类⽂章) _______________________________________\n\nAnalytical 分析类⽂章) ________________________________________\n\nTask 3: Refine 完善\n\nChoose your strongest thesis statement from Task 2. Ask a peer or use an AI tool (e.g., \" critique this thesis statement:\n[paste your thesis]\") to get feedback. Revise it to make it clearer and more specific.\n\n\f从任务2中选择你最强⼤的论⽂陈述。请⼀位同学或使⽤AI⼯具（例如：“评价这个论⽂陈述：[粘贴你的论⽂陈述]”）获取反馈。修改\n它，使其更清晰、更具体。\n\nOriginal 原句: ________________________________________________\nFeedback 反馈: ________________________________________________\nRevised 修改后: ________________________________________________\n\nHomework: The Thesis Workshop - Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded and contribute to your overall Coursework.\n\nGrading Rubric for this Assignment\n\nThis homework will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points. The total points from this assignment will contribute to your\nmonthly coursework portfolio (e.g., under \"November\"). The rubric below details how your work will be evaluated across\nthe three tasks.\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nTask 1\nAnalyse\n\nBoth thesis statements are\nexpertly deconstructed. All\ncomponents (topic, position,\nrationale) are correctly and\ninsightfully identified. Essay type\nis perfectly matched, and the \"So\nWhat?\" test is answered with\nclear, logical reasoning.\n\nThesis statements are\ncorrectly deconstructed.\nMost components are\naccurately identified. Essay\ntype is correct, and the \"So\nWhat?\" test is answered\nadequately.\n\nThesis statements are\npartially deconstructed, but\nsome components are\nincorrect or missing. Essay\ntype may be misidentified.\nThe \"So What?\" answer is\nvague or illogical.\n\nAnalysis is\nincomplete,\ninaccurate, or\ndemonstrates a lack\nof understanding of\nthesis components.\n\nTask 2 Create\n\nThree distinct, well-formed, and\narguable thesis statements are\nprovided. Each perfectly matches\nits designated essay type\nArgumentative, Comparative,\nAnalytical) and demonstrates a\nclear understanding of each\nform's purpose.\n\nThree good thesis\nstatements are provided\nthat match their essay\ntypes. They are arguable\nbut could be more specific\nor impactful.\n\nThesis statements are\nprovided but are weak—they\nmay be too broad, factual, or\nnot properly tailored to the\nessay type.\n\nThesis statements are\nmissing, completely\noff-topic, or do not\nfunction as arguable\nclaims.\n\nTask 3 Refine\n\nThe revision process is clear and\neffective. The feedback is\nthoughtfully Summarised, and the\nrevised thesis is significantly\nimproved—more specific,\nnuanced, and complex than the\noriginal.\n\nThe revision process is\nevident. Feedback is\nrecorded, and the revised\nthesis is an improvement,\naddressing the feedback\nclearly.\n\nA revision is attempted, but\nthe changes are minimal or\ndo not effectively address\nthe feedback. The\nimprovement is slight.\n\nThe task is\nincomplete, or the\nrevised thesis is\nweaker than the\noriginal. Feedback is\nnot recorded.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\n\nTask 1: Analyse 分析\n\nThesis 1 \"The widespread adoption of renewable energy is not just an environmental imperative but a critical economic\nopportunity, as it can drive job creation in new technologies and foster energy independence.\"\nTopic: Renewable energy adoption.\nPosition: It is a critical economic opportunity.\nRationale: It drives job creation and fosters energy independence.\nEssay Type: Argumentative It aims to persuade the reader of a specific position).",
  "7": "Chapter 7: Research & Note-Taking for Synthesis\n第七章：研究与综合笔记法 (Yánji\n\nyǔ zònghé bǐjì fǎ)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond simply collecting sources and learn how to\n\nactively engage with them. You will learn systematic note-taking methods that help you synthesise information from your\nresearch into your own original arguments.\n\n超越简单地收集来源，学习如何积极地利⽤它们。你将学习系统的笔记⽅法，帮助你将研究中的信息综合成你⾃⼰原创的论点。\n\nLesson 7.1: From Hunting to Gardening\n\n第⼀课：从狩猎到耕耘 (Cóng shòuliè dào g ngyún)\n\n\fPart 1: Two Research Mindsets\n两种研究⼼态 (Liǎng zhǒng yánji\n\nx ntài)\n\nThe Hunter 狩猎者 (Shòuliè zhě): This researcher only \"collects trophies.\" They find quotes and facts, copy them down,\nand paste them into their essay. Their essay is a patchwork of other people's ideas.\n\n这种研究者只“收集战利品”。他们找到引⽤和事实，复制下来，然后粘贴到他们的⽂章中。他们的⽂章是别⼈想法的拼凑。\n\nThe Gardener 耕耘者 (G ngyún zhě): This researcher \"plants seeds.\" They gather information from sources (seeds),\nmix it with their own thinking (soil), and grow something entirely new: their own unique argument (the plant).\n\n这种研究者“播种”。他们从来源中收集信息（种⼦），⽤⾃⼰的思考（⼟壤）与之混合，然后培育出全新的东⻄：⾃⼰独特的论点\n（植物）。\n\nYour goal is to be a Gardener. Synthesis 综合 (Zònghé) is the process of blending your ideas with your research to create\nnew insight. It's the highest level of academic work.\n你的⽬标是成为⼀个耕耘者。综合是将你的想法与研究相融合以创造新⻅解的过程。这是学术⼯作的最⾼⽔平。\n\nPart 2: The RADAR Recap\n\nRADAR 回顾 (RADAR huígù)\nBefore you take notes, you must evaluate your sources. Remember your RADAR checklist from Chapter 5. Only take\ndetailed notes from sources that pass this test. Don't waste time on unreliable information.\n\n在记笔记之前，你必须评估你的来源。记住第五章的RADAR检查清单。只对通过这个测试的来源做详细笔记。不要在不可靠的信息上\n浪费时间。\n\nRelevance: Does it connect to my thesis?\nAuthority: Is the author/source credible?\nDate: Is the information current enough?\nAppearance: Is it professional and well-referenced?\nReason: Is its purpose to inform, not just to persuade or sell?\n\nLesson 7.2: Note-Taking Systems for Synthesis\n\n第⼆课：⽤于综合的笔记系统 (Yòngyú zònghé de bǐjì xìtǒng)\n\nPart 1: The Cornell Method\n\n康奈尔笔记法 (K ngnài'ěr bǐjì fǎ)\n\nThis method forces you to Synthesise as you take notes. Divide your paper into three sections:\n\n这种⽅法迫使你在记笔记时进⾏综合。将你的纸分为三个部分：\n\n\fAcademic Writing and AI - Nonfiction G11-12 Student Book - English Chinese Feb 2026 (2nd Ed.)\n\n\fHow to use it 如何使⽤:\n\nNotes 笔记: Take notes in the main section during your research. Use abbreviations, bullet points. Always note the\nsource!\n在研究过程中，在主区域记笔记。使⽤缩写、项⽬符号。⼀定要记下来源！\n\nCues 提⽰: After reading, review your notes. In the left margin, write key words, questions, or main ideas that connect to\nyour thesis.\n\n阅读后，复习你的笔记。在左边距，写下与你的论⽂相关的关键词、问题或主要思想。\n\nSummary 总结: At the bottom, write a 1 2 sentence summary of the entire source in your own words. This is the most\nimportant step for synthesis.\n\n在底部，⽤你⾃⼰的话写下整个来源的1 2句总结。这是综合中最重要的⼀步。\n\nExample\nThe Cornell Method Note-Taking Sheet\n\nTopic TITLE School Uniforms: Impact on Bullying Date: Oct 26, 2023\nCue Column After Class)\nMain Argument: Pro-Uniform\nHow uniforms reduce bullying\n\nNotes Column During Class)\nDo School Uniforms Reduce Bullying?Key arguments for and against.\nArguments That Uniforms REDUCE Bullying:• Reduces Economic\nBullying: Minimises teasing over clothing brands, wealth, & fashion\nstatus. • Promotes Unity: Creates a \"level playing field,\" reduces\nvisible in-groups/out-groups based on attire. • Focus on Character:\nStudents are judged on personality/actions, not on their clothes.\n\nKey Study Cited\n\n- Cited a 2011 study from the University of Houston: schools with\nuniforms saw a reduction in exclusionary bullying.\n\nCounter-Argument: Shifts bullying\n\nArguments That Uniforms DO NOT STOP Bullying (or make it\nworse):• Bullying Shifts, Not Stops: Bullying may just focus on other\nthings: shoes, accessories, hairstyles, technology, body\n\n\fCue Column After Class)\n\nNotes Column During Class)\nshape. • Forces Conformity: Can punish students for self-expression,\nmaking non-conformists new targets.\n\nIdentity & Self-Expression\n\n• Hurts Self-Expression: Clothing is a key way for teens to express\nidentity. Suppressing this can cause stress and conflict. • Doesn't\nAddress Root Causes: Bullying is a behavioural issue; uniforms are a\nsuperficial \"fix\" that doesn't teach empathy or resolve underlying\nproblems.\n\nOther Considerations:• Enforcement Issues:\n\nThe \"Enforcement\" Problem\n\nDetentions/suspensions for uniform violations can themselves be\npunitive and create conflict. • Financial Burden: While reducing some\ncompetition, cost of uniforms can still be a stress for low-income\nfamilies.\n\nConclusion: No clear consensus. Evidence is mixed. Uniforms may\n\nKey Question: What is the consensus? reduce certain types of bullying (economic, fashion-based) but are\n\nunlikely to eliminate it entirely, as bullying can simply shift its focus.\nThe root causes of bullying are complex and social.\n\nSummary (Written after class, in your own words)\n\nThe connection between school uniforms and bullying is complex and debated. Proponents argue uniforms reduce\neconomic and status-based bullying by creating a more equal appearance and fostering unity. However, opponents\ncontend that bullying simply shifts to other attributes like shoes or hairstyles, and that suppressing self-expression through\nclothing can create new problems. Ultimately, uniforms may manage some symptoms of bullying but do not address the\nunderlying social and behavioural root causes.\n\nPart 2: The Synthesis Matrix\n综合矩阵 (Zònghé jǔzhèn)\n\nThis is a powerful tool for organising notes from multiple sources on a single topic. It helps you see connections and gaps.\n这是⼀个强⼤的⼯具，⽤于组织来⾃同⼀主题多个来源的笔记。它帮助你看到联系和空⽩。\n\nResearch Question:\nSource 1 Smith\nShould school uniforms 2022 Journal of\nbe mandatory?\nEducation\n\nSource 2 Chen & Li\n2023 Sociology Study\n\nImpact on Bullying\n\nFinds a 30%\ndecrease in bullying\nreports.\n\nImpact on Academic\nPerformance\n\nNo direct correlation\nNot studied.\nfound.\n\nImpact on Student\nIdentity\n\nArgues uniforms\nsuppress\nindividuality.\n\nSource 3 National\nEducation Report\n\nNo significant change in\nReports mixed results;\nbullying, but a shift in what highly contextis mocked (e.g., shoes).\ndependent.\n\nMy Analysis / Synthesis\nSources disagree. Uniforms may\nreduce some bullying but not\neliminate it. The type of bullying\nmight change.\n\nSlight improvement in No strong evidence that uniforms\nattendance, no change improve grades. Maybe other\nin grades.\nfactors like attendance improve.\n\nFound students found new\nways to express identity\nNot discussed.\n(accessories).\n\nHow to use it 如何使⽤:\n\nThesis Link: This is a key tradeoff. Does reducing bullying justify\nlimiting self-expression? My\nargument could focus here.\n\nLabel the columns with your sources.\n将你的来源标注在列上。\n\nLabel the rows with the key themes or ideas from your research question.\n将你的研究问题中的关键主题或想法标注在⾏上。\n\nFill in the cells with short notes, quotes, or page numbers from each source.\n⽤简短的笔记、引⽤或⻚码填充每个单元格。\n\n\fUse the final column (My Analysis) for your own thoughts, connections, and criticisms. This is where synthesis\nhappens!\n使⽤最后⼀列（我的分析）来记录你⾃⼰的想法、联系和批评。综合就在这⾥发⽣！\n\nLesson\n\n7.3: Putting It Into Practice\n\n第三课：实践应⽤ (Shíjiàn yìngyòng)\n\nPart 1: Activity: Note-Taking Lab\n活动：笔记实践课 (Bǐjì shíjiàn kè)\n\nInstructions 说明: Read the short text below. Take notes on it using The Cornell Method.\n阅读下⾯的短⽂。使⽤康奈尔笔记法在上⾯做笔记。\n\nText:\n\n\"A recent study from the University of Toronto Lee, 2023) observed classroom dynamics in ten high schools. The\nresearchers found that while mandatory uniform policies did reduce 'clothing-based' teasing, social hierarchies simply\nreasserted themselves based on other factors, such as smartphone brands, jewelry, and even the quality of students'\nschool supplies. The study concludes that efforts to improve school climate must address deeper social issues rather than\napplying superficial fixes like dress codes.\"\n\n\fPart 2: Activity: Start a Matrix\n\n活动：创建⼀个矩阵 (Chuàngjiàn y gè jǔzhèn)\n\nInstructions 说明: Think about your essay topic or a topic you're interested in. Start a Synthesis Matrix in the space below.\n思考你的⽂章主题或⼀个你感兴趣的主题。在下⾯的空间⾥开始⼀个综合矩阵。\nMy Research Question: ______________________________________________________\nKey Themes\n\nSource 1\n\nSource 2\n\nMy Analysis / Synthesis\n\nTheme 1\nTheme 2\nTheme 3\n\nHomework 7: The Synthesis Bootcamp\n\n作业：综合训练营 (Zònghé xùnliàn yíng)\n\nTask 1: Cornell in Action\n\nFind one credible source (article, book chapter) related to your potential essay topic. Take notes on it using the Cornell\n\nMethod. Remember to write a summary in your own words.\n\n找到⼀个与你潜在论⽂主题相关的可靠来源（⽂章、书籍章节）。使⽤康奈尔笔记法做笔记。记住要⽤你⾃⼰的话写⼀个总结。\n\nSource Title & Author: ___________________________________________\nSummary (in your own words): ____________________________________\n\nTask 2: Matrix Builder\nFind two more sources on your topic. Start a Synthesis Matrix on a separate piece of paper. Include at least three key\nthemes. The goal is to fill in the cells and, most importantly, the \"My Analysis\" column.\n\n找到关于你主题的另外两个来源。在⼀张单独的纸上开始⼀个综合矩阵。⾄少包含三个关键主题。⽬标是填满单元格，并且最重要的\n是填满“我的分析”栏。\n\nTask 3: Reflect on the Process\n\nAnswer the following questions:\n\n回答以下问题：\n\nHow did using the Cornell Method change how you read the source, compared to just highlighting?\n\n与仅仅划重点相⽐，使⽤康奈尔笔记法如何改变你阅读来源的⽅式？\n\nWhat is the main value of the Synthesis Matrix? What connection or gap did you notice?\n\n综合矩阵的主要价值是什么？你注意到了什么联系或空⽩？\n\n\fHomework 7: The Synthesis Bootcamp - Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points and will contribute to your overall\nCoursework average Weight: 25% of your final grade).\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nTask 1 Cornell\nNotes\n\nSource is highly\ncredible/relevant. All Cornell\nsections Cues, Notes, Summary)\nare fully utilized, insightful, and\ndemonstrate deep engagement.\nSummary is original and\naccurate.\n\nSource is\ncredible/relevant. All\nCornell sections are\ncompleted adequately.\nSummary captures the\nmain idea.\n\nSource is of questionable\ncredibility/relevance. Cornell\nsections are incomplete or\noverly brief. Summary is\nvague or relies on source\nphrasing.\n\nSource is not credible\nor missing. Cornell\nmethod not followed.\nSummary is missing\nor plagiarized.\n\nTask 2\nSynthesis\nMatrix\n\nMatrix includes 2+ new sources\nand 3+ clear, relevant themes.\nCells are filled with specific\nevidence. The \"My Analysis\"\ncolumn shows sophisticated,\noriginal synthesis identifying\nclear connections, contradictions,\nand gaps.\n\nMatrix includes 2\nsources and 3+ themes.\nCells are filled. The \"My\nAnalysis\" column\nidentifies obvious\nconnections or gaps.\n\nMatrix is incomplete (missing\nsources/themes). \"My\nAnalysis\" column is minimal,\nlisting information without true\nsynthesis.\n\nMatrix is largely blank\nor does not\ndemonstrate an\nunderstanding of the\ntask.\n\nReflections are insightful and\nself-aware, clearly articulating\nTask 3 Process the cognitive benefits of each\nReflection\nmethod and demonstrating a\ndeep understanding of their\npurpose in the research process.\n\nReflections are clear and\naddress the questions,\nshowing a solid\nunderstanding of how the\nmethods aided learning\nand synthesis.\n\nReflections are vague,\nsuperficial, or only partially\naddress the questions.\n\nReflections are\nmissing, irrelevant, or\ndemonstrate a lack of\nunderstanding.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\n\nEssay Topic: The ethical implications of generative A.I. in education.\n\nTask 1: Cornell in Action\nSource Title & Author: \"The Promise and Peril of A.I. in the Classroom\" by Dr. Ben Miller, Journal of Educational\nTechnology.\n\nSummary (in your own words): This article argues that while generative A.I. tools like chatbots can act as powerful\n\npersonal tutors, they also risk fostering intellectual dependency and undermining academic integrity. The author\ncontends that the key challenge for educators is not to ban these tools, but to design \"A.I.-resistant\" assessments that\nprioritize critical thinking and process over the final product.\n\nTask 2: Matrix Builder\n\nSynthesis Matrix: Ethical Implications of Generative A.I. in Education\n\n\fKey Themes\n\nAcademic\nIntegrity\n1.\n\nSource 1 Miller\n(\"Promise and Peril\")\nWarns about\nundermining integrity\nwith A.I.-generated\nwork.\n\nSource 2 Chen & Li (\"A.I. and the\nDigital Divide\")\n\nNot a primary focus.\n\nSource 3 National\nEducation Report\n\nReports a 40% rise in\nplagiarism cases\nlinked to A.I. tools.\n\nMy Analysis\nConnection: Miller and the\nReport both see integrity as a\nmajor threat. The Report\nprovides hard data that supports\nMiller's theoretical concern.\nThis is a widely acknowledged\nrisk.\nGap/Connection: Chen & Li\n\nEquity &\nAccess\n\n2.\n\nPedagogical\nShift\n3.\n\nBriefly mentions cost\nas a barrier.\n\nProposes \"A.I.resistant\nassessments.\"\n\nPrimary focus. Argues A.I. tools\ncould worsen the digital divide;\nwealthy schools will adopt them\nfaster, giving their students an\nunfair advantage.\n\nSuggests A.I. literacy should be a\nnew core skill.\n\nidentify a crucial, specific equity\nissue that Miller only glosses\nRecommends federal\nover. The Report's policy\nfunding for A.I. tools in\nrecommendation is a direct,\nlow-income districts.\nproposed solution to the\nproblem Chen & Li highlight.\nThis is a core area of debate.\n\nAdvocates for teacher\ntraining on integrating\nA.I. responsibly.\n\nSynthesis: All three sources\nagree a major shift is needed,\nbut they focus on different\nsolutions: assessment design\nMiller , student skills Chen &\nLi), and teacher readiness\nReport . An effective policy\nwould need to combine all three.\n\nTask 3: Reflect on the Process\nHow did using the Cornell Method change how you read the source, compared to just highlighting?\nHighlighting is passive; I just mark what seems important in the moment. The Cornell Method forced me to be active.\nI had to pause after each section to formulate questions in the \"Cues\" column, which made me interrogate the\nmaterial. Writing the summary in my own words ensured I truly understood the author's core argument, not just a\ncollection of highlighted sentences.\n\nWhat is the main value of the Synthesis Matrix? What connection or gap did you notice?\nThe main value is that it visually forces you to have a \"conversation\" with your sources. Instead of seeing each\nsource in isolation, you see where they agree, disagree, and what they collectively miss. I noticed a clear connection\nbetween Miller and the National Report on academic integrity. More importantly, I identified a gap in Miller's argument\nregarding equity, which was powerfully filled by the Chen & Li article, showing me a central point for my own essay.\n\nHow This Assignment Affects Your Grade\n\nTeacher Evaluation: Using the rubric, the teacher would evaluate the example as follows:\nTask 1 Excellent Notes are structured, summary is original and accurate).\nTask 2 Excellent Matrix is complete with specific evidence and sophisticated analysis in the final column).\nTask 3 Excellent Reflections are insightful and clearly articulate the value of each method).\nTotal Score: 10 out of 10.\nIntegration into Final Grade: This score of 10/10 is added to your other coursework scores. At the term's end, a\nCoursework Average is calculated. This average is then multiplied by 0.25 25%) to determine its contribution to your\nfinal grade. This points are added to your points from Exams and Projects to determine your final percentage, ACB\nletter grade, and CEFR level.",
  "8": "Chapter 8: The Argumentative Essay\n第⼋章：议论⽂ (Yìlùnwén)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To synthesise all the skills you've learned so far—thesis crafting,\nlogical reasoning, source integration, and paragraph structure—to write a complete, persuasive argumentative essay.\n综合你⽬前所学的所有技能——论⽂陈述构建、逻辑推理、来源整合和段落结构——来完成⼀篇有说服⼒的议论⽂。\n\nLesson 8.1: The Architecture of Argument\n第⼀课：论证的架构 (Lùnzhèng de jiàgòu)\n\nPart 1: What is an Argumentative Essay?\n\n什么是议论⽂？(Shénme shì yìlùnwén?)\n\nAn argumentative essay is your chance to be a lawyer for your ideas. You must:\n议论⽂是你为⾃⼰的观点充当律师的机会。你必须：\n\nState a Clear Position 陈述⼀个清晰的⽴场: Present a debatable thesis statement.\n提出⼀个可辩论的论⽂陈述。\n\nPresent Your Evidence 呈现你的证据: Support your claim with logical reasoning, facts, statistics, and quotes from\n\ncredible sources.\n\n⽤逻辑推理、事实、数据和对可信来源的引⽤⽀持你的主张。\n\nAcknowledge the Opposition 承认反对意⻅: Address counterarguments—the strong points of the other side.\n处理反论点——对⽅的强项。\n\nRefute the Opposition 反驳反对意⻅: Refute those counterarguments to show why your position is stronger.\n反驳这些反论点，以说明为什么你的⽴场更强。\n\nThe goal is not to \"win\" a fight, but to persuade your reader through respectful, evidence-based reasoning.\n\n⽬标不是“赢得”争吵，⽽是通过尊重他⼈、基于证据的推理来说服你的读者。\n\nPart 2: The Structure Blueprint\n结构蓝图 (Jiégòu lántú)\n\nA powerful argument needs a clear structure. This is your blueprint:\n⼀个强⼤的论证需要⼀个清晰的结构。这是你的蓝图：\n\n\fLesson 8.2: The Counterargument and Refutation\n第⼆课：反论与反驳 (Fǎnlùn yǔ fǎnbó)\n\nPart 1: Why Acknowledge the Other Side?\n\n为什么需要承认对⽅观点？(Wèishéme x yào chéngrèn duìf ng gu ndiǎn?)\n\nIgnoring strong opposing views makes you look biased or uninformed. Addressing them makes you look fair, honest, and\nconfident in your position.\n\n忽视强有⼒的反对观点会让你显得有偏⻅或⽆知。处理它们会让你看起来公平、诚实并对⾃⼰的⽴场有信⼼。\n\nThink of it like this: If you can explain your opponent's best argument and then explain why it's\nyour overall argument becomes much more powerful.\n\nstill\n\nnot as strong as yours,\n\n可以这样想： 如果你能解释对⼿的最佳论点，然后解释为什么它仍然不如你的论点有说服⼒，那么你的整体论证就会变得有⼒得多。\n\nPart 2: How to Do It: The \"They Say / I Say\" Model\n如何操作：“他们说/我说”模型 (“T men shu\n\n/ Wǒ shu ” móxíng)\n\nThis is a simple but powerful framework for counterargument paragraphs.\n\n这是⼀个⽤于反论段落的简单⽽强⼤的框架。\n\nThey Say... 他们说...\n\nIntroduce the opposing point of view. Use phrases like:\n\n引⼊反对的观点。使⽤这样的短语：\n\n\"Critics of this position argue that...\"\n“这个⽴场的批评者认为...”\n\n\"Some people might contend that...\"\n“有些⼈可能主张...”\n\n\f\"A common concern about this solution is...\"\n“对这个解决⽅案的⼀个普遍担忧是...”\n\nI Say... 我说...\n\nNow, refute it! Explain why that point is flawed, incomplete, or less important than your points. Use evidence. Use\nphrases like:\n现在，反驳它！解释为什么这个观点有缺陷、不完整或不如你的观点重要。使⽤证据。使⽤这样的短语：\n\n\"However, this view overlooks...\"\n“然⽽，这种观点忽略了...”\n\n\"While this concern is valid, it fails to account for...\"\n“虽然这种担忧是合理的，但它未能考虑到...”\n\n\"The evidence, however, suggests otherwise. For example...\"\n“然⽽，证据表明情况并⾮如此。例如...”\n\nExample 例⼦:\n\nThey Say... \"Some argue that a four-day school week is too short and will lead to less learning.\"\n“有些⼈认为每周四天上课时间太短，会导致学习效果下降。”\n\nI Say... \"However, studies from districts that have adopted this model show that restructured class time and improved\nteacher morale can actually lead to more focused instruction and stable, or even improved, test scores.\"\n\n“然⽽，采⽤这种模式的地区的研究表明，重新安排的课堂时间和提⾼的教师⼠⽓实际上可以带来更专注的教学和稳定甚⾄提⾼的\n考试成绩。”\n\nbookmark\n\nLesson 8.3: Building Your Essay\n\n第三课：构建你的⽂章 (Gòujiàn nǐ de wénzh ng)\n\nPart 1: Outline Workshop\n\n提纲⼯作坊 (Tíg ng g ngzuò f ng)\n\nUse this template to plan your entire essay. This is your blueprint.\n\n使⽤这个模板来规划你的整篇⽂章。这是你的蓝图。\n\nThesis Statement 论⽂陈述: __________________________________________________\n\nBody Paragraph 1 主体段落 1\n\nPoint 论点: _________________________________________________________\n\nEvidence 证据: _______________________________________________________\nSource 来源: _________________________________________________________\n\nBody Paragraph 2 主体段落 2\n\nPoint 论点: _________________________________________________________\n\nEvidence 证据: _______________________________________________________\nSource 来源: _________________________________________________________\n\nBody Paragraph 3 主体段落 3\n\nPoint 论点: _________________________________________________________\n\nEvidence 证据: _______________________________________________________\nSource 来源: _________________________________________________________\n\nCounterargument Paragraph 反论段:\n\n\fThey Say 他们说: _____________________________________________________\nI Say 我说: _________________________________________________________\nEvidence for Refutation 反驳证据: ______________________________________\nConclusion 结论:\nFinal Thought 最终思考: _______________________________________________\n\nPart 2: Language for Argumentation\n论证语⾔ (Lùnzhèng yǔyán)\n\nIntroducing Evidence 引⼊证据:\n\nFor example,...\" “例如...”\n\"According to a study by Author ,...\" “根据[作者]的⼀项研究...”\n\"\n\nThis is supported by the fact that...\" “这⼀点得到了...事实的⽀持。”\n\n\"\n\nExplaining Evidence 解释证据:\n\nThis shows that...\" “这表明...”\n\n\"\n\nThis is significant because...\" “这很重要，因为...”\n\"This evidence demonstrates...\" “这个证据表明...”\n\"\n\nIntroducing Counterarguments 引⼊反论:\nIt is true that...\" “确实...”\n\n\"\n\nAdmittedly,...\" “必须承认...”\n\n\"\n\nWhile some believe X, a closer look reveals Y.\" “虽然有些⼈相信X，但仔细研究后发现Y。”\n\n\"\n\nMaking Concessions 做出让步:\n\nAlthough it is true that [opposing point], [my point] is more important because...\"\n\n\"\n\n“虽然[反对点]确实如此，但[我的观点]更重要，因为...”\n\nI grant that [opposing point], but nevertheless...\"\n\n\"\n\n“我承认[反对点]，但尽管如此...”\n\nRefuting 反驳:\n\nHowever, this argument is flawed because...\"\n\n\"\n\n“然⽽，这个论点是有缺陷的，因为...”\n\nThis view ignores the key fact that...\"\n\n\"\n\n“这个观点忽略了⼀个关键事实...”\n\nThe data, however, tells a different story.\"\n\n\"\n\n“然⽽，数据告诉我们不同的情况。\n”\n\nHomework: The Argument Architect\n\n作业：论证建筑师 (Lùnzhèng jiànzhù sh )\n\nTask 1 Deconstruct an Argument\n\nFind an opinion editorial (op-ed) online or in a newspaper. Read it and complete the following:\n\n在⽹上或报纸上找⼀篇观点⽂章（社论）。阅读并完成以下内容：\n\nAuthor's Thesis 作者的论⽂陈述: _______________________________________\n\n______________________________________________________________________________\n______________________________________________________________________________\n\n\fTheir Main Points 他们的主要观点:\n1. _______\n2. _______\n3. _______\n\nCounterargument? 有反论吗? Do they address the other side? If so, how?\n他们处理对⽅观点了吗？如果是，如何处理的？\n\nPersuasive? 有说服⼒吗? Was it effective? Why or why not?\n它有效吗？为什么？\nTask 2 Build Your Blueprint\nUsing the Outline Workshop template in this chapter, create a detailed outline for your own argumentative essay. Choose a\ntopic you are passionate about and have researched.\n\n使⽤本章中的提纲⼯作坊模板，为你⾃⼰的议论⽂创建⼀个详细的提纲。选择⼀个你热衷并研究过的主题。\n\nTask 3 Draft the Hardest Part\nWrite a full draft of your Counterargument / Refutation paragraph. Use the \"They Say / I Say\" model and include at least\none piece of evidence to support your refutation.\n写出你的反论/反驳段落的完整草稿。使⽤“他们说/我说”模型，并⾄少包含⼀条证据来⽀持你的反驳。\n\nHomework: The Argument Architect - Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points.\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nTask 1\nDeconstruct an\nArgument\n\nOp-ed is well-chosen and credible.\nThesis and main points are accurately\nidentified. Analysis of the\ncounterargument and persuasive\neffectiveness is insightful and welljustified.\n\nThesis and main points\nare correctly identified.\nAnalysis of\ncounterargument and\npersuasion is logical but\ncould be more detailed.\n\nThesis or main points\nmay be misidentified.\nAnalysis is vague,\nsuperficial, or lacks\nclear justification.\n\nAnalysis is\nincomplete,\ninaccurate, or\ndemonstrates a lack\nof understanding of\nargument\ncomponents.\n\nTask 2 Build\nYour Blueprint\n\nOutline is exceptionally detailed, logical,\nand follows the chapter's template.\nThesis is complex and arguable. Main\npoints are well-supported with specific,\nplanned evidence.\n\nOutline is complete and\nlogical. Thesis is\narguable. Main points are\nsupported, but evidence\ncould be more specific.\n\nOutline is incomplete or\nillogical. Thesis is weak\n(too broad/factual).\nMain points lack clear\nevidence.\n\nOutline is missing,\nincoherent, or does\nnot reflect an\nargumentative\nstructure.\n\nThe counterargument/refutation\nparagraph is flawlessly executed using\nTask 3 Draft the the \"They Say / I Say\" model. The\nHardest Part\nopposing view is presented fairly and\nthen convincingly refuted with strong,\nrelevant evidence.\n\nThe paragraph correctly\nuses the model. The\nrefutation is logical and\nsupported by evidence,\nbut could be more\nimpactful or nuanced.\n\nThe paragraph attempts\nthe model but is\nunbalanced (e.g.,\nspends too long on\n\"They Say\"). The\nrefutation is weak or\nlacks evidence.\n\nThe paragraph does\nnot use the model,\nfails to include a\nrefutation, or the\nargument is entirely\none-sided.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\n\n\fEssay Topic: The implementation of a four-day workweek.\n\nTask 1: Deconstruct an Argument\nAuthor's Thesis: \"The traditional five-day workweek is an outdated relic; for most knowledge-based industries, a fourday workweek is not a perk but a necessary strategy to boost productivity, innovation, and employee well-being.\"\nTheir Main Points:\nBoosted Productivity: Cites studies showing that a shorter week leads to more focused work and reduces \"timewasting\" activities, maintaining or even increasing total output.\nEnhanced Innovation: Argues that well-rested employees with more personal time are more creative and bring\nfresher perspectives to problems.\nImproved Well-being: Highlights reduced burnout and improved mental health, leading to lower turnover and hiring\ncosts for companies.\n\nCounterargument?\nYes, the author does address the other side. They acknowledge the counterargument that \"a four-day week would\ncripple businesses that rely on constant availability and could lead to a pay cut for hourly workers.\" They refute this\nby pointing to pilot programs in the service industry that used staggered schedules to maintain coverage and by\nadvocating for policies that ensure salaried pay remains the same.\n\nPersuasive?\nIt was largely effective. The use of data from studies and real-world pilot programs made the argument credible. By\nacknowledging and refuting a key counterargument, the author appeared more trustworthy and thoughtful, which\nstrengthened the overall persuasion. However, the solution for hourly workers felt slightly underdeveloped.\n\nTask 2: Build Your Blueprint\n\nThesis Statement 论⽂陈述: The widespread adoption of a four-day workweek, with no loss of pay, is a viable and superior\nmodel for the 21st-century economy, as it enhances employee well-being, increases long-term company productivity, and\nfosters a more sustainable society.\n\nBody Paragraph 1 主体段落 1\nPoint 论点: A four-day workweek significantly improves employee mental and physical health.\nEvidence 证据: Major trials show drastic reductions in stress and burnout among employees working fewer hours.\nSource 来源: (Parker, 2023).\nBody Paragraph 2 主体段落 2\nPoint 论点: Companies benefit from increased productivity and reduced costs.\nEvidence 证据: Microsoft Japan reported a 40% boost in productivity during their four-day workweek experiment.\nSource 来源: (Microsoft Report, 2019).\nBody Paragraph 3 主体段落 3\nPoint 论点: A shorter workweek reduces environmental impact and promotes sustainability.\nEvidence 证据: With one less day of commuting and office energy use, carbon emissions are significantly lowered.\nSource 来源: (Environmental Research Journal, 2021).\nCounterargument Paragraph 反论段:\nThey Say 他们说: Critics argue that a shorter week would cripple productivity and hurt business competitiveness.\nI Say 我说 (Evidence for Refutation 反驳证据): Empirical evidence from numerous pilot programs contradicts this,\n\nshowing maintained or improved output alongside major gains in employee retention and operational efficiency, which\nenhance competitiveness.",
  "9": "Chapter 9: The Comparative Essay\n第九章：⽐较类⽂章 (Bǐjiào lèi wénzh ng)\n\nYour Goal for This Chapter 本章⽬标 (Běn zh ng mùbi o): To move beyond simple description and learn to analyse the\nsignificance of similarities and differences between two or more subjects.\n超越简单的描述，学习分析两个或更多主题之间相似性和差异性的意义。\n\nLesson 9.1: More Than Just a List\n第⼀课：不仅仅是列表 (Bùjǐn jǐn shì lièbiǎo)\n\nPart 1: The \"So What?\" of Comparison\n\n⽐较的“那⼜怎样？” (Bǐjiào de “nà yòu zěnyàng?”)\n\nA strong comparative essay does NOT just list how Thing A and Thing B are alike and different. Anyone can make a list.\n\n⼀篇强⼤的⽐较类⽂章不仅仅是列出事物A和事物B如何相似和不同。任何⼈都可以列⼀个清单。\n\nA strong comparative essay explains the significance of those similarities and differences. It answers the question: \"So\nwhat?\"\n⼀篇强⼤的⽐较类⽂章会解释这些异同的意义。它回答了这个问题：“那⼜怎样？”\n\n\fOne of these is salt, one of these is sugar.\n\nTwo Financial Habits: The $5 Daily Coffee vs. The $5 Daily Investment\nWhat seems similar: You spend about $5 a day. It's a small, almost invisible amount from your daily flow of money.\nThe \"small\" difference: The destination of that $5.\nThe enormous difference: If it's a coffee, the money is gone, consumed. If you instead invested that $5 daily (about\n$150/month) into a retirement account averaging 7% annual return, in 40 years you would have over $375,000. That\nsmall, daily choice is the difference between a fleeting pleasure and profound long-term financial security.\n\nWeak Vs Strong Comparison\n\nWeak Comparison 薄弱的⽐较: \"Country X has a monarchy. Country Y has a president. Country X has a national\nreligion. Country Y has separation of church and state.\"\n“X国是君主制。Y国是总统制。X国有国教。Y国政教分离。”\n\n\fStrong Comparison 强⼤的⽐较: \"While Country X's monarchy provides a stable, unifying figurehead, Country Y's\npresidential system allows for more direct political accountability. Furthermore, the presence of a national religion in\nCountry X creates a more culturally homogeneous society, whereas the separation of church and state in Country Y\nfosters greater religious pluralism but also leads to ongoing debates about the role of faith in public life.\"\n“虽然X国的君主制提供了⼀个稳定的、具有统⼀象征的元⾸，但Y国的总统制允许更直接的政治问责。此外，X国国教的存在创造\n了⼀个⽂化上更同质的社会，⽽Y国的政教分离促进了更⼤的宗教多元化，但也引发了关于信仰在公共⽣活中⾓⾊的持续辩论。”\nThe strong comparison doesn't just state facts; it explains the consequence or meaning of those facts.\n\n强⼤的⽐较不仅仅是陈述事实；它解释了这些事实的后果或意义。\n\nPart 2: The Comparative Thesis\n\n⽐较类论⽂陈述 (Bǐjiào lèi lùnwén chénshù)\n\nYour thesis must make a claim about the relationship between the subjects you are comparing. It should highlight the key\nsimilarity or difference and suggest its significance.\n\n你的论⽂陈述必须对你所⽐较的主题之间的关系提出⼀个主张。它应该强调关键的相似性或差异性，并暗⽰其意义。\n\nFormula 公式: While both X and Y are similar in that they both..., X is ultimately more [adjective] because of A and B,\nwhereas Y is more [adjective] because of C and D.\n虽然X和Y在...⽅⾯相似，但由于A和B，X最终更[形容词]，⽽由于C和D，Y更[形容词]。\nExample 例⼦:\n\n\"While both 1984 and Brave New World depict dystopian futures of extreme control, 1984 achieves this through brutal\npunishment and fear, ultimately presenting a more overtly terrifying world, whereas Brave New World argues that a\nmore insidious and lasting control is achieved through pleasure and psychological conditioning.\"\n\n“虽然《1984》和《美丽新世界》都描绘了极端控制的反乌托邦未来，但《1984》通过残酷的惩罚和恐惧来实现这⼀点，最终呈\n现了⼀个更公然可怕的世界，⽽《美丽新世界》则认为，通过快乐和⼼理调节可以实现更阴险、更持久的控制。”\n\nLesson 9.2: Choosing Your Structure\n第⼆课：选择你的结构 (Xuǎnzé nǐ de jiégòu)\n\nYou have two main choices for how to structure the body of your essay. The one you choose depends on what you want to\nEmphasise.\n如何构建⽂章主体，你有两个主要选择。你的选择取决于你想强调什么。\n\nPart 1: The Block Method (Subject-by-Subject)\n块状法（逐主题）(Kuàizhuàng fǎ Zhú zhǔtí))\n\nflowchart TD\nA[Introduction with Thesis]\n-->\nB[Body Paragraphs 1-2: All about Subject A -- Point 1 -- Point 2 -- Point 3]\n-->\nC[Body Paragraphs 3-4: All about Subject B -- Point 1 -- Point 2 -- Point 3]\n-->\nD[Conclusion]\nB -.-> C\n\nHow it works 如何运作: You discuss all of your points about Subject A first. Then, you discuss all of the same points\n\nabout Subject B.\n\n\f你先讨论关于主题A的所有论点。然后，你讨论关于主题B的所有相同论点。\n\nBest for 最适合: Shorter, simpler comparisons where the points of comparison are straightforward and easy for the\nreader to remember.\n更短、更简单的⽐较，其⽐较点直接，读者容易记住。\n\nRisk ⻛险: Can sound like two separate reports if you don't use strong transition sentences to connect the two halves.\nThe comparison might get lost.\n\n如果你不使⽤强有⼒的过渡句来连接两部分，可能会听起来像两个独⽴的报告。⽐较性可能会丢失。\n\nPart 2: The Point-by-Point Method\n逐点法 (Zhúdiǎn fǎ)\n\nflowchart TD\nA[Introduction with Thesis]\n-->\nB[Body Paragraph 1: Point 1 -- Subject A -- Subject B]\n-->\nC[Body Paragraph 2: Point 2 -- Subject A -- Subject B]\n-->\nD[Body Paragraph 3: Point 3 -- Subject A -- Subject B]\n-->\nE[Conclusion]\n\nHow it works 如何运作: You organize your essay by points of comparison. Each body paragraph discusses one point of\ncomparison, examining both Subject A and Subject B within that paragraph.\n你按⽐较点来组织你的⽂章。每个主体段落讨论⼀个⽐较点，在该段落内审视主题A和主题B。\nBest for 最适合: Longer, more complex essays. It creates a tighter, more integrated argument because the comparison\nis happening in every paragraph.\n更⻓、更复杂的⽂章。它创造了⼀个更严密、更综合的论证，因为⽐较发⽣在每⼀个段落中。\n\nRisk ⻛险: Can feel repetitive if you don't vary your language. You must use strong transition words to show contrast\nand similarity.\n如果你的语⾔缺乏变化，可能会感觉重复。你必须使⽤强有⼒的过渡词来显⽰对⽐和相似性。\n\nRecommendation 建议: For university-level writing, the Point-by-Point method is usually preferred because it forces\ndeeper analysis.\n对于⼤学⽔平的写作，逐点法通常是⾸选，因为它迫使进⾏更深⼊的分析。\n\nLesson 9.3: Language of Comparison\n\n第三课：⽐较的语⾔ (Bǐjiào de yǔyán)\n\nTo write a good comparative essay, you need a rich vocabulary to show similarities and differences.\n要写出⼀篇好的⽐较类⽂章，你需要丰富的词汇来显⽰相似性和差异性。\n\nPart 1: Showing Similarity 显⽰相似性 (Xiǎnshì xi ngsì xìng)\nsimilarly 同样地\nlikewise 同样地\nalso 也\n\nboth... and... 两者都...\nin the same way 以同样的⽅式\ncompared to 与...相⽐\n\n\fanalogous to 类似于\n\nX is similar to Y in that... X 在...⽅⾯与 Y 相似\n\nPart 2: Showing Difference 显⽰差异性 (Xiǎnshì ch yì xìng)\nhowever 然⽽\n\non the other hand 另⼀⽅⾯\nin contrast 相⽐之下\nunlike 与...不同\nwhereas ⽽\nwhile 虽然\n\nconversely 相反地\nX differs from Y in that... X 在...⽅⾯与 Y 不同\non the contrary 正相反\n\nPart 3: Showing Result or Significance\n\n显⽰结果或意义 (Xiǎnshì jiéguǒ huò yìyì)\n\ntherefore 因此\nas a result 结果\n\nconsequently 因此\nthis suggests that 这表明\n\nthis implies that 这意味着\n\nthe significance of this is... 其意义在于...\n\nHomework: The Comparison Architect\n作业：⽐较建筑师 (Bǐjiào jiànzhù sh )\n\nTask 1 Structure Analysis\n\nFind a comparative essay online (e.g., a compare/contrast article, a product review comparing two models). Analyze its\nstructure.\n在⽹上找⼀篇⽐较类⽂章（例如，⼀篇⽐较/对⽐⽂章，⼀篇⽐较两种型号的产品评论）。分析其结构。\n\nEssay Topic ⽂章主题: ________________________________________________\nThesis 论⽂陈述: ____________________________________________________\nStructure 结构: Is it Block Method or Point-by-Point? How can you tell?\n\n它是块状法还是逐点法？你是怎么判断的？\n\nLanguage 语⾔: List two words/phrases used to show similarity and two used to show difference.\n列出两个⽤来显⽰相似性和两个⽤来显⽰差异性的词语/短语。\nSimilarity 相似: ____________ , ____________\nDifference 差异: ____________ , ____________\n\nTask 2 Build Your Blueprint\n\nChoose two subjects to compare (e.g., two books, two historical figures, two theories, two phones). Decide which structure\n(Block or Point-by-Point) is best for your essay. Then, complete the outline below.\n\n选择两个主题进⾏⽐较（例如，两本书、两个历史⼈物、两种理论、两部⼿机）。决定哪种结构（块状法或逐点法）最适合你的⽂\n章。然后，完成下⾯的提纲。\n\n\fSubject A _________________________ Subject B _________________________\nMy Thesis 我的论⽂陈述: __________________________________________________\n\nBody Paragraph 1 主体段落 1 Point about _________________________\nSubject A _________________________________________________________\nSubject B _________________________________________________________\nSignificance/So What? 意义/那⼜怎样? ________________________________\nBody Paragraph 2 主体段落 2 Point about _________________________\nSubject A _________________________________________________________\nSubject B _________________________________________________________\nSignificance/So What? 意义/那⼜怎样? ________________________________\nBody Paragraph 3 主体段落 3 Point about _________________________\nSubject A _________________________________________________________\nSubject B _________________________________________________________\nSignificance/So What? 意义/那⼜怎样? ________________________________\nTask 3 Draft a Paragraph\nUsing your outline above, write one full body paragraph. Use at least two comparison words from the Language Box in this\n\nchapter.\n\n使⽤你上⾯的提纲，写⼀个完整的主体段落。使⽤本章语⾔框中的⾄少两个⽐较词汇。\n\nParagraph Draft 段落草稿: ________________________________________________\n\nHomework: The Comparison Architect - Grading Rubric & Example\n\nThis assignment is a Coursework Assessment. It will be graded on a scale of 0 10 points and will contribute to your overall\nCoursework average Weight: 25% of your final grade).\n\nGrading Rubric\nCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nTask 1\nStructure\nAnalysis\n\nThe chosen essay is a clear\nexample of a comparison.\nThesis, structure Block/Pointby-Point), and language are all\ncorrectly and insightfully\nidentified.\n\nThe essay is a comparison.\nThesis, structure, and\nlanguage are correctly\nidentified, but the\nexplanation may be brief.\n\nThe essay may be a weak\nexample. Identification of\nthesis, structure, or language\nis partially incorrect or\nvague.\n\nAnalysis is\nincomplete,\ninaccurate, or\ndemonstrates a lack\nof understanding of\ncomparative\nstructures.\n\nTask 2 Build\nYour Blueprint\n\nOutline is detailed and logically\nfollows the chosen structure\nBlock or Point-by-Point). The\nthesis is sophisticated, arguable,\nand states the significance of\nthe comparison. All points of\ncomparison are relevant and the\n\"So What?\" analysis is strong.\n\nOutline is complete and\nlogical. The thesis is clear\nand indicates a basis for\ncomparison. The \"So\nWhat?\" analysis is present\nbut could be more\ninsightful.\n\nOutline is incomplete or\nillogical. The thesis is weak\n(e.g., just states two things\nwill be compared). The \"So\nWhat?\" analysis is missing or\nsuperficial.\n\nOutline is missing,\nincoherent, or does\nnot reflect a\ncomparative\nstructure.\n\n\fCriteria\n\nExcellent 9 10 pts)\n\nGood 7 8 pts)\n\nSatisfactory 5 6 pts)\n\nNeeds Improvement\n0 4 pts)\n\nTask 3 Draft a\nParagraph\n\nThe paragraph is wellstructured, seamlessly\nintegrates comparison language\n(using 2+ words correctly), and\nprovides specific, balanced\ndetails for both subjects that\ndirectly support the point of\ncomparison.\n\nThe paragraph is structured\ncorrectly and uses the\nrequired comparison\nlanguage. Details are\npresent but could be more\nspecific or the balance\nbetween subjects could be\nimproved.\n\nThe paragraph is attempted\nbut may be unstructured, use\ncomparison words\nincorrectly, or provide\nunbalanced/unclear details.\n\nThe paragraph is\nmissing, does not use\ncomparison language,\nor fails to compare\nthe two subjects.\n\nExample of a Completed Homework Assignment\nTask 1: Structure Analysis\nEssay Topic: A Comparison of Classical and Operant Conditioning in behavioural Psychology.\nThesis: While both classical and operant conditioning are fundamental to behavioural psychology, they are distinct\n\nprocesses, differing primarily in the mechanisms of learning, the role of the learner, and the timing of the reinforcement.\n\nStructure:\nPoint-by-Point. I can tell because the essay is organized by points of comparison (e.g., \"Mechanism of Learning,\"\nRole of the Learner\"). For each point, it discusses classical conditioning first and then immediately discusses\noperant conditioning, before moving on to the next point. This creates a direct, integrated comparison throughout.\n\"\n\nLanguage:\nSimilarity 相似: both, similarly\nDifference 差异: in contrast, however\n\nTask 2: Build Your Blueprint\nSubject A Traditional In-Person Learning\nSubject B Online Learning\nMy Thesis: While online learning offers superior flexibility and access to resources, traditional in-person education\nfosters a more engaging and structured environment that is ultimately more effective for developing critical\ninterpersonal and collaborative skills.\n\nBody Paragraph 1 Point about Social Interaction and Collaboration\nSubject A Provides spontaneous, face-to-face interaction in classrooms, group projects, and clubs, fostering\nteamwork and communication skills naturally.\n\nSubject B Interaction is often mediated through forums and scheduled video calls, which can feel transactional and\nlacks the nuance of in-person communication.\nSignificance/So What? This difference is crucial because the ability to collaborate effectively in real-time, physical\nsettings remains a highly valued skill in most professional workplaces.\n\nBody Paragraph 2 Point about Flexibility and Self-Discipline\nSubject A Follows a fixed, rigid schedule that provides external structure and discipline for students, leaving little room\nfor self-pacing.\n\nSubject B Offers significant flexibility, allowing learners to access materials and complete work at their own pace,\nwhich is ideal for self-motivated individuals.\nSignificance/So What? This highlights a key trade-off: online learning accommodates diverse schedules but requires a\nhigh degree of intrinsic motivation, a skill not all students possess.\nBody Paragraph 3 Point about Access to Resources and Learning Environment"
};

